deck_excerpt: In short, your whole deck is pretty much hand traps some being actual trap cards that u activate from hand.
deck_description:
Okay so what we have here are the infamous Runicks collaborating with the Magical Musketeers, which share a similar mechanic of allowing their respective archtype backrow cards to activate from hand ( Runicks being their quick-spells and Musketeers being their Musket spells and traps).

The main play of this deck is thinning out your opponent's deck with Runick spells while simultaneously controlling their field with the Musketeers, and what makes it even better is that the Musketeers do not require their own cards to activate the monster effects, any spell or trap will do so you can say for example activate a Runick Tip in Magical Musketeer Caspar 's column, not only will you get another runick card from your deck, you can also activate Casper's effect to search for any Magical Musketeer card, whether monster, spell or trap card which most of the time is Magical Musket - Last Stand but it can vary depending on the context of the field. The key cards for the deck are:

Runick Fountain - The main card that makes your runick quick-spells hand traps, you will want to have this card on your field to recycle back your quick-spells and potentially draw into either more quick-spells or Musket spells and traps.

Runick Allure - Although not really necessary, It does fuel up the amount of cards you can banish for quick-spell played, and I mean any quick-play spell card so if your opponent is playing quick-plays, they will be digging their own demise.

Runick Flashing Fire / Runick Destruction / Runick Freezing Curses - Disruptions for your opponent, Flashing fire destroys a Special summoned monster, Destruction destroys a spell/trap card and Freezing curses negates a monster's effect, all Runick quick spells also can special summon their fusion monsters to the extra-monster zone for protection and adding/recovering Runick cards.

Magical Musketeer Starfire - Use her effect to special summon other Musketeers from the deck.

Magical Musketeer Caspar - Use his effect to add a Musket card to your hand, I mostly use him Turn 1 to search out Last Stand and during the next turn, you can use either a runick quick-spell or Magical musket spell or trap then add either Magical Musket - Cross-Domination or Magical Musket - Desperado for an additional disruption.

Magical Musketeer Doc  Normally use his effect late-game when you have a decent amount of Magical Musket spells and Traps in your GY to recycle them back into your hand, Oh and it can recycle any Magical Musket card, it is not only limited to the spells and traps.

Magical Musketeer Max - The catalyst for the Musketeers, given the right circumstances, upon summon you can either add up to 6 Magical Musket spells and traps ( Depending on how many monsters your opponent controls) or special summon up to 5 Magical Musketeer monsters ( Depending on how many spells and traps your opponent controls on the field) all of this from a Link-1 monster. Only downside is it conflicts a bit with the Runick fusions since they have to be summoned in the extra-monster zone, so you don't want to summon him if your hand has more Runick cards than Muskets.

Magical Musket - Cross-Domination / Magical Musket - Desperado / Magical Musket - Last Stand - The musket disruption for your opponents, Cross-Dominations negates and changes the targeted monster's attack to 0, good for getting rid of monsters when they attack, Desperado destroys any face-up card on the field. and Last Stand a counter-trap that negates spells and traps, good for negating cards like Evenly Matched or stopping Fusions/Rituals from being summoned by their spell/trap effects.

Time-Rending Morganite - It syncs pretty well with the deck strategy so why not y'know lol, draw 2 cards every draw phase to dig through your runick and musket cards faster, have 2 normal summons which go very well with the Musketeers, the only downside is monster effects can't activated from the hand but that doesn't matter because we are running spell and trap hand traps.

Hugin the Runick Wings - Searches your field spells and protects your board from getting destroyed by tributing herself which is pretty solid.

Munin the Runick Wings - Searches your Runick allure and gives you free 1000LP during the end phase, also banishes itself to negate cards that target your runick cards, which is also pretty solid.

What I like about this deck more than pure Runicks is that with the Muskets package, the two archetypes combats the other's weakpoints ( For example, Skill Drain shuts down Muskets which you can destroy with a Runick Destruction where as Chaos Hunter or Secret Village of the Spellcasters completely shuts Runicks down but can be easily outed with Magical Musket - Desperado  or Magical Musket - Cross-Domination.

The main weakness I can think of about this deck is that most of the effects 'target' your opponent's cards, so when you come across a monster that is non-targetable, well good luck getting rid of that said monster without targeting it. Maybe siding in a Dark Ruler No More or 2 might make a difference.

But then again for that price you get a recycling hand trap-system not only made of quick spells, but traps and counter traps that you can activate from your hand completely by-passing the standard set and pass to activate your traps. a spell that allows you to draw 2 cards every draw phase on top of drawing up to 3 with Runick Fountain, a Link-1 monster that can either add multiple disruption cards at once, or special summon multiple monsters.

It's honestly frustrating playing against this deck simply because you have no clue what your opponent will activate since everything that will affect your side of the field is activated from their hand, your opponent will most likely surrender out of frustration more than you decking them out.

If you have any suggestions on how it can be improved or cards that can be replaced for more consistency, let me know :)

deck_excerpt: 2023 Masterduel Agents with new Ishizu and Spright cards.
deck_description:
Possible Endboards of the Deck (from weakest to strongest): 

  1. Masterflare Hyperion; Baronne de Fleur; Spright Elf (with Diviner of the Herald in the GY)
  2. Masterflare Hyperion; Baronne De Fleur; Spright Elf (with Diviner of the Herald in the GY) + The Sanctuary in the Sky and Divine Punishment 
  3. Masterflare Hyperion; Baronne De Fleur; Spright Elf (with Diviner of the Herald in the GY) + I:P Masquerena / Herald of the Arc Light + Field Spell and Counter Trap
  4. Masterflare Hyperion; Baronne De Fleur; Spright Elf (with Diviner of the Herald in the GY) + I:P Masqerina + Herald of Arc the Light OR F.A. Dawn Dragster OR The Executor of the Underworld - Pluto + Field Spell and Counter Trap
  5. Masterflare Hyperion; Baronne De Fleur; Spright Elf (with Diviner of the Herald in the GY) + I:P Masqerina + Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying + Field Spell and Counter Trap

Gameplan: 

The main loop is to turbo out Masterflare Hyperion and pitch a The Agent of Creation - Venus with his effect to extend towards the end board. The key is to use several Mystical Shine Ball and depending on the hand and mills there are dozens of ways to do that.

The easiest way to get to Masterflare is to summon Diviner of the Herald. Diviner pitches Trias Hierarchia to tribute itself with it and to then summon Buten (who can later turn a Shine Ball into a tuner). From there you use Protector of The Agents - Moon to search for Majesty Hyperion. From this point the combolines diverge and are heavily dependant on the hand and mills. The goal is to fuel yourself with Mystical Shine Ball to get to Celestial Knightlord Parshath, who can discard a card (ideally a Eva or one of the Millers) and search out the card you need to get to the end board: Ideally you search Divine Punishment BUT it can happen that you need to search for Neptune or even Diviner if the Fieldspell is activated to extend the combo ALSO if you milled the fieldspell you might have to either reshuffle it before you banish Neptune or you can save yourself the Parshath search / search something else. In order to get to Endboard 1 and in general all others aswell, you need to make sure to have Parshath on the field and a reachable Level/Link 2 monster to get to Spright Elf, who will serve as 1. a level 2 tuner revival to go into Baronne with Majesty and 2. interuption on opponents turn by special summoning Diviner, which can lead to a Eva activation that then gives you Herald of Orange Light.

You can get there also the themed way with The Agent of Mystery - Earth if you have either Venus or Neptune in Hand. In that case you go to your Links before you summon Masterflare. Ideally you want to get Diviner into the grave so you can revive her with Elf and get another Synchro 10.

If you have only Venus in hand you have to 1. go into the Links ending on Parshath AND a shineball (or any level/link 2) and 2. have a Diviner in the GY (mills, foolish, discard). From there its just Elf revival and the loop starts over. In this case you most likely have to pitch The Agent of Destruction - Venus to recover the shineballs. Even if you have Diviner in hand; opening with Venus can bait an Ash once you get to Moon, which might be the better way depending on your hand.

Another possible extender is to use Parshath's second effect to Special Summon a fairy from hand, when a fairy leaves the field. The main Target is obviously a Diviner, but can also be the second Majesty, Venus or Destruction Venus. However, that will require some preparations, because in order to Special Summon Diviner you need a Level 1 Fairy in Grave (Eva or Neptune). It can happen that you have to link off a Shine Ball into Link Spider, which will likely stay there for a bit and might mess with your zones a bit.

TLDR (general objectives): Get Diviner into Hand or GY, Turbo out Masterflare, Parshath search for Extender or Countertrap, Elf revives tuner to get another Synchro 10 or Diviner, Restover materials can make I:P or Herald of the Arc Light or other Extras.

Some Comments:

  1. The Main effort in this deck is to manage your monster spaces and the order of your actions. The first is important once you have to use destruction Venus to recover your shineballs and the second is simply due to there being many combolines that potentially allow you to bait many handtraps or ressources and still get to a decent endboard.
  2. With a decent hand you will generally have extra shineballs to make I:P Masquerena and the other Extras, while the minimum endboard is generally Masterflare, Elf and a synchro 10. 
  3. You will notice that the Countertrap search often has to be ditched inorder to get the extenders you need, but usually thats alright, if you can fill your hand with Orangelight or other handtraps.
  4. Considering Runick is heavily played, I tend to go for Chengying instead of Baronne, if i can end on the Counter Trap or a Herald of the Arc Light to have at least 1 omni negate.
  5. The Ishizu cards are basically there to serve as 1. Link fodder if you can special summon them 2. Tribute fodder for Trias for the card draw 3. Filling the GY with Diviner, Majesty, Trias, Eva or Neptune 4. Reshuffling your own Shine Balls to keep extending 5. Get a peak at what the opponent is playing.
  6. Once you have Neptune in Hand your mills become your second hand since you can special summon any Agent you milled.
  7. Sadly the deck bricks every now and then, which is just natural if you play 3 Garnets and the mills can go wrong if you need them to hit well, but it just happens from time to time.
  8. The interaction between Orange Light and Eva will many times give you the starter or extender you need.
  9. Handtraps: The deck can bait many Handtraps - especially with the Ishizu cards (many ash the millers and if they dont the mills can be useful) BUT it can die to an Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring or Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit if your hand doesn't have any follow up. Also Infinite Impermanence will become the bane of your existence UNLESS you have Trias in Hand or Grave, which entirely dodges it. Nibiru, the Primal Being can mess you up BUT with decent set-up you can play through it HOWEVER I don't really see a way to play around it unless you have Orange Light in hand.
  10. Sidedeck of this list: I think the decklist works best for now like this, but you can slot in more maxx c protection or other defensive handtraps HOWEVER i found them to be more bricky than useful overall. Having said that i think that Artifact Lancea can be a decent pick, because it is a fairy that you can pitch with Orange Light and it also shuts off Runick for a turn and can protect you from cards like Spright Smashers. I am considering slotting in an additional Green and Purple Light since Eva can search them, but I didn't test those yet. The Extra deck has a flexspot that you can fill up with what you have, I am testing Artifact Dagda right now, because it is generic which can remove a Link spider or a Nibiru token (and then serve as fodder for the Fairy links or Trias). I personally don't have Underworld Goddess of the Closed World or Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax, but both are very good I:P targets.
A pure cardian build utilizing both Paulownia and Lightflare as the bosses of the deck.

The Infernoble Knight support in DUNE gives the Deck a lot more consistent and powerful plays to do than the wierd Beyond the Pendulum build that is currently going around that people are coping about. Basically, access to Isolde and a Level 5 Synchro is fully combo for the Deck and the plays are pretty simple.

2 Super Quantum Red Layer, 3 Neo Space Connector, and 1 Neo-Spacian Aqua Dolphin to get to Isolde. 2 Immortal Phoenix Gearfried which is a monster negate and it is very easy to Summon. You don't need to search it as you have pretty much enough interruption in your basic combo already, but it is another addition to your end-board if you do happen to draw it. 2 Fire Flint Lady for extension. 3 Infernoble Knight - Oliver, 3 Infernoble Knight - Ogier, and 3 Infernoble Knight - Renaud. Renaud is great for extension, as a Summon off of Isolde, and he can grab back something like Living Fossil for more extension. Oliver is another extender and he can make himself into an equip which is important for this Deck. Ogier has more usage with the new Infernoble support, so having something that can foolish an equip or a FIRE Warrior is great with the new grave effects. Also, he can also make himself an equip which is important as we need at least 1 monster who can make themselves an equip in our starting combo. 1 Infernoble Knight - Ricciardetto. Drawing him is fine as he can basically make Isolde pretty easily depending on your starting hand if you do draw him, but he is also a pretty good Summon off of Isolde as well since he can reborn a FIRE Warrior on summon. 2 Infernoble Knight - Turpin which is a free summon from hand or GY if you control an equip and he can also make himself an equip.

For Spells and Traps, we are playing 3 Heritage of the Chalice and Reinforcement of the Army to search our stuff. 3 Infernoble Arms - Durendal, 2 Infernoble Arms - Almace, 1 Infernoble Arms - Joyeuse, 3 The Infernoble Arms Museum, 1 Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade, and 1 Living Fossil. Durendal searches a Level 5 or lower FIRE Warrior. Almace can equip a different Infernoble Arms from Deck. Joyeuse can add back a FIRE Warrior from GY. Noble Arms Museum searches a Noble Arms card and specials a Noble Knight that is currently an equip.

ED: 1 Baronne de Fluer, 2 Infernoble Knight Emperor Charles, 2 Infernoble Knight Captain Roland, 2 Angelica, Princess of Noble Arms, 1 Accesscode Talker, 1 Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax, 1 Knightmare Unicorn, 1 I:P Masquerena, 2 Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights, and 2 Charlemagne. Ricciardetto does Warrior lock you if you use his effect on Summon, and because you will be using that effect most of the time, you can't really play much outside of Warriors in your Extra Deck. If you aren't Warrior locked, you can make Masquerena with your extra bodies to go into Avramax or Unicorn. Angelica seraches Noble Arms Museum and if she is targeted, she can banish herself until the End Phase to foolish a FIRE Warrior from Deck and summon Captain Roland from your Extra Deck. You can target her with the effects of your Infernobles in GY that allows them to make themselves equips which then gets you to the rest of your combo. Charlemagne basically is another Charles after he equips Charles using his effect on Link Summon. Then, you can Summon your equipped Charles using Noble Arms Museum to have another body on field.

Side Deck can be whatever, but I would recommend board clearers and backrow removal for going second.

Full combo is simple: Make Isolde using whatever and dump Living Fossil to Summon out Ricciardetto. Ricciardetto revives a Level 4 non-Tuner FIRE Warrior which can be put into your GY through something like Ogier or Oliver. Synchro into Angelica and search Noble Arms Museum. Museum pay 1200 to add whatever Noble Arms you need or are missing. An Infernoble in GY targets Angelica to try to equip, and then chain Angelica to banish herself, dump Turpin, and Summon Captain Roland. Then, you can equip an Equip Spell to Roland so that you can Summon back Turpin. Synchro into Charles and equip Roland to him. Link that off into Charlemagne and effect to copy effects and equip Charles. Museum Summon out the equipped Charles. End Phase Angelica returns. If you were not Warrior locked, then you can get more bodies on field to make Masquerena, but it all depends on what you open.

Killer Toys, Sora Perse's deck updated. Trying to bring the best out of his character deck whilst keeping it in the Arc-V era so no Link monsters.

let me know if you've got any ideas to improve it.

Kill your opponent before they even draw a card

COMBO:Activate Prodigy Wakaushi (Can be pretty easily searched w bike), place Monk Big Benkei in pend zone, ss Wakaushi, activate Monk Benkei eff, add Soulpiercer, Normal soulpeircer into Scarecrow, Search Soulpeacemaker, Discard to summon Soulpiercer back w scarecrow, equip soulpiecemaker to scarecrow, tribute to ss Wagon, wagon search Soulbreaker, Wagon and Soulpiercer into Ancient gear Ballista, Ballista search Box (Which searchs General Coral), Soulpiercer searches Bike. Ballista and Wakaushi into Beyond the Pend, Beyond the Pend eff to add Supersight 0 king maxwell, set other Pend scale w general coral, Pend summon Wakaushi and any other superheavy monster w a different level (such as Bike), activate Beyond the pends eff, pop general coral and itself, Activate 0 king Maxwell, activate Wakaushi eff, discard Soulbreak armor to ss Scales from deck, Activate Scales eff SS Soulpiercer from GY, Synchro Scales, Soulpiercer, and Wakaushi into Masurao, Search Soulbreaker with Soulpiercer, King Maxwell Eff to reduce Masurao's def to 0. Banish Soulbreak Armor from gy to burn 4000 points of dmg. Equip Soulbreak to Bike and Link into scarecrow, burn 4000 more.

 

Alternative:

When pendulum summoning, also pend summon Ancient Gear Box, and destroy both the pend monsters with beyond the pend instead. Then shuffle beyond the pend and box into deck to ss Awakening of the possessed: Nefariouser Archfiend. Then use it to ss Soulpiercer. Use bike eff to increase its own, or soulpiercers level, then synchro them both into accell synchro stardust Dragon. Use it to ss bike, then synchro them into barronne. You can use barrones pop at the end of the combo to get a 2nd soul break into the gy, and it still works.

The deck is based on the traptrix structure deck with some other cards low budget to upgrade the deck a little.

This scareclaw deck was built to attempt to make negations and attack for game with tri-heart. This plays around Ash-Blossom but is susceptible to Nibiru, Sphere Mode, and sometimes Bystials. A great board that I usually want to end on is a tri-heart, Baronne, and cloudcastle (Visas Starfrost either being in hand or searched). Rescue Cat allows you to start a combo with your smaller scareclaws, but it's always nice to have at least 2 scareclaws in your starting hand. Side in the super polys if garura isn't accessible using your opponents cards (Nirbiru or Sphere Mode should be in Main). You can add in Lava Golems or Book of Eclipse/Moons to your preference.

Scareclaws >>>>>>>>>> Kashtira :)

This updated Abyss Actor deck is a going first build with decent capacity going 2nd too. The aim is have the field spell ready with a set opening ceremony going into your opponents turn, (alongside as many additional negates as possible). Once your opponent intentionally/inadvertently destroys opening ceremony, you should be able to replenish your hand traps, which will hopefully prevent them winning, so that you can counter attack on turn 3. See the video for a discussion on the build, combos from different starting hands, and discussion on alternative choices & side deck cards.

A dark world build that exchanges consistency for hilarity (and the ability to style on your opponent). Do your usual dark world plays (including hand-loops, if you can), link-climbing into Saryuja as soon as possible. Then, use it to dig for Gale Dogra, which you either normal summon or special summon off of Saryuja. Use Dogra to send Cyberdark Dragon to the GY. Keep using the Danger! brigade and darkworld extenders to dig through your deck and put both Necro Fusion and King of the Swamp into the GY, then link-climb into Knightmare Gryphon to re-set Necro Fusion. Finally, flip over Necro Fusion during your opponent's turn (banishing Cyberdark Dragon + King of the Swamp) to make Cyberdark End Dragon. 

 

Is it good? No, not at all. Is it funny to make CED during your opponent's turn? I would argue yes :D
The deck is really consistent, although, practice is really needed to perform the new combos!

deck_name: A Beginner's Guide to Branded Despia (March 2023)
deck_excerpt: Guide for those who want to learn Branded Despia post-PHHY! Youtube Link inside!
deck_description:
Branded currently is one of the top contenders for today's March 2023 meta. Able to consistently make gigantic fusion beatsticks with board clearing capabilities backed by a solid resource grindgame, Branded is currently the ultimate aggro-beatdown deck. Pushed into meta relevance by Konami because of it's fan favourite status as the "lore" deck of series 12, Branded post Photon Hypernova is a fusion powerhouse!
 
However, this Branded suffers from two major weaknesses: Ash Blossom (On esp. on Branded Fusion) and Nibiru. This version of Branded aims to fix that, by giving the pilot so much gas and plays to work with so that you can play through those devastating handtraps and eventually out-resource your opponent! This "gas" variant of Branded can keep playing, even though Branded Fusion is negated! Some hands allow the pilot to make Dragoon before you use Branded Fusion (so you can negate Ash) and before 5 summons (so you can negate Nibiru).
 
Dragoon is especially strong in today's meta vs. many meta decks since they all target/destroy, meaning this overpowered Deviantart OC is a nigh-invincible instant-win button!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING

 
This core of this deck is composed of the traditional Branded and Despia cards. The only card that isn't standard is Dramaturge. I personally like to use Dramaturge since he can negate Mirrorjade if you're going first, which enables 2 uses of Mirrorjade's effect rather then 1 - thus getting you more dumps in the GY from the ED and more resources. 3 Tragedy is included as a banish target for Allure of Darkness (essentially a +1!).
 
The Bystial package is relatively small, since banishing Light/Dark monsters in the GY isn't very impactful and common in today's metagame. Lubellion is "searcheable" from deck since Branded Fusion dumps him to the GY,and Lubellion can summon itself from the GY by tributing the on-field Albion. Lubellion can activate from deck Branded Lost as extra protection/search power or Branded Beast for a quick effect pop during the main phase.
 
The Frightfur package is included as another piece of "gas" in the deck - maintaining hand advantage since all the pieces search each other and giving access to Polymerization (a powerful boardbreaker with Guardian Chimera).
 
Fusion Deployment functions as a toolbox in this deck, since its 3 targets each serve a distinct function. Albaz can breakboards when summoned, and Albaz + Super Poly cracks most boards nowadays. If your opponent happens to field Dragon monsters, Albaz can contact fuse them away. Cartesia enables fusion summoning as a quick effect. Not only does she give access to Granguinol (which is a foolish burial), she can protect your activating monster effects on the field from targeting negates like Impermanence and Effect Veiler. Finally, Dark Magician can be summoned from deck if you have all the pieces for Dragoon, so that you can have access to his omni-negate to deter Ash/Nibiru before you full combo.
 
50 cards are utilized in this deck rather than around 40ish since every important piece (esp. Branded Fusion) is highly searcheable anyways. 50 cards also reduces the likelihood of drawing garnets and bricks. This "gas" version of Branded is designed to draw alot, search alot, and to play alot to overwhelm any sort of interaction your opponent has whether it is Ash Blossom, Nibiru or on-board interruption.
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
"Gas" Branded is designed to play through your opponent's interruption to create gigantic fusion beatsticks and overwhelm with high ATK and massive resource generation. If given even a second of breathing space, your opponent will find that they are facing down a field full of powerful fusion monsters!
 
Branded Fusion is both a blessing and a curse for this strategy. The whole deck revolves around searching and resolving that card, and if it's negated, your further options are likely limited. Your obvious glaring chokepoint and weakness is Branded Fusion, so it is imperative that you can bait out the Ash Blossom or fusion summon Dragoon before you use the card. It is advisable to use every other card first like Frightfur Patchwork, Branded Opening or Lubellion so that you can bait out your opponent's Ash Blossom. Also, from experience playing the deck, I've discovered that people intentionally hold their Ash Blossom saving it for Branded Fusion - so if you don't have the card, you can bluff having it and just do all your searches/summons from deck!
 
End boards are very hand dependant, but here are the mainline combos:
 
Branded Fusion + Dark Monster + Discard = Mirrorjade (banish), Bystial Lubellion + Beast (pop), Set Branded in Red
  1. Activate Branded Fusion to summon Albion, sending Albaz + Bystial Lubellion from deck.
  2. Fusion summon Lubellion the Searing Dragon by fusing Albaz + Dark Monster with Albion. Ideal dark monsters to banish are Tragedy (search) and Dramaturge (free body on field).
  3. Lubellion (discards for cost) fusion summons Mirrorjade by shuffling back Albaz from banished pile and Lubellion the Searing Dragon on the field.
  4. Summon Bystial Lubellion from the GY by tributing Albion.
  5. Activate Lubellion's card effect to activate from deck Branded Beast. Alternatively, you can activate from deck Branded Lost for further searches/fusion protection.
  6. End phase - set your Branded card of choice from deck. Ideally, you set Branded in Red so you can fusion summon on your opponent's turn. If you already have Branded in Red, you can set Branded Opening for further searches/protection from destruction. 
Branded Fusion + Discard = Red-Eyes Dragoon (Best to use if you suspect your opponent has Nibiru, or you are against a Kashtira player, or if you want to play safe).
  1. Activate Branded Fusion to summon Lubellion the Searing Dragon, sending Albaz + Dark Magician from deck.
  2. Lubellion (discards for cost) fusion summons Dragoon by shuffling back Albaz and Dark Magician from GY to deck.
Cartesia + Light/Dark monster + Either Bystial Saronir/Albion the Shrouded Dragon = Search for any Branded card (Best to use if you're missing a particular Branded card, esp. Branded Fusion!)
  1. Activate Cartesia's effect to fusion summon Granguinol by using Cartesia + Light/Dark monster. If Saronir is in hand, you use Saronir instead.
  2. Granguinol sends to GY from deck Bystial Saronir. (Or Albion the Shrouded Dragon)
  3. Bystial Saronir/Albion the Shrouded Dragon sends to GY Branded Retribution. 
  4. Bystial Saronir/Albion the Shrouded Dragon sends to GY your Branded spell/trap card of choice. 
  5. Banish Branded Retribution from GY to retrieve from GY your Branded spell/trap of choice.
Going first and uninterrupted, your opponent will likely contend with Mirrorjade's banish, a pop with Branded Beast, and a set Branded in Red. Depending on the hand, your opponent may also be dealing with Mercourier's monster negate, Dramaturge's monster negate, Masquerade's -600 burn, and Granguinol can summon Proskenion from the Extra Deck. Red-Eyes Dragoon can also be summoned, a much needed omni-negate that Branded needs. If you're lucky, you also have a facedown Super Polymerization - a devasting turn ending card if used at the right time. Your hand will likely also be sizeable and ready with follow-up for next turn since Cartesia, Alba-Lenatus and Albion generate resources during the end phase.
 
Going second, Branded can slog through interruption, pierce through boards and beat down your opponent's monsters with big beatsticks. Branded is naturally equipped with in-engine ways to play going second. Polymerization fusing into Guardian Chimera is a nigh-unstoppable juggernaut since it's effect is often chainblocked with the fusion material used for it's fusion summon and it is untargetable since you used Polymerization. If Branded Opening is on the field, it also can't be destroyed! Super Polymerization can fuse away most boards in today's meta, especially with Garura, only needing 2 monsters with the same type and attribute. Muddy Mudragon can fuse away your Kashtira opponent's Diablosis + Ariseheart as well! Against the rare Dragon deck, Albaz can contact fuse their problematic Dragons away like Borrload Savage Dragon and Crystal Wing into Alba-Lenatus. Alot of interruption these days involve flipping monsters facedown, destroying and banishing (For example, Traptrix, Labrynth, Ninja and Kashtira does this alot) - Branded is very comfortable with that since they can fuse face down monsters and shuffle back banished monsters with Lubellion to fusion summon.

GENERAL TIPS

  • Try to bait out Ash Blossom by your many searches/summons from deck before you use Branded Fusion. If you don't have Branded Fusion, your opponent will likely hold Ash Blossom in their hand waiting for it, so you can bluff having the card to search/summon all you want!
  • Branded lacks in-engine ways to remove backrow, except with Guardian Chimera. Backrow floodgates absolutely slaughter Branded, so if you're against an opponent using something like Rivalry of Warlords, it probably is time to proceed to next game! Be sure to side in backrow hate in those match-ups!
  •  Guardian Chimera is the best card to crack open established boards. With it's untargetability, beefy 3300ATK/DEF statline and non-targeting destruction, most boards fall to this offensive juggernaut. If your opponent negates Polymerization/Branded in Red to prevent Chimera from coming out, they have wasted a precious interaction paving the way for you to use Branded Fusion.
  • Try to have Cartesia on board before you summon monsters on the field with important effects. Cartesia's quick effect fusion summon allows you to dodge common targeting negates like Impermanence and Effect Veiler.
  • The best cards to side out is the Bystial package, especially when the match-up doesn't call for them (for ex. Traptrix/Kashtira don't have light/dark for Bystials to banish). Super Polymerization can also be sided out in certain matchups where your Super Poly targets don't work out.
  • If Branded Lost is active, Fusion effect's activation cannot be negated. Cards that negate the activation like Baronne De Fleur, Borreload Savage Dragon and even Solemn Judgment cannot negate your Branded Fusion! Branded Lost is a perfect way to bait a negate or to guarantee your Fusion effect when you're against these threats.
  • In certain common meta match-ups, Dragoon is untouchable by your opponent. If you can, try to summon Dragoon before you use key cards like Branded Fusion to guarantee it's resolution. Also, if you want to play around Nibiru, summon Dragoon before 5 summons. Dragoon is also your go-to answer when facing down Kashtira Ariseheart's macro-cosmos like floodgate and targeting banish.
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

CONCLUDING COMMENTARY

The culmination of the "Abyss" storyline also coincides with the strongest form that Branded has ever fielded. All the support for Branded over the last couple years creates a consistent, strong and resilient deck. Naturally playing through established boards while having a robust grind game is only something that few decks can boast. To see for youself how this deck performs vs. meta, I highly recommend you see the deck in action by watching the Youtube video linked below!
 
Our hero, Albaz has faced his enemies to ultimately triumph through trials and adversity. Now, you can do the same thing as you pilot Branded!

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Ritual Summon the Legendary Swordsman and wipe out your opponent's board.
deck_description:
- DECK STATS

  • ATTACK: 9/10
  • DEFENSE: 3/10
  • VERSATILITY: 4/10
  • CONSISTENCY: 5/10
  • DIFFICULTY: 3/5
  • OVERALL: 5.25/10
  • PREFERENCE: SECOND
  • TYPE: BOARD BREAKER
  • TIER: FUN / CASUAL

Very satisfying and fun when it works.

 

- HOW TO

A very simple deck to use, but difficult to operate. Its main objective is to clear the opponent's field, either by Spell Cards or using Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman. However, due to the lack of protection, it is difficult to keep this consistent for many turns, so try to finish as quickly as possible.

Summon monsters like Accesscode Talker and Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder to help you with the board wipe. And if you are in need of protection, your only way is with Black Luster Soldier - Soldier of Chaos summoned with a Level 7+ Monster or Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax summoned using I:P Masquerena.

Your priority is to bring Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman to the field, keep this in mind. After all, it is your Boss Monster. But sometimes we need to improvise, so don't be afraid to use it as material for Black Luster Soldier - Soldier of Chaos. Besides, Super Soldier Synthesis can summon it back from the GY.

- NOTES AND TIPS

  • Bring forth Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman and wipe out your opponent's board.
  • If everything goes wrong, Summon Accesscode Talker.
  • Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax is also your friend if everything goes wrong.
  • This deck has quick access to Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder.
  • Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir and Scareclaw Tri-Heart will buy you time. Always Summon them with priority if you go first.
  • The Battle Phase is where this deck excels, always keep that in mind. Your goal will always be to summon Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman and go into the Battle Phase.
  • Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade can be used to banish Beginning Knight and Evening Twilight Knight.
  • Always try to use one of the Normal Monsters as material for the Ritual Summon.
  • Keep in mind that this deck is quite limited. Keep an eye on your resources so you don't spend it all in a single turn. However, if the opportunity arises, don't hesitate to finish the duel also in a single turn.
  • Envoy of Chaos may be useless sometimes, but it can help your Black Luster Monsters in some battles. Also, its effect of recovering from the GY can be combined with the Knights' banish effects.

- KEY CARDS

  • Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman - Your main Boss Monster. Having it in your opening hand is one of your win conditions, especially going second. Its effect of being able to add any Ritual Spell is very versatile and can define your entire turn.
  • Gateway to Chaos - One of the best cards in your deck. Its first effect allows you to easily add Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman to your hand. Also, when this card is combined with Rescue Rabbit, it is not difficult to activate the second effect on the same turn.
  • Rescue Rabbit - Your 1-card combo. It can be used to easily bring Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights to the field. or in other situations, it can be used to get the materials needed for the ritual. furthermore, the possibilities are so many with this card, from making moves with Link Summoning or even moves with Xyz Monsters, like summoning Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir for stalling or summoning the Utopias and going into 4-Materials Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder.
  • Unexpected Dai - Basic combo extender. Can be used to summon Noble Knight Artorigus.
  • Raigeki, Lightning Storm and Harpie's Feather Duster - Basic board breakers. If you draw both Raigeki and Lightning Storm, use Storm to destroy the Spell/Trap Cards.
  • Super Soldier Synthesis - The best ritual card of the deck. It can be used to either get a Normal Monster as material or use both Knights and create a Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman with the Knights' effects.
  • Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax, Accesscode Talker and Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder - The monsters that will guarantee your victory if things are not looking good. Sometimes your opponent doesn't have a way to out your Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax summoned with I:P Masquerena as material.
  • Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir and Scareclaw Tri-Heart - Most of the time, they are the monsters that will guarantee your survival if you go first.

- BASIC COMBO #1 - Going Second

  1. Normal Summon Rescue Rabbit and activate its effect.
  2. Special Summon 2 x Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster.
  3. Special Summon Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights using the two Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster as materials.
  4. Add either Noble Knight Artorigus or Envoy of Chaos using Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights' first effect.
  5. Activate Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights' second effect and send Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade to the GY. Special Summon Super Soldier Soul.
  6. Either Special Summon Linkuriboh using Super Soldier Soul as material or Special Summon a Link Monster using both Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights and Super Soldier Soul.
  7. Activate Super Soldier Soul's effect in the GY.
  8. Add either Evening Twilight Knight or Beginning Knight to your hand.

- BASIC COMBO #2 - Going First

  1. Normal Summon Rescue Rabbit and activate its effect.
  2. Special Summon 2 x Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster.
  3. Special Summon Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir using the two Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster as materials.

- BASIC COMBO #3 - Going First or Second

  1. Activate Unexpected Dai and Special Summon Noble Knight Artorigus.
  2. Normal Summon Rescue Rabbit and activate its effect.
  3. Special Summon 2 x Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster.
  4. Special Summon Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights using the two Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster as materials.
  5. Add Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning using Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights' first effect.
  6. Activate Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights' second effect and send Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade to the GY. Special Summon Super Soldier Soul.
  7. Special Summon I:P Masquerena using Super Soldier Soul and Noble Knight Artorigus.
  8. Special Summon Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax using Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights and I:P Masquerena.

- BASIC COMBO #4 - Going Second

  1. Activate Gateway to Chaos and add Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman to your hand.
  2. Normal Summon Rescue Rabbit and activate its effect.
  3. Special Summon 2 x Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster and Link Summon Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights using them as materials.
  4. Add Envoy of Chaos with Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights' first effect.
  5. Activate Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights' second effect and send either Living Fossil or Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade.
  6. Special Summon Super Soldier Soul.
  7. Link Summon Knightmare Unicorn using Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights and Super Soldier Soul and activate its effect if possible.
  8. Activate Super Soldier Soul's GY effect. Add either Beginning Knight or Evening Twilight Knight to your hand.
  9. Activate Gateway to Chaos' second effect and add Super Soldier Synthesis to your hand.
  10. Special Summon Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman using Super Soldier Synthesis.

Note: You can either summon Legendary Swordsman using the two Knights or using Envoy of Chaos + Noble Knight Artorigus.

- ADVANCED COMBO

  1. Normal Summon Rescue Rabbit and activate its effect.
  2. Special Summon 2 x Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster.
  3. Special Summon Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights using the two Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster as materials.
  4. Add Noble Knight Artorigus using Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights' first effect.
  5. Activate Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights' second effect and send Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade to the GY. Special Summon Super Soldier Soul.
  6. Either Special Summon Linkuriboh using Super Soldier Soul as material or Special Summon a Link Monster using both Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights and Super Soldier Soul.
  7. Activate Super Soldier Soul's effect in the GY.
  8. Add Beginning Knight to your hand.
  9. Activate Super Soldier Synthesis and Special Summon Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman using Evening Twilight Knight (Deck) and Beginning Knight (Hand),
  10. Special Summon Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning banishing Evening Twilight and Beginning.
  11. Activate their effects and add another Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman and Super Soldier Ritual.
  12. Special Summon your second Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman using Noble Knight Artorigus and Beginning Knight.

Note: Your opening hand must be Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning, Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman, Super Soldier Synthesis, Beginning Knight and Rescue Rabbit.

deck_excerpt: Level 5/7 and occasionally 8 Synchros alongside Triamid Field Spell loop to Triamid Sphinx.
deck_description:
This deck is more Triamid than Adamancipator. Only play this deck if you enjoy Triamid and would like to use them.

Use Ancient Fairy Dragon to give you access to Triamid Hunter through Triamid Cruiser if you draw Adamancipator Analyzer or Doki Doki.

Garden Rose Flora has synergy with Triamid Field spells, triggering their effects when sent to the graveyard. This can search with Triamid Cruiser when you otherwise cannot get it into the graveyard. You can then go into a Level 7 Synchro with the Token summoned by Flora.

Ideally, your Level 5 Synchro will be Naturia Beast, if you hard drew into your Field Spells and do not need to use Garden Rose Flora.

Triamid Pulse is an extremely valuable trap. Use it to destroy your opponents face-up cards, as well as special summon needed Adamancipator or Triamid monsters from the Graveyard.

prog

Goal is to summon Merrymaker, then Champion Sargas on top so it has 3+ materials, use Tally-ho! to summon 3 monsters and do what you will from there since its pretty versatile at that point.

- Spright Smashers is a good way to add a second body on the field (you can banish spells from the GY too!) to make a Link-2 or Merrymaker without the field's effect, and since you can summon Champion Sargas on top of it, you can summon Exblowrer for an additional Xyz body.
- Use Brothers' or Kitt's effects to special summon once, then summon another monster to make Qliphort Genius. At this point you can search Tally-Ho! with Champion Sargas and Regulus with Qliphort Genius afterwards.
- Try to always summon Kitt and then use Branded in High Spirits to send Sprind to the GY, end with any kind of Xyz with material on the field so that in the end phase Sargas can be special summoned from your deck, giving you a face-up removal + Champion Sargas additional removal immediately after.
- If you didn't use your Normal summon until the end, you can make sure Sargas is in the graveyard and Brothers in hand, and instead use two monsters to make IP Masquerena. Then on your opponent's turn you can summon Unicorn, discard Brothers to remove a card, then summon Sargas to have his removal on the field too.
- On the other hand, if you didn't use your Normal summon, you can add Cartesia to your hand with High Spirits, normal summon her, then use either a spare Kitt on the field or whatever Extra Deck monster is of no use to you anymore to summon either Rindbrumm or Mirrorjade. Rindbrumm allows for an additional negate and Albaz extender. If it leaves the field you can either bring it or Albaz right back, Albaz could use its effect to fuse with an opponent's monster and make either Lubellion or Mirrorjade.
- If you summoned Merrymaker without the field you can revive it with Tally-Ho! Then you can search Interluder with Branga to have a continuous omni-negate.
- Ash/DRNM/Called By can be replaced with any staples you want. If you want to make even more space for them you can also take out Pedor and 1 Branga. I'd say 1 Sargas but you REALLY want 1 in the Deck always, and it sucks if he's your dedicated discard target, plus you always want more Springans names available. If you want even more space you can take out Albaz and Cartesia (and if you do then also Lubellion, Mirrorjade and Rindbrumm).

You can very effortlessly end with a board of 2 or 3 removals and 1 or 2 omni-negates, plus a little bit extra disruption from either Number 38, Redoer or Dweller or whatever generic Rank 4 or 8 you prefer like Bagooska, Dingirsu, or even bring a UDF pack instead of Draglubion. 
It's fun, easy to play and versatile enough to fit different strategies. This is just what I personally have available right now, but yeah. Tally-ho, baby!

deck_excerpt: Pierce through your enemy's defenses using the galloping champion of the skies.
deck_description:
- DECK STATS

  • ATTACK: 10/10
  • DEFENSE: 1/10
  • VERSATILITY: 5/10
  • CONSISTENCY: 6/10
  • DIFFICULTY: 2/5
  • OVERALL: 5.5/10
  • PREFERENCE: SECOND
  • TYPE: ONE TURN KILL
  • TIER: FUN / CASUAL

End it on Turn 2 or it's over for you.

- HOW TO

There is not much to be said. Summon Curse of Dragon, the Magical Knight Dragon, then summon Sky Galloping Gaia the Dragon Champion or, Gaia the Magical Knight of Dragons if you already have Spiral Spear Strike in your hand. If the duel goes on even after you attack, you can summon Soldier Gaia the Fierce Knight and hope that it will finish the job.

Since this is a pure version of the deck, there is really not much to be done. It is a deck designed to finish the job on Turn 2. But if you go first, I recommend that you prioritize summoning Gaia the Magical Knight of Dragons or, if the opportunity arises, Black Luster Soldier - Soldier of Chaos.

- NOTES AND TIPS

  • Eliminate any threat to the OTK before starting your combo.
  • Always use Terraforming before Set Rotation.
  • Always use Gateway to Chaos before Galloping Gaia.
  • Spell / Trap cards are a bigger threat to this deck than monsters, remember this always.
  • Link Monsters are your worst nightmare. This deck takes great advantage of weak defenses, and since links can't stay in defense position they become great threats to the OTK.
  • Speaking of nightmares... Cards like Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax and Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon can ruin this deck completely, so I recommend keeping an eye on these monsters.
  • Black Luster Soldier - Soldier of Chaos is your only line of defense in this deck, or with a lot of luck Millennium-Eyes Restrict can also help you live another turn.
  • Curse of Dragon, the Cursed Dragon can be Special Summoned from your GY using Gaia the Magical Knight. That said, you can freely use it for Forbidden Droplet.
  • Only use Curse of Dragon, the Magical Knight Dragon as fusion material in the outermost cases. It may only have 2000 attack, but that can make a huge difference.
  • This deck does not have 1-card combos. The only thing preventing it from being a completely brick deck is the fact that there are several searches.

- KEY CARDS

  • Sky Galloping Gaia the Dragon Champion and Gaia the Magical Knight of Dragons - The bosses of the deck. It will be one of them that will perform the OTK. Most of the time will be Sky Galloping Gaia the Dragon Champion, because of its effect of adding Spiral Spear Strike. But don't underestimate Gaia the Magical Knight of Dragons in the least, as its ATK gain effect can be brutal and enough for many cases.
  • Galloping Gaia and Gateway to Chaos - Both are a 2-card combo. Always activate Gateway to Chaos first and then, activate and use the effect of Galloping Gaia.
  • Gaia the Magical Knight and Curse of Dragon, the Cursed Dragon - Again, a 2-card combo. Gaia the Magical Knight can be Normal Summoned without tribute, and it can also Special Summon Curse of Dragon, the Cursed Dragon. If you already have Spiral Fusion on your hand, you can use the effect of Curse of Dragon, the Cursed Dragon to add something else.
  • Artillery Catapult Turtle - One of the best cards in the deck. Can be used to get the piece needed to complete the combo.
  • Soldier Gaia the Fierce Knight - Its main function in the deck is to help the OTK. Especially if the opponent has little LP left. It will be very rare that you end up using its search effect. Its summoning effect is a (Quick Effect) which means that you can summon it still in the Battle Phase. That said, tribute Curse of Dragon, the Magical Knight Dragon to Special Summon it.
  • Instant Fusion - It will be used mainly to summon Millennium-Eyes Restrict or Invoked Raidjin. In the worst situation, if you need material urgently, summon Alligator's Sword Dragon. That is the only function of Alligator's Sword Dragon by the way, to be used as a material. Feel free to swap it with anything else if you want.
  • Terraforming and Set Rotation - Always use Terraforming first to add Gateway to Chaos and use it to add Gaia the Magical Knight, then activate Set Rotation and activate Galloping Gaia on your side of the field.
  • Curse of Dragon, the Magical Knight Dragon - One of the best monsters in the deck. It will be the one that allows the OTK to happen. Its effect allows you to recover Spiral Fusion from the GY. Avoid using it as fusion material.
  • Black Luster Soldier - Soldier of Chaos - Your only line of defense. Since most of the monsters in the deck are Level 7 or higher, it will always have its protection effect on.

- BASIC COMBO #1 - Going Second

  1. Activate Galloping Gaia.
  2. Use its effect and reveal Curse of Dragon, the Cursed Dragon (or Gaia the Magical Knight).
  3. Add to your hand Gaia the Magical Knight (or Curse of Dragon, the Cursed Dragon).
  4. Normal Summon Gaia the Magical Knight. Use its effect and Special Summon Curse of Dragon, the Cursed Dragon.
  5. Using Curse of Dragon, the Cursed Dragon's effect, add Spiral Fusion.
  6. Fusion Summon Curse of Dragon, the Magical Knight Dragon using Spiral Fusion.
  7. Use Curse of Dragon, the Magical Knight Dragon's effect and add Spiral Fusion from your GY to your hand.
  8. Fusion Summon Sky Galloping Gaia the Dragon Champion using Spiral Fusion and banishing the materials from the GY. Use its effect and add Spiral Spear Strike.

Note: If you have 1 additional Gaia monster in your hand, don't use the Gaia the Magical Knight on the field as fusion material. It can be used later to attack or as material for Black Luster Soldier - Soldier of Chaos.

 - BASIC COMBO #2 - Going First

  1. Activate Galloping Gaia.
  2. Use its effect and reveal Curse of Dragon, the Cursed Dragon (or Gaia the Magical Knight).
  3. Add to your hand Gaia the Magical Knight (or Curse of Dragon, the Cursed Dragon).
  4. Normal Summon Gaia the Magical Knight. Use its effect and Special Summon Curse of Dragon, the Cursed Dragon.
  5. Using Curse of Dragon, the Cursed Dragon's effect, add Spiral Fusion.
  6. Fusion Summon Curse of Dragon, the Magical Knight Dragon using Spiral Fusion.
  7. Use Curse of Dragon, the Magical Knight Dragon's effect and add Spiral Fusion from your GY to your hand.
  8. Fusion Summon Gaia the Magical Knight of Dragons using Spiral Fusion and banishing the materials from the GY.

- BASIC COMBO #3 - Going Second

  1. Normal Summon Artillery Catapult Turtle. Use its effect to Special Summon Curse of Dragon, the Cursed Dragon (or Gaia the Magical Knight, only if Curse of Dragon, the Cursed Dragon is already in your hand).
  2. Follow Basic Combo #1 from step 4.

- BASIC COMBO #4 - Going First or Second

  1. Activate Gateway to Chaos. Use its effect to add Gaia the Magical Knight.
  2. Follow Basic Combo #3 from step 1.

- BASIC COMBO #5 - Going First or Second

  1. Activate Gateway to Chaos. Add Gaia the Magical Knight.
  2. Activate Galloping Gaia and follow Basic Combo #1 from step 1.

deck_excerpt: We do a little bit of trolling
deck_description:
Nemurelia doesn't have a Normal Summon, so why not Normal Therizia and set Dinomorphia Frenzy?

3 Dinomorphia Therizia. You can Normal Summon this card to directly set Dinomorphia Frenzy or Dinomorphia Intact (whichever you are missing or need) and we are playing 3 copies just to have material to fusion with Frenzy. 3 Dreaming Nemurelia. It is better to draw her than to place her directly into your Extra Deck. She places herself in the Extra Deck and places a Nemurelia Continuous Spell directly from her Deck. On the crackback, she can summon herself from the ED and banish a card from your opponent's field or GY face-down for every 3 face-down of your banished cards and recycles some of them if you have no other cards in your ED besides her. Most of your Nemurelia cards do enough banishing and we are playing Pots for more banishing, but your techs for banishing is up to your really. 3 Nemurelia Realiser, the Dreamaterializer Sleeping Princess. This card Summons itself by placing one of your monsters on the bottom of the Deck and it either books a monster or places Nemurelia in your Extra Deck from your Deck. It is better to summon this off of the Trap for interruption, but it can set up Nemurelia which is definitely something. It will get a lot better once we get a card for Nemurelia that gets her from ED to hand. 2 Nemurelia's Dreameater - Reveil. It's a free Summon by banishing 3 ED cards and you don't need Nemurelia. It can also send a Level 10 Beast from hand or field other than it to GY to set a Nemurelia Trap. The one we have right now is okay, but it might get better with more releases. 2 Nemurelia's Dream Defender - Couette. This is a free Summon if you have a face-up Pendulum in your ED and it negates Targeting effects. 1 Nemurelia's Dream Defender - Oreiller. This card has the same Summoning Condition as Couette, but it is an attacker. You are only playing 1 as something to send for Reveil after you search with Tower.

3 Pot of Prosperity for searching and banishing. 3 Fossil Dig to search Therizia. 2 Triple Tactics Talent since you oftentimes need to recoup the loss after facing something like being Ashed and it can steal a monster for a free monster for Realiser. 1 Called by the Grave. 3 Sweet Dreams, Nemurelia which searches a Nemurelia monster and protects against effects when a Nemurelia monster is normal or Specialed if you already have Nemurelia. It can also put Nemurelia back once you Summon her. 1 The Sleeping Beauty Tower of Nemurelia which banishes 2 ED cards to search 2 Level 10 Beast monsters w/ different names and it protects your Nemurelia monsters from destruction by banishing an ED card. 3 Infinite Impermanence. 3 Dinomorphia Frenzy which Fusions using material from Deck and Extra Deck. This gets you to Kentregina and then to Rexterm for what is basically Skill Drain. 2 Dinomorphia Intact which is a monster negate if you control a Dinomorphia monster. It is just something extra if you already drew Frenzy and need something to search with Therizia. 2 Nemurelia Louve which Summons a Nemurelia monster or a Level 10 Beast from Deck most importantly.

ED: 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder, 2 Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe, 1 Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora, 2 Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max. 3 Dinomorphia Rexterm which is just Skill Drain, 3 Dinomorphia Kentregina which copies a Dinomorphia Trap from GY, and 3 Dinomorphia Stealthbergia which is just here for material for Frenzy. 

Side Deck, you just want good stuff for going second. Maybe some stuff for stealing monsters to have free material for Realiser.

deck_excerpt: Runick Kaiju Plunder Patroll / YCS Lima Top 8
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Deck

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Michel Verissimo

Tournament: YCS Lima - March 12th 2023

Placement: Top 8

The amount of combos that are possible off the first card with this deck are insane.

Primary engine involves getting out a field of level 2 monsters (easily attainable with Spright Starter and the Spright special summon effects), link summon first in to I:P Masquerena. Then XYZ summon into Gigantic Spright (or link summon into Dharc or Hiita first then into GS if you're ready to sacrifice the card advantage to double its attack.) Use GS effect to special summon Ipiria to draw another card (or Capshell if you normal summoned Ipiria to start the combo). Link summon using I:P and that card into Spright Elf. Now the enginge gets interesting because, as long as your opponent controls a monster you can use Spright Elf to continuously special summon I:P from the graveyard and, during your opponents turn, use I:P to go into your higher level Links, such as Knightmare Unicorn to send a your opponent's monster right back to the deck as soon as they summon it during their Turn. Other options are I:P into borrelsword to close the game out or Appollousa if the gamestate will continue for a few more turns and you'll need some negate power. And with I:P's ability, each of these will have destruction protection. If youre not able to go into Link 3 or 4, Lib the World Key Blademaster is another good support option, if you've already used World Legacy Succession, who can then set another of those.

There are other options for additional support, such as Thunderdragon Colossus. Since Sprights are Thunder type, Thunder Dragonmatrix can be easily discarded to up the attack of one, then tribute it into Colossus, and still be able to pull of the majority of the rest of the Spright engine.

If you are able to get Duel Academy in the Field Spell Zone, this combo is all the more effective, as it can burn for 1000 damage once per turn when you use a spell card (when you have a Thunder monster on the field, which you almost always will). Even better, it can raise one of your monsters' attack by 1000 if a monster effect is activated while you have a fiend or Fairy (which you will if you have any of the Knightmare link monsters or Appollousa on the field or if you summon Capshell by Gigantic Spright's effect).

 

Even without all this combo, it is very possible to OTK your opponent with the main deck Spright Cards, if your opponent did not get out a sufficient opening board, as you can flood the field with Levell 2s and use Spright Gamma Burst to raise their attack by 1400 each.

 

Really fun deck, very high win rate.

Heal and spend your life points flippantly.  Play the long game, gradually accumulating a board state that makes you untouchable.  Gain life on your opponent's turns to trigger various effects that let you bounce, negate, change battle positions, destroy, banish from graveyards, draw and search for more plants.  Gain life every turn in the round.  Use every bit of synergy you can to gain card advantage.  Shift between Sylvans, Rikkas, Aromas, and various other plants and use cards like recycle and the pots and jars to consistently replenish your deck.  Protect your major players with Aromaseraphy Jasmine.  Use your life points as a sword and a shield with cards like Child's Play, Wall of Revealing Light, Ultimate Offering, Unending Nightmare, Dried Winds, Michael the Arch-Lightsworn and Soul Charge, and finish them off with a massive swing from Ancient Sacred Wyvern.

This is extremely toxic and rude to play. I used this in duelist cup event and got 10 wins in a row against mostly Spright Runick Stun players. If your opponent uses Maxx C you have a very high chance of winning by deck out. The nemeses monsters can be special summoned from your hand if you have a banished monster. This allows you to search protos or eschatos. Using mills you find out what deck your opponent is playing then summon reproductus to make any attribute or monster type for lingering floodgate of eschatos or protos. Even worse if you summonend reproductus using IP Masquerena. This makes it indestructable by card effects including your eschatos/protos giving you infinite potential lingering floodgating. You can use chaos creator to shuffle back your necroface from banish zone. The chances of starting with a bricked hand is surprisingly low considering the lack of draw power. The major weakness to this deck is Artifact Scythe or similar special summon floodgates as well as Droll & Lock Bird. One potential change I would consider is swapping in left arm offering to search grass or card destruction to increase FTK chances.

deck_excerpt: Power comes at a price.  It's a burden.  It demands sacrifice.
deck_description:
The full P.U.N.K. archetype and a littany of Psychic monsters.  I wanted to heavily emphasize combos and lifegain with this one, and play-tested a fair number of times to tune it to my liking.  I'm personally running two custom cards I made (link below) in place of Overmind Archfiend and Supernatural Regeneration, keeping those two to the side in case someone wants to play with official cards only.  Originally I was trying out a Dark/Wind/Psychic Teledad deck with Ezmerin as the Deck Master, but it didn't work out the way I wanted, as what I really wanted was as pure Psychic deck, and I really liked the structure that the P.U.N.K.s could offer.

The game-plan with this deck is to be tricky and use your life and monsters as resources to rush through combos.  One of the main plays is getting out Noh-P.U.N.K. Ze Amin as fast as possible to search for Noh-P.U.N.K. Foxy Tune or another P.U.N.K. to start accumulating card advantage.  Once you've got a decent board of punks out you can start filling out the rest of the board with various support Psychics.  Sometimes it's better to hold off on using various effects, like Ukiyoei-P.U.N.K. Amazing Dragon's on-summoned effect, so you can bring a monster back immediately for more power or combos.  D.D. Seeker is really useful if you have Soul Absorption out, netting you 1000 LP a round (4 players), and he can protect anything you control from battle, targeting and destruction as a quick effect, as well as prevent them (or himself) from being banished by Emergency Teleport at the end of the turn.  I opted not to run a Psy-Frame package in this deck as you really want to maintain a board presence, but I did put in the synchros, who can help with control, lifegain off of Soul Absorption, and returning your banished cards to the GY.  Psychic End Punisher is one of my favorites.  Whether you have more or less LP than an opponent, he gains attack equal to the difference.  He alone can end games with his permanent ATK buff every turn, but it gets even worse if you chain Psychic Fervor to his battle phase effect activation - taking 3500 to double his ATK, and if you're already lower than your opponent, he'll gain even more.  He and some of the monsters that gain life when they destroy monsters by battle work really well with Psychic Snail, who allows a Psychic monster to attack twice for 800 LP.  Aromage Cananga helps by suppressing your opponent's stats and getting troublesome backrow cards out of the way. It's okay if some of your dudes get destroyed, as you can punish them with Psi-Curse and Telepathic Power, and you've got TONS of ways to recycle all of your cards.  Ultimate Offering helps get out monsters quickly at a negligble cost to a lifegain deck, and Future Glow can make your board incredibly oppressive if you banish a level 7-11 Psychic monster from your GY.  The P.U.N.K. spells and traps are essential for locking in a win.  The field spell let's you summon an extra P.U.N.K. every turn, and you get up to 2 free draws per turn if you pay LP to activate a Psychic monster's effect.  Gagaku-P.U.N.K. Wild Picking and Number 26: Spaceway Octobypass will have your opponent's thinking twice before attacking you.  And you can hold up your P.U.N.K. traps as a political threat, waiting until someone has the audacity to target you.  I would suggest testing this deck on YGOPRO / Project Ignis for a while before playing so you can get a handle on all the possible combos and how to maximize the deck's potential.

My two custom cards for this deck: https://imgur.com/a/gf3eSiB

As for my custom Tao monster type, they're summoned by using monsters and spells/traps as material.  You can always use set spells and traps for material by revealing them to your opponent, so long as they meets the summoning conditions. For Ezmerin the Psychokinetic, you use Ezmerin the Psycher (main deck monster) and 2 Psychic/'mentions "Psychic" in its text' spells/traps to summon her. you can use dead-weight cards like a lingering monster or Brain Hazard to summon her, and the main deck Ezmerin makes whatever Psychic Extra Deck monster you summon with her untargetable by your opponent's. To give a basic rundown of my Tao monsters, Tao (the yin-yang symbols) are treated as levels and ranks simultaneously, and any effect that would effect those without specifying Xyz monsters or specific monster card type will affect them as well.  They don't double up the effect of something like "monsters you control gain/lose 100 ATK/DEF times their Level/Rank"; it's just the single buff/nerf, like any other monster.  And that's it.  You now know how to play them.  I don't use either of them as the Deck Master, as that would require a complete overhaul of the deck, since multiple P.U.N.K. monsters don't fit into her Dark/Wind/Psychic domain, but she's fun to play either way.

Whichever way you decide to play this deck, I hope you all enjoy!  It's a blast!

deck_excerpt: Harness the power of VTUBERs and LIGHTNING and electrify your Masterduel ladder opponents!
deck_description:
With the release of "Spright of Miracle," in Masterduel, every deck that contains level 2 monsters rejoiced since they have received a massive boost in form of the Spright archetype. Spright's many one card starters end on a board with multiple interruptions, negates and a decent grindgame. 
 
Augmenting Live Twin with Sprights, this mischevious VTUBER duo are more powerful than ever before. As VTUBER and lightning flawlessly meld into each other and synergize, Live Twin's draw power/pop coupled with Spright's negates/grindgame create one of the strongest contenders in the Masterduel meta! (Fun fact, this deck was a finalist on a recent Masterduel tournament!) 
 
Harness the power of VTUBERs and LIGHTNING and electrify your Masterduel ladder opponents!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING

 
Spright Live-Twin contains a whopping 14 handtraps and still has enough room to include starters for both the Spright and Live Twins to reliably start! An emphasis on handtraps is particularly potent with Live Twins, since Ki-sikil draws you potentially 2-3 cards (once on your turn and another during your opponent's turn with Ki-sikil and Ki-sikil Frost). The handtrap line-up include the most common handtraps for Crossout Designator to negate. 
 
As we all know, 2 cards = Full Spright combo, and a normal summon of 1 Live Twin is enough to suffice for that. This makes each Live Twin a 1 card starter, and there are 10 cards in the deck that start your Live Twin combo (3 Lil-la, 2 Ki-sikil, 3 Secret Password, and 2 Sunny's Snitch). 
 
8 Spright cards are also full combo (3 Blue, 3 Jet and 2 Starter), since they search pieces of the deck that summons more Sprights on board. 
 
With the Live Twins and Sprights conbined, this gives the deck a fantastic total of 18 one card starters! Each of these starters have the potential to end on a full board with 3+ interruptions, an "Iblee lock" and with several handtraps in hand! 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Spright Live Twin's gameplan is to interrupt and negate your opponent so much that they get out-resourced or they surrender since they've run out of options. Ki-sikil's draw 1, Lil-La's pop 1, Carrot's S/T negate, Red's monster negate, and Smasher's non-targeting banish are your main go-to choices of interruption. Most games you can Iblee lock your opponent so they cannot special summon except for link monsters, and if they try to link it away for a generic link 2 by normal summoning something, Lil-la will destroy their summoned monster to prevent the summon! I:P Masquerena is also an option, and she can be used to link summon during your opponent's main phase for Avramax or Underworld Goddess. 
 
Going first, you will establish a board with as many negations and interruptions as possible. Ideally in your hand, you should have several handtraps, especially those you drew off of Ki-sikil's effect. 
 
Going second, you will use your several handtraps to slow down or stop your opponent. If your opponent still has significant board presence you have the option to clear their board with Zeus. Summon 2 level 2s, XYZ summon Sky Cavalry Centaurea to eventually go to Zeus in main phase 2. From there, you can reset the board state, and play as normal next turn. 
 
Here is this deck's mainline combo: 
 
Live Twin Lil-la + Spright Blue/Jet = Iblee Lock + I:P Masqurena, + Spright Elf revive (Blue/Jet/Carrot/Red) + Evil Twin Ki-sikil (draw 1) + Evil Twin Lil-la (Target/Destroy 1)
 
  1. Normal summon Lil-la. Lil-la's effect to summon Ki-sikil Frost from deck. If you already have Frost, then summon the regular Ki-sikil instead. 
  2. Special summon Spright Blue/Jet. Search with their effect. (If you summoned Blue, it searches Jet) (If you summoned Jet, search Spright Starter to summon Blue). 
  3. Summon Jet/Blue. Search again for either Red (monster negate) or Carrot (S/T negate). 
  4. Summon Red/Carrot. Link away Blue + Jet to summon Elf. 
  5. Elf summons from GY a Spright monster (doesn't matter which one).
  6. XYZ summon Gigantic by using Red/Carrot + the Spright monster summoned by Elf from GY. 
  7. Gigantic effect to summon Iblee from deck. 
  8. Link away Iblee + Gigantic for I:P Masqurena. 
  9. Link away Lil-la + Ki-sikil Frost for Evil Twin Ki-sikil.
  10. Evil Twin Ki-sikil effect to summon Lil-la from GY. Link away Evil Twin Ki-sikil + Lil-la for Evil Twin Lil-la. 
  11. Evil Twin Lil-la summons Evil Twin Ki-sikil. Evil Twin Ki-sikil effect to draw 1 card. 
This combo with both archetypes working in tandem grants you a WHOLE LOT of interruption for your opponent to slog through. Iblee Lock limits your opponent's special summon options to links only. Spright Elf can revive whatever is in the GY (Blue/Jet/Carrot/Red) for a variety of effects. Ideally to further interrupt your opponent, you can summon Carrot/Red to tribute a Evil Twin monster so you can negate AND destroy your opponent's cards. I:P Masqurena can link away extra material on board for into a link toolbox of Unicorn (target shuffle 1), Avramax (Untargetable and indestructible protection) or Underworld Goddess (Link "superpoly," GY summon negate and fieldwide negate). Evil Twin Ki-sikil draws 1 card on summon, perhaps digging into your deck for more handtraps, while her bestie Evil Twin Lil-la target destroys 1 card on the field. Not counting your handtraps and set cards, that is 3 interruptions + Iblee lock! Of course, more strength is added to this board if you have the right extenders.

GENERAL TIPS

  • Leave the Evil Twin shenanigans as the last of your combo/interruption during your opponent's turn! Summoning from the GY using an Evil Twin locks you for the rest of the turn into fiend type! 
  • Instead of an "Iblee Lock," this deck can also Scythe lock. Instead of summoning I:P Masqurena during the main combo, Artifact Dagda is summoned so it can set Scythe from deck. Lil-la pops Scythe during your opponent's main phase to start the lock!
  • If you're going second and your opponent still has significant board presence, you can summon 2 level 2s, XYZ summon Sky Cavalry Centaurea to evetually go to Zeus in main phase 2. From there, you can reset the board state, and play as normal next turn. 
  • Since this deck relies a lot on hand traps, it is important to know the chokepoints of each deck, which handtraps are effective to use, what the most optimal time to handtrap your opponent's strategy, etc. For example, always save your Ash Blossom for your opponent's Branded Fusion! 
  • It generally is safer during the current meta to summon Spright Red during your first combo to negate a possible handtrap your opponent may use (especially Ghost Ogre vs. Gigantic Spright). 
  • You can cut Iblee and Spright Gamma Burst to bring this deck down to 40 cards, as they aren't essential to this strategy. 
  • Don't play the "Maxx C challenge" with this deck, unless you are confident you can OTK your opponent the same turn. Otherwise, if you go full combo, you'll be giving your opponent 10+ cards!
  • Unfortunately, Dark Ruler No More and most common floodgates eviscerate this deck. You can't handtrap/stop those cards! 
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

CONCLUDING COMMENTARY

Have you watched 10000+ hours of watching VTUBER livestreams and content? Do you have bunch of VTUBER merch? Is your current PC/phone background a (lewd) picture of a VTUBER? Do you also want to flatten your ladder opponents, leaving them in the dust with a million handtraps and interruptions? Then Live Twin Spright is the perfect deck for you! 

Seriously though, Spright breathes a whole new life into Live Twin, since both archetypes synergize and enable each other so well. Even I have managed to reach Diamond using only this deck, and it's pretty damn consistent and strong!
 
I hope you have as much fun piloting Spright Live Twin as I do - your opponent certainly won't enjoy facing it though. :3
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_name: 1st Place Locals Competitive Danger Dark World Deck (Combo-focused)
deck_excerpt: Hand rip for 4 and end on a ton of interruptions...
deck_description:
Overview of the Deck

This is the exact list I ran to win my locals, beating Swordsoul, Traptrix, Labrynth, Branded and Kashtira. It is similar to my last list, with a few changes that I feel help to make it optimal. While the deck has a high ceiling, it struggles with side-decking, as the Dark World and Dangers function together as a 40 card engine. I realised the best 5 cards to side out (this is usually the most cards you can remove without killing the engine) are 2x Ceruli, Guru of Dark World, a single copy of Sillva, Warlord of Dark World (because there's not usually any point hand-looping going second), Blackwing - Zephyros the Elite (so you can put in better going-second normal summons like Denko Sekka and Lava Golem) and a single copy of Broww, Huntsman of Dark World. Broww is a fantastic card, but the engine functions just fine with two copies post-siding. 

The changes and Dark World's adaptation to the meta

-1 Danger! Mothman! +1 Danger! Chupacabra! (Mothman is dangerous since it can allow your opponent to draw valuble side cards, and Chupacabra has more inherent synergy with the engine being a Fiend type while still being a level 4 for the critical rank 4 Xyz plays)

-1 Abyss Dweller (moved to the side) +1 Akashic Magician (Dweller has fallen out of favour since Tear got hit, but it is a fantastic side deck card going 1st, as it does not punish your engine and beats GY decks. Akashic is just a fantastic card, being able to bounce back both a Danger! monster and a Ceruli)

-3 Volcanic Scattershot +2 The Winged Dragon of Ra - Sphere Mode (I realised scattershot is fairly useless as we have Coach King Giantrainer to burn on time. It goes without saying that Sphere Mode is fantastic, especially when paired with Lava Golem as your 5 card side-in vs combo decks)

-3 Neko Mane King +3 Denko Sekka (With Labrynth and Traptrix running wild in the meta, Denko is a must since we don't need our normal summon. Also pairs nicely with a copy of Cosmic Cyclone and Harpie's Feather Duster for your 5 card side against backrow decks. You want the two cyclone for Runick, and you could even run 3 cyclone instead of Duster if you run into it too much. Duster is better than Lightning Storm as we can draw into it easily by comboing, and having anything on field turns off Lightning Storm after we draw into it. Neko was a good cheese option vs Tear, but that's no longer relevant) 

- Called by the Grave & Dark World Puppetry + Evilswarm Nightmare and 2x Linguriboh (Called by is just too sacky from my testing, no one was running Droll & Lock Bird today as most people are more scared of Kashtira, so it wasn't needed anyway. Dark World Puppetry is also less relevant because of the Tear hits. Evilswarm Nightmare is hilarious vs Kashtira going 1st, and Linguriboh is there to beat the Knightmare Corruptor Iblee lock)
