deck_description:
Deck Master: Ghostrick Jiangshi

Play peek-a-boo with a horde of chibi monsters!  This deck focuses on controlling the board and building a pillow fort of spells and traps to protect your spooky dudes as they gradually eat away at your opponent's through direct damage.  My personal build uses a custom card I made called Ghostrick Little Sistein in place of Number 96: Dark Mist - who threatens to return an opponent's card to the hand unless they give her a small treat of 500 LP, up to twice per turn.  Tao monsters use monsters and spells/traps as material, with Sistein requiring exclusively Ghostrick cards.  Tao (the yin-yang symbols) are treated as levels and ranks simultaneously, and any effect that would effect those without specifying Xyz monsters or specific monster card type will affect them as well.  They don't double up the effect of something like "monsters you control gain/lose 100 ATK/DEF times their Level/Rank"; it's just the single buff/nerf, like any other monster. She helps to unclog your backrow, given this deck runs a ton of spells and traps.

I'm unsure of the rules on setting your Deck Master, so at the moment I'm leaning on the safe side and just summoning Jiangshi normally and flipping it face-down with its effect.  Ghostricks are one of my all-time favorite archetypes.  The flavor of all the monsters and the mischievous peek-a-boo games are chef's kiss.

My custom card, Ghostrick Little Sistein: https://imgur.com/a/O03yxpN

Taken from AceOneOneSixTwoOne's Reptile Good Stuff TCG decklist but changed the ratios to include more draw power.

Slightly more bricking involved as now you might need to figure out how to get certain cards in grave before doing certain actions.

For example, if you start with Masked Chameleon, you need to figure out how to get it in the GY before Ogdoadic Water Lily. You also would ideally start with Nunu or else need to figure out how to get 5 Reptiles in the GY without Nunu before using Ogdoadic Water Lily. Having 10 draw cards that goes +0 should help though, but sometimes you will still brick...

When you're special summoning monsters off of Alien Shocktrooper, you would want to special summon Aron, Keurse, Lamia and Coatl. Aron and Keurse will be your Advance Draw targets at this point. 

Zohah is a great way to send a card in hand to the GY and bring back a Dark monster as an Allure target.

If you do start with Nunu, you should be able to draw out your entire deck without much issue.

deck_excerpt: Make zombies great again featuring branded
deck_description:
Have been experimenting with making zombies viable in the current meta since tearlaments and the ishizu cards got banned meaning that the zombie mill stratergy is far to inconsistent now. Also the ceiling for pure zombies is quite low with the amount of cards needed to reach a decent end board and the lack of follow up if the opponent clears the board.

The branded engine is perfect for consitensy as it gets necroworld banshee into the graveyard with branded fusion and has a banish on field with mirrorjade.

Combos:

You want to see zombie world/ necroworld banshee, uni-zombie/ shiranui solitaire/ doomking balderoch and 1 of the branded starters. You will normally open 2 out of 3 of these based on the play tests I have done.

If you open all 3 of these combo pieces you can make dragoon with balerdroch in the grave and zombie world on the field which is an omni, floodgate, banish and monster negate

If you don't see a line from the opening hand that can get balerdroch in the graveyard and zombie world on the field, you do not go into dragoon on that hand instead its mirrorjade with balderoch in the grave for 2 banishes and a negate for the next turn

Both these combo lines also play around nib

If you don't open a branded starter or have a way to go into one you do the normal zombie combo because you should have drawn at least 1 starter (the deck can still brick as it wouldn't be zombies if it couldn't) go to the normal zombie line where you end on baronne and balerdroch or red-eyes zombie dragon lord, balerdroch and felgrand in graveyard depending on what zombies you opened.

Handtraps/ Board breakers: I went with ash because it does work well in the zombie deck and is good against quite a few of the current meta decks, kaiju's were the other tech choice as with how kashtira are starting to play around lava golem and sphere mode kaiju's remove the arise heart without taking away your normal summon. The deck struggles to play through to many negates so being able to tribute an omni or monster negate helps the deck greatly.

Side Deck: The side deck is pretty standard evenly is very strong in this meta, twin twister being able to discard one helps the deck more than hinders it, rivalry zombie world will win the game on its own, ra's disciple branded expulsion also will win the game on it's own, called by is necessary hand traps hurt the deck greatly and if they side them in heavily it's good to have when your going first, by main decking kaiju's you get to side deck one of the strongest board clears avaliable in kaiju slumber as well and get a free level 8 body on the board for synchro plays
BD1 - YUGI - MAR/2002
Zombies, Charge!

The purpose of the deck is to summon Shining neos Wingman and dark law on the same turn, there are several different combos that can reach this situation, but the deck consistently manages to put Shining on turn 1, the main idea of ​​​​every combo is to put "Elemental HERO Flame Wingman - Infernal Rage" on the field using a normal monster for fusion, from then on he fights alone.

 

Combo 1.

EN - Engage Neo Space + any 2 elemental heroes in hand.

The ideal is to discard "Elemental HERO Shadow Mist" for its effect to bring another elemental hero to hand.

With the effect of the spell, just put Neos on the field and merge with the Hero in your hand.

 

Combo 2.

"Elemental HERO Blazeman" + "EN Shuffle" + "Any Hero in Hand"

Blazeman takes the poly of the deck and with the EN exchanges it for Neos and just merge.

 

Combo 3.

Only "Vision HERO Vyon"

Summon Vyon and send Dark Myst to the grave, with her effect take Neao to hand, exile with Vyon's effect to take the poly and just fuse.

 

Combo 4.

Only "Neos Fusion"

This one is slower, takes 2 turns to put Shining on the battlefield, Neos Fusion sends neos + armed dragon pro grave and summons Armed Neos cleaning the opponent's field, after destroying a monster in combat it can sacrifice to summon shining .

 

Main Combo.

"Elemental HERO Flame Wingman - Infernal Rage" sacrifices itself to bring "Elemental HERO Sunrise" which in turn will seek a miracle fusion that will merge the neos with the wingman of the bass, putting our boss on the field.

You can aways remove the Desnity Hero packge to put some hand traps, but i like to be greed and have all.

Good luck duelist!

deck_description:
2 Of Every Monster In Main Deck

3 Of The 2 Watt Synchro's

Zombie World Deck

Also known as The Army Of Darkness, this Deck type, as the name suggests, is based around the Field Spell, "Zombie World". This Deck is very versatile, as almost any of the Zombie staples can be splashed in. This Deck can be brutally effective against many other Decks, as "Zombie World", as well as changing all your opponents monsters on the field and in the Graveyard into Zombies, also stops your opponent from Tribute Summoning anything other than a Zombie monster. This negatively affects many commonly used Decks, such as Bujin, Plants, and Brotherhood of the Fire Fist. Many cards are designed specifically to work with the Field Spell, such as "Doomkaiser Dragon" or "Trap of the Imperial Tomb" or even "Sacred Crane" or "Molten Zombie" for draw power. Other cards have indirect merit, such as "Getsu Fuhma", "Marionette Mite", or even "Tutan Mask" when used on your opponents to stop pesky Spells or Traps. Another good card to try is "Beelze of the Diabolic Dragons", using "Plaguespreader Zombie" you can go into any level 6 Synchro monster, then bring Plaguespreader back using its effect, then Synchro Summon again for "Beelze".

This Deck has many Zombie staples such as "Pyramid Turtle", "Zombie Master", "Goblin Zombie", or "Plaguespreader Zombie" if you want to Synchro Summon. The key player in this Deck is without a doubt "Il Blud". "Kasha" can also be included, but remember that monsters treated as Zombies by the effect of "Zombie World" that are returned to the Deck are not counted towards its ATK. "Immortal Ruler" can also be used to recycle "Zombie World". Another excellent card to use is "Red-Eyes Zombie Dragon", which allows you to Summon any Zombie which it destroys by battle. "Pyramid Turtle" and "The Black Stone of Legend" can be used to search "Red-Eyes Zombie Dragon".

 

"Night Dragolich", while not a Zombie monster, can be used to support the Deck since the majority of its monsters will be Special Summoned from the Graveyard, if the likes of "Doomkaiser Dragon" are not being used (unless they are revived after being destroyed), which may not be the case for the opponent. "Curse of Dragonfire" can also be used with this Deck to not only destroy opposing Field Spells, but also Fusion Summon "Dragonecro Nethersoul Dragon" while "Zombie World" is on the field.

SD6 - SPELLCASTER'S JUDGMENT - JAN/2006

A deck that mixes a rock archetype and an archetype that should be a rock archetype but isn't. Combined, they make a strategy that really *rocks* (please don't complain about that in the comments).

This deck is designed to solve one main problem I have with Adamancipators, in that I always struggle to start the combo. I've found that anything that can XYZ summon Gallant Granite will set up a strong combo and endboard. The problem is getting to that. Previously, I've used the Ishizu cards and Tearlaments Schieren to get the two level four monsters needed, but that was costly to card advantage (not to mention the banlist).

However, Crystal Beast Sapphire Pegasus can easily set up an XYZ summon, and the combo won't lock you out of your rock monsters (unless I'm misunderstanding something - please correct me if I'm wrong). All you need is either Rainbow Bridge, Crystal Bond, or Sapphire Pegasus.

1: Use Rainbow Bridge to search for Crystal Bond 

2: Use Crystal Bond to add Crystal Beast Sapphire Pegasus to your hand, and to place Crystal Beast Cobalt Eagle into your Spell/Trap Zone

3: Normal summon Sapphire Pegasus, and activate its effect to place Crystal Beast Rainbow Dragon into your Spell/Trap Zone

4: Activate Crystal Beast Rainbow Dragon's effect, banishing it to special summon another Sapphire Pegasus from your deck while adding Rainbow Dragon to your hand

5: Overlay the two copies of Sapphire Pegasus in your monster zones to special summon Gallant Granite to an extra monster zone (placing it here gives you more room to summon cards with your tuner monsters. If you are able to link summon, then Granite's a good choice to use as material after you've used its effect anyways)

6: Detatch a material from Granite to add Adamancipator Researcher from your deck to your hand

7: Since you have a rock monster on the field now, you can special summon Researcher and activate its effect to try and summon a non-tuner rock monster.

From here, you can continue to summon using your Adamancipator cards. I generally aim to summon Adamancipator Risen - Dragite, Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess (with four negates), and Abyss Dweller for my endboard. This gives you plenty of negates to stop your opponent's combo, and you'll have plenty of attack power to finish them off the next turn. You can get pretty far off of just one copy of Rainbow Bridge, so if you have a third copy of either that or Crystal Bond then I would recomend adding those to your deck (the only reason I'm not doing that is because when I only have two of each. I'm trying to get third copies right now since I do play a lot of Crystal Beasts in general).

The side deck's just loaded with handtraps in case you need to side them in. Don't mind Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying... That's just to mess around with decks focused on banishing cards.

I know that it's an unconventional deck, it's been working well for me so far. Let me know if you have suggestions to improve this. Thanks!

deck_excerpt: The first good idea to come out of this site's randomizer
deck_description:
These two archetypes go surprisingly well together. I'm just angry Return got banned, or else this setup could go somewhere.

Feedback is always welcome.

Hi everybody,

 

This meta lets finally more space for other decks. And it's about time to bring back our Marincess strategy. Furthermore, some decklists did tops in YCS and WCQ. Then, I decided to update my own decklist for this format.

 

Some Thoughts

I think this list stays kinda standard. However, this is some things to enlighten

  • In this meta, Infinite Impermanence is a must have. Marincess has in its tools, a powerful trap : Marincess Wave. I think you have to play more than one copy of this card, as it's a powerful interruption + a good protection for your field monsters (it also includes not Marincess monsters). However, I think two copies is enough, as you can recycle this trap with Marincess Pascalus and Marincess Great Bubble Reef.
  • I prefered to run two copies of Cynet Mining and two of Pot of Desires instead of three of Cynet. IMO, Pot can be annoying if you banish the field spell. But most of the time, you are supposed to use it after having searched your Battle Ocean. Finally, you will be able to get some interruptions for the following turn.
  • I think Triple Tactics Talent is a solid two of in the deck. It's for me a good way to start to play after some interruptions (Marincess is pretty weak to the handtraps in general), especially with Ash and Nibiru in the meta.
  • The use of some Marincess monsters is debatable. First, Marincess Sleepy Maiden can be seen as a big brick (sometime it is), but I believe this card to be important for the deck more as a protection for the field spell than an extender for your board. For Marincess Basilalima, I've been convinced that this card is good to protect your monster from destruction and also for the bannishment effect (Fun stuff: you can use her attack buff multiple times in combination with Marincess Great Bubble Reef). For those reasons, I decided to keep one copy of each in the deck. Feel free to cut those card if you prefer other extenders or Power cards to run instead. 
  • Honestly, I don't really like Marincess Crystal Heart. I also find Eria the Water Charmer, Gentle a little situational (useful in the Spright matchup but not really that much). For that, I still believe Abyss Dweller to be a powerful card in the Extra Deck for a final spot (good lock of GY effects, little Atk buff as you use Water Materials)

 

As usual, if you have any thoughts/improvements/feedbacks respecting the list, do not hesitate to share it in the comment :)

Marincess is one of my favorite deck (and the first one I played when I start locals and tournaments) and I think the deck is a fun deck in the meta, with great weapons to make results and shine in tournaments. 

Hope you liked this list. Enjoy the game!

A nice blackwing deck

Advanced Crystal Beast Sapphire Pegasus and Advanced Crystal Beast Ruby Carbuncle are very good cards that are hindered by the fact that they cannot work without Advanced Dark. Now that AFD's errata is legal, you can search it in a more optimal way.

For our AFD package, we are playing 3 Dragunity Remus and 1 Destrudo the Lost Dragon's Frission. For Crystal Beasts, we are playing 3 Crystal Beast Sapphire Pegasus and 3 Crystal Beast Ruby Carbuncle. You want to open Ruby Carbuncle to use in tandem with Golden Rule, so we are playing 3 of it instead of the usual 1 or 2. For Advanced Crystal Beasts, we are playing 3 Advanced Crystal Beast Sapphire Pegasus, 3 Advanced Crystal Beast Cobalt Eagle, and 1 Advanced Crysal Beast Ruby Carbuncle. Advanced Pegasus is your 3rd, 4th, and 5th copy of Sapphire Pegasus and Advanced Ruby can only Summon Advanced Crystal Beasts. Advanced Eagle can discard itself to search Advanced Dark. You want to be able to access Advanced Dark to still do your plays if you don't see your AFD package and it is another name. Advanced Ruby can Summon itself if it is crystalized and it summons all other crystalized Advanced Crystal Beasts for more bodies. 

You want to draw more of your Spell/Traps more so than monsters which is why we are playing a lot. 3 Golden Rule. This is what the whole Deck centers around. It plus Ruby is an immediate 5 monsters worth of materials to work with and that is not counting things like AFD and other cards. 3 Armory Call to search Golden Rule. We usually do not use our Normal Summon in this Deck, so having more searchers for Golden Rule is great. 3 Dragon Ravine and 3 Advanced Dark. 3 Rainbow Bridge to search mainly either Golden Rule or Crystal Bond (whichever you are missing). 3 Bridge of the Heart for interruption when a Crystal Beast is crystallized and it can also search Golden Rule. Finally, 1 Crysal Conclave and 3 Crystal Miracle. 

Extra Deck can be whatever you want, but you should be playing some Rank 4's and Link Monsters and AFD of course. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder, 1 Drill Driver Vespenato, Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir, 1 Abyss Dweller, 1 Lighting Chidori, 1 Tornado Dragon, Ancient Fairy Dragon, Underworld Goddess of the Closed World, 1 Accesscode Talker, 1 Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess, 1 Knightmare Unicorn, 1 Knightmare Phoenix, 2 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Tri-Brigade Ferrijit the Barren Blossom. 

For the Side Deck, we are playing 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 1 Advanced Crystal Beast Topaz Tiger which buffs all of your Advanced Crystal Beasts and lowers the ATK/DEF of your opponent's stuff, 3 Dark Ruler No More, 1 Twin Twister, 1 Harpie's Feather Duster, 3 Evenly Matched, and 3 Infinite Impermanence.

deck_excerpt: It’s March 2023 and our favourite red lobster boi Gren Maju is still here to wreck face in Masterduel's Duelist Cup!
deck_description:
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

It’s March 2023 and our favourite red lobster boi Gren Maju is still here to wreck face in Masterduel's Duelist Cup! Blind second and smash boards with Super Poly, Kaijus, Lightning Storm and more! This deck is also fairly consistent since it features 6 draw cards, and Trade-In can be activated multiple times a turn! 

Games are usually extremely short, it doesn't matter if you win/lose the coinflip since you blind second, and it's very satisfying tearing down your opponent's board!

Either hit for game with 8000+ ATK Gren Maju, or OTK with a 9000 ATK Numeron Dragon! 

I’m not going to publish a long article with card ratios, combos, and strategies for this deck since it’s very straight-forward. Banish your own cards, obliterate your opponent’s board, summon big beatsticks and attack for game!

GLHF Duelists!

Note that many monsters in the Extra Deck don't need to used, you don't have to make the expensive URs for this to work.

deck_name: Danger Dark World w/ Branded Engine
deck_excerpt: For the times you need all gas on a budget
deck_description:
Consists of cards mostly from 3x Dark World structure decks with a few cards brought over from the Albaz Strike structure decks (also 3x). Only Muckraker From the Underworld is not found in these structure decks, as with Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring in the side deck.

 

Main Deck Overview:

- Danger! cards facilitate easy Special Summons and draw power. Can add Nessi or Chupacabra for better flow, but come at an increased price. Danger! cards also make for easy link material.

- Reign-Beaux, Overking of Dark World, Grapha, Dragon Lord of Dark World, and Genta, Gateman of Dark World are the main "meat" of the deck, utilizing their discard and summon effects to build a board of strong monsters.

- Snoww, Unlight of Dark World, Sillva, Warlord of Dark World, and Ceruli, Guru of Dark World are other useful Dark World discard effects. Notably, Snoww can search any Dark World card you may otherwise have to draw.

- Dark World spells pair with Dark World monster effects to utilize discard effects and summon the Grapha fusion.

- The Gates of Dark World is an essential field spell (easily searched with Genta) to help cycle Dark World monsters, load up the front row, and trigger other Dark World discard effects.

- Branded Fusion easily places Fallen of Albaz and another dark monster in grave to summon Lubellion (usually sending Grapha or Reign-Beaux to grave to easily special summon themselves from grave later). Lubellion effect can place another Dark World monster to grave while simultaneously summoning Mirrorjade and cycling Fallen of Albaz back into deck for a later use of Branded Fusion.

- Foolish Burial Goods can send Dark World Accession to grave for fusion summon with additional Dark World monster discard, or can send Dark World Punishment to protect Dark World monsters on the board.

- Card Destruction can cycle out a less-than-ideal hand while triggering Dark World discard effects.

 

Extra Deck Overview:

- Muckraker From the Underworld is an easy link summon that triggers more Dark World discard effects and can bring additional fiends from grave.

- Grapha, Dragon Overlord of Dark World fuision monster is an insanely strong beatstick that can negate any monster effect, normal spell, or normal trap once per turn.

- Lubellion the Searing Dragon is almost exclusively used to summon Mirrorjade.

- Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon is a strong beatstick monster with an easy monster removal effect (usually sending the dead Lubellion from extra deck for cost). Mirrorjade's grave effect wipes opponent's front row in the End Phase

 

Side Deck Overview:

- Danger! Thunderbird can be subbed in for slightly better draw power. Easily can be switched with nearly any other Danger! monster if you're willing to pay more for them.

- Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring for more interruptions.

- Dark World Lightning and Dark World Puppetry to enhance Dark World monster capability if needed (rarely used these in tournaments)

- Skill Drain to lock down effects (Warning: this does affect your monsters too. Use situationally when absolutely necessary)

- Deck Devastation Virus shuts down some meta decks with weaker monsters, namely Sprights and a few of the Traptrix monsters. If willing to pay more, Eradicator Epidemic Virus serves a similar purpose, using Grapha or Reign-Beaux as easy tributes

 

Main weaknesses noticed:

- Drawing Fallen of Albaz turn 1 is generally very bad. If sniped by Danger! effect, Branded Fusion cannot be played. If going second, Fallen of Albaz can be normal summoned, attempting to use opponent's monsters as material for Lubellion (if dark attribute) or directly into Mirrorjade (if they have extra deck monsters on the board). Fallen of Albaz is usually best sent from the deck.

- Drawing more than 1 Branded Fusion bricks your hand significantly. Can remove copies as needed, but then limits the Branded combo likelihood

- Called By The Grave, opponent Ash Blossom, and Ghost Belle completely shut down Dark World grave effects and Branded Fusion.

- Deck is significantly lacking in draw power. If you utilize Danger!s, Dark Worlds, and Braded Fusion all in one turn, you can often be left without a hand. Maintaining at least 1 card in hand is absolutely essential for the Grapha fusion effect, but more cards in hand is always better for further discard power. You could fill the extra deck with more cards of your choice and potentially sub in Pot of Prosperity or Pot of Extravagance for enhanced draw power (Ceruli and 2x Dark World Archives are what I would sub out for Pots). These cards can fetch a hefty price, however

This is a powerful and versatile Dark Magician deck that can adapt to different situations and strategies. The deck includes multiple copies of Dark Magician, the iconic card of the archetype, as well as powerful support cards like Magician's Rod and Magician's Souls that can search and recycle key cards from the deck. The addition of Timaeus the United Dragon and Palladium Oracle Mana allows for powerful fusion plays, while Apprentice Illusion Magician and Dark Magician Girl provide additional ways to summon Dark Magician and access the deck's fusion monsters. Fallen of Albaz and Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous are also great additions to the deck, providing extra power and control options. The deck's spell and trap cards are also strong, with multiple copies of Dark Magical Circle and Eternal Soul to protect and search key cards, while Secrets of Dark Magic and Soul Servant provide additional draw power and consistency. Branded Fusion and Illusion of Chaos allow for further fusion plays, while Skill Drain can shut down opposing strategies and disrupt the opponent's plays. The extra deck is also well-constructed, featuring powerful fusion monsters like Dark Magician the Dragon Knight and The Dark Magicians, as well as Synchro and Link monsters like Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon and Accesscode Talker that can deal with different types of threats. The inclusion of Black Luster Soldier - Soldier of Chaos and Knightmare Unicorn also provides additional removal and disruption options. Overall, this Dark Magician deck is a strong and well-rounded option for any duelist who wants to harness the power of the Dark Magician archetype. With a variety of fusion, control, and disruption options, this deck can handle any situation and emerge victorious.

deck_name: Duelist Cup DLV. MAX Spright Deck
deck_description:
This is the build I used to reach DLV. MAX in March 2023's Duelist Cup.

Let's start by talking about "missing the timing of activation." Swap Frog's effect text has these two words "when and "can" which is an indicator that this effect in order to activate, no event should take place after the effect's condition "When this card is Summoned." In my case, I activated Ronintoadin's effect (chain 1), then I chained Spright Elf to summon Swap Frog from the GY. Chains in Yu-Gi-Oh! resolve backwards, so Spright Elf summons Swap Frog (the effect must activate at this very moment and cannot wait), chain 2 resolved and we move to chain 1 summoning Ronintoadin. Chain's cannot be interrupted after they start resolving and must resolve fully before any card can be activated, so Swap Frog when it was summoned wanted to activate, but according to the rules that's illegal and since this kind of effect does not wait, it ends up missing the timing of activation.

Things to note about this deck:
- Spright Starter and Gigantic Spright lock you from Special Summoning above Level/Rank/Link 2 monsters. In the case of Gigantic Spright, it locks both you and your oponent from Special Summoning above Level/Rank/Link 2 monsters. The text also says "For the rest of this turn" which means you can still summon any Level/Rank/Link prior to the activation of the effect of any of these two cards.
- Avramax inherently cannot be targeted by any effect and your oponent can only attack him. With I:P Masquerena, Avramax gains protection from destruction. Avramax's effect to gain attack power during Damage Calculation can only work against Special Summoned monsters.
- If you don't have the materials to summon Number 65: Djinn Buster and you're summoning using Spright Elf while Swap Frog is in the GY, make sure to summon it to send another copy of itself to the GY for Ronintoadin. Having that extra Special Summon will always matter.

As usual, you can find the gameplay video below. Enjoy the replays! Peace.

deck_excerpt: floo is back, with a new bird friend
deck_description:
Floo took a pretty big hit with the latest patch, hitting an important piece of their puzzle: Barrier Statue of the Stormwinds. But that doesn't mean Floo is unusable without their primary floodgate; it just means we'll have to adapt and rely on new weapons, including a new bird to the fellowship. 

Simorgh's Winged-Beast and Wind typing make it an easy fit to the Floo system, with Elborz providing strong search potential when Magnificent Map doesn't get drawn, and Simorgh itself acting as good fodder for tribute summons. 

Barrier's ban means that to remain viable (and as annoying as usual), we'll have to put greater emphasis on two familiar cards; Empen and Unexplored Winds. Empen's surprisingly oppressive and effective floodgating along with Unexplored Winds' strong, Super Poly-style disruption creates a strong core to build around. 

Other than that, load your deck up with other knick-knacks like the (honestly, quite OP) Harpie's Feather Storm, which synergizes really well with Simorgh; Nibiru for Sprights and other combo decks; along with the interesting choice of Lancea, to be used against Kashtira, the spiritual successor to Tearlaments. They'll need a lot of banishing to get their work done, so a well places Lancea will send them reeling. Other than that, side deck options include Ultimate Slayer, Forbidden Lance, Cyclone, etc. AND ALSO D. Shifter, which has moved from main deck tyrant, to rogue side deck option. Banishing extra cards just makes things easier for Kashtiras, with Arise-Heart's Macro Cosmos-esque effect. 

As a finishing note, you might be interested in the very out-of-place extra deck; it's used as a facade, a way to confuse opponents, particularly Kashtira fans and their frequent Diablosis uses, which can get them completely mistaken about your archetypes (pretty common Tearlaments-ish extra deck). You barely use the extra deck anyways, with Floo's inherent restrictions on extra deck summoning, so make use of it in a different way! You can optionally add a synchro monster for Ultimate Slayer, but I didn't because it might mess with the illusion.

deck_excerpt: Simorgh / Floowandereeze deck focusing on trap/spell locking
deck_description:
A Simorgh / Floowandereeze deck that juggles between Floo and Simorgh normal summoning mechanics.

It can perform up to 8 normal summons in a single turn!

Combine the powerful effects of Anti-Spell Fragrance, Dark Simorgh, Harpie's Feather Storm and Floowandereeze & Empen to lock your opponents' traps, spells and monster effects!

Book of Moon and Book of Eclipse are here to protect your low-level birds from some hand traps like Infinite Impermanence or Effect Veiler (first turn) or to flip your opponent's monsters face-down and weaken their board.

Combining Simorgh Onslaught and Elborz, the Sacred Lands of Simorgh, it is possible to reduce the tribute cost of your wingfed beast and normal summon monsters like Dark Simorgh or Mist Valley Apex Avian without any tribute.

The extra-deck is here to support you if Floowandereeze can't be used. Cyber Dragon Nova is an answer to monsters like Dogmatika Maximus. Chimeratech Megafleet Dragon will remove extra zone monsters and cyber dragon monsters from your opponent's field. Unlike Floo, Simorgh monsters can still work after performing a special summon.

Les recomiendo ver el canal  @MaskedHEROVic  que tiene una cantidad valiosa de como detener este arquetipo. TRASLATE Kashtira appeared in the DARKWING BLAST main set, KASHTIRA is meant to be a competitive deck. After the recent banlist hit of March 2023, Kashtira has gained more notoriety in the most important konami tournaments. It is an extremely strong deck but not invincible. I highly recommend watching the @MaskedHEROVic channel which has a valuable amount on how to stop this archetype.

This is my decklist rn, I'm still working on it. I'm set on the monster lineup, maybe cut one panthera. Bystials are very good in the deck, Magnamhut can search your boss monster while Baldrake can tribute your link to active it's effect.
The deck needs to consistently get to Razen first turn and I'm split between Durendal/Small World. Small world has the added versatility of being able to get you pretty much any monster at the cost of going -1. Neither are ideal because you can't use them without a monster and the same goes for Stake Your Soul!.
There can be only one is a must because it's good going first and second and doesn't affect you at all.
I don't use the extra deck much, Knightmare Phoenix is a must because it can easily be co-linked with your link 1. Link 3s are very awkward to make,the extra Zoodiacs are there to fill the extra deck and get Zeus to 6 mats, I could use just Chakanine and Boarbow if I need to make up space.

I haven't put much thought into the side deck yet.

deck_excerpt: A somewhat budget but competitive branded despia deck
deck_description: Yuh

This deck focuses on draw power and getting out either Rexterm or Plasma. Maybe both? The idea is to lock your opponent out of game by playing Rexterm or Plasma. At first, this doesn't seem like it works, but this deck is fun. So you have three lock out options, two you can use at the same time.

First one is Destiny Hero Dark Angel. You Fusion Destiny into Destiny Hero Dominence and place in defense mode. Three destiny heroes in GY are needed to activate Dark Angel and palce on opponents side of the field. Your three targets are Dreadmaster, Draw Hand, and Disk Commander. What you do is activate Dominence effect to look at the top five cards and stack them how you want. When Dominence is destroyed at the end phase of the next turn, Special Summon Dreadmaster, Disc Commander, and Draw Hand. Disc Commander and Draw Hand lets you draw 3 cards off their effect.

Second is Rexterm, Draw Therizia and search Frenzy. Set the card in your S/T zone, and fusion summon on your opponents turn. First into Kentrigina and then Rexterm. Rexterm prevents your opponent from activating monster effects if they are equal or more to your life points. Rexterm's quick effect is to half the life points and make opponents monsters equal your life points.

The Third is Plasma Plus D-Force, You get three monsters on the field, play D-Force to search Plasma and then play Plasma. Plasma is both Skill Drain and Relinquished at the same time. Easy way to get the three monsters on the field is play Fusion Destiny and summon any destiny hero monster from the extra deck but make sure your targets are Malicious and Denier. They can summon themselves from the GY. They're an easy summon, and can turbo out Plasma easy. Plasma + Rexterm just says nope to all effects and D-Force gives Plasma staying power. They're pretty formidable together and they annoy friends pretty easy too.

I wanted to post something different and see where this goes. If you build the deck, I promise you'll have fun with it. Happy Dueling.

deck_excerpt: Spright Runick is arguably the current reigning champion of Masterduel meta as of March 2023! Earn that Diamond 1 or MAX Duelist LVL!!!
deck_description:
Spright Runick is arguably the current reigning champion of Masterduel meta as of March 2023. The ridiculously strong combination of Spright and Runick's smothering control and endless grind game create a deck that all strategies would have to fear and respect. Sprights ending on 3-5 interruptions (Red's monster negate, Carrot's S/T negate, Smasher's banish, and I:P Masquerena's quick link) combined with Runick's draw 3 and quick play spells generally stop any deck cold in their tracks. Both archetypes combined have a potential 10+ interruptions for your opponent to slog through, while maintaining a superior resource loop - outpacing most other strategies!
 
If you want to win and reach Diamond 1 or reach max rank in Duelist Cup in Masterduel with a relentlessly strong control strategy, you've chosen to pilot the correct deck!
 
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
 
SPRIGHT has 8 one card starters in the deck (3 Blue, 3 Jet and 2 Starter). In any case, if you don't open any of these cards, 2 level 2 monsters would create Gigantic Spright, leading to full Spright combo. Spright has immense synergy with Runick since their quick play spells summoning Hugin already fulfills one of the two level 2s needed for Gigantic Spright or Spright Elf! 
 
There are 16 RUNICK quick play spells in the deck to maximize the chances of drawing 2-3 in your opening hand in a deck of 40 cards. Ideally, the duelist would use 1 quick play spell to summon Hugin, searching for Runick Fountain, 1 for the discard for Hugin's cost to search, and the last quick play spell to trigger Fountain, drawing you 2-3 cards. After Hugin is established on board, it is a level 2 - enabling your Spright combo. 
 
The rest of the deck is composed of STAPLES, designed to counter the current meta of Masterduel. 2 of each staple rather than 3 is used to lower the likelihood of drawing multiples of the same card. 2 Cosmic Cyclone is generally useful, and more so important in the common Runick mirror match to banish Fountain. 2 Lava Golem is used to tribute through established boards, especially when versing other Spright players. Lava Golem is great in this deck since it doesn't require it's normal summon. 2 Maxx "C" and 2 Ash Blossom are always really good in OCG-centred Masterduel format. Drawing more cards with Maxx "C" is great for keeping other decks in check while providing you with more Runick ammunition to play with.


COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
 
Spright Runick's gameplan is to interrupt and negate your opponent so much that you out resource them. If they don't outright surrender, the strategy is to deck them out in an extended grind game as Spright Elf recovers/recycles Sprights in the GY and Runick Fountain draws you up to 3 cards every turn. Theoretically, your opponent will be so helpless and out-resourced that they cannot come close to attacking you for game, especially as you and your monsters hide behind your Avramax.
 
Here is the mainline combo for this Spright Runick:
 
Spright 1 card starter + Runick quick play spell(s) = Spright Elf, I:P Masquerena, 3-5 cards and possibly Spright Red/Carrot with a set Smashers. 
  1. Activate Runick quick play spell to summon Hugin. 
  2. Hugin searches for Runick Fountain. Discard a card for cost (Ideally you discard another Runick quick play to draw more with Runick Fountain You can also discard another Spright since it can be revived later by Elf). 
  3. Activate Runick Fountain. If you can trigger Runick Fountain with another quick play spell, activate it to draw 1-3 cards. It is best to do this after you finish all your searching with your Spright combo to increase your chances of drawing into more Runick quick-play spells or handtraps.
  4. Activate your 1 card Spright starter. Do the full Spright combo! (Spright Blue -> Spright Jet -> Searches Starter or Smashers). 
  5. Use Hugin + Blue/Jet to XYZ summon Gigantic. 
  6. Activate Gigantic's effect to summon your level 2 (Capshell/Iperia draw 1, Red/Carrot negate) of choice from deck by detaching the Spright material. 
  7. Link away Blue/Jet and level 2 summoned from deck to link summon Spright Elf. 
  8. Elf summons level 2 of choice from GY. 
  9. Link away Level 2 from GY + Gigantic Spright = I:P Masquerena. 
  10. If you have any other extenders, summon them, and set any cards you want to use in the backrow like Smashers. 
This combo should leave you with Spright Elf's quick summon from GY, I:P Masquerena's quick link, and perhaps a negate with Spright Red/Carrot. You may have drawn 3-5 cards due to Runick Fountain, Ipiria and Capshell, leaving you with many of interruptions ready in your hand. You also may have a set Smashers or Cosmic Cyclone. 
 
During your opponent's turn, you may have 3-10 interruptions ready for them (highly dependent on opening hand and draws). Your life points and low ATK monsters are protected as you link away Elf + Masquerena for Avramax (You can also link into Unicorn for the targeted shuffle or Underworld Goddess for blanket negate and GY summon negate). On top of that, you will continue to draw additional cards with Runick Fountain on your opponent's turn! 
 
Due to your immense pressure as you choke your opponent out of their possible plays and banish their deck, they will surrender in no time as they are out-resourced and out-matched! 
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • If you want to play safe to protect your combos, summon Spright Red early so it can negate the ever-prevalent Ash Blossom and Nibiru.
  • Verses S/T strategies, summon Spright Carrot to protect your plays. This is useful in Runick matchups and the occasional Labrynth player. 
  • Little known fact, you can still successfully use I:P Masquerena in this strategy if your opponent drops Dark Ruler No More! CL1 your opponent uses Dark Ruler, CL2 you use one of your quick play spells, then CL3 I:P Masquerena activates her quick link effect! Ideally she links away your monsters (who would otherwise be negated) for Underworld Goddess, who is unaffected by Dark Ruler No More. 
  • Avramax is the ideal I:P Masquerena link target, linking with Elf. After your opponent's first action in main phase (CL1), chain Masquerena's effect (CL2), then Elf's effect to summon from GY (CL3). Avramax is a monster many decks have difficulty outing since he is untargetable, indestructible (due to Masquerena) and mostly unkillable in battle! Your lifepoints and low ATK monsters are in good hands with him around! 
  • If your opponent resolves Maxx "C," don't continue with the Spright combo. It just isn't worth it giving your opponent 10+ cards. Your Runick cards are still a potent force!
  • Keep in mind that with Spright Runick, your Extra Monster Zone is used up by Spright Elf - meaning you can't protect your cards from destruction effects by summoning Hugin. 
  • Dharc the Dark Charmer is full Spright combo. Dharc summons dark monster from opponent's GY -> Link away into Spright Elf -> Elf summon level 2 from GY -> Elf + level 2 makes Gigantic Spright -> Proceed to Spright combo!
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
I would say that Spright Runick is the ultimate meta deck as of March 2023 (If you pilot this deck, you are officially a hardcore, no-fun, meta sheep. Be proud of the title!!! >:D)
 
Resilient, flexible, and powerful, Spright Runick can play through most end boards while preventing any strategy from starting their plays. Reach Diamond 1 and max level Duelist Cup as you crush your opponents with your 10+ interruptions/negates while you draw 2-5 extra cards per turn!

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: A new consistent way to play Dark Magician with no bricks and every card you draw or play into will help your strategy to win your duels!
deck_description:
This deck does not brick. For further proof, use the playtest button. Every card in this deck does something to further your strategies. For example, Deployment can be used for Combination, Wonder Wand (if sided in), Circle, and Piercing. A bunch of synergy and Conscription can be used for Allure, Combination, Timaeus, (a pitch for) Branded, and SoDM. Too much combos in this deck. It does literally everything! 

The key to this deck is getting to TDMs and/or your Fusion material monsters including and mainly DM (and his Fusions majority wise, using Dragons). You can also summon 2 Dragoons in 1 turn by using cards like Magicalized & Branded for example. If not, you can setup the Dragon Knight boardlock.

Deck is too consistent not to win with. Handtrap baits in here also. But it can die to Droll if theres not a negate in time and Nibiru if its not less than 5 summons. Otherwise, this deck is great.

deck_excerpt: Everybody knows Shaddoll Fusion. But what if we use the Shaddolls to create a powerful end board for Gate Guardians Combined?
deck_description:
Everybody knows Shaddoll Fusion. But what if we use the Shaddolls to create a powerful end board for Gate Guardians Combined? Could we use Sacred Sword of Seven Stars to help our opening hand if we brick? This deck is currently built to use the Gate Guardian pieces as part of the Shaddoll fusions.

 

Side Deck Usage:

  • Chaos Trap Hole can be sided in when facing a deck like Spright and Tearalament
  • The Selection can be sided in when facing Spright and Tearalament
  • Skill Drain can be sided in when facing just about any deck, but is most beneficial against Branded and Dragon Link
  • Grand Horn of Heaven can be sided in when facing a deck that starts its turn with a Special Summon (i.e. Lyrilusc, Speedroid, and Superheavy Samurai

deck_excerpt: Post-PHHY, Generaider receives two strong incredible cards which greatly solve their past issues - bricking and breaking boards!
deck_description:
Generaider has been one of the coolest archetypes from the deck build packs. As a RPG connoisseur, the idea of piloting a deck as the dungeon master pitting your opponent through a "boss rush" scenario is so cool! 

With the release of Photon Hypernova, Generaider receives two strong incredible cards which greatly solve their past issues - bricking and breaking boards! 
 
Vala, Seidhr of the Generaider Bosses unbricks your hand by summoning herself from hand or GY by sending a Generaider cards to the GY. When she is summoned, she also summons another Generaider from hand or GY - providing two level 9 bodies for a rank 9 play! 
 
Talking about rank 9s Laevatein, Generaider Boss of Shadows is XYZ "superpoly" with essentially a 3500ATK/DEF statline. Attach any cards that your opponent has in the field or GY, even backrow!

Even more consistent and strong with the new support pure Generaider is now able to stuff 15+ staples in their decklist, allowing it to compete with the meta. Be your opponent's final BOSS as you pilot Generaider!
 
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
The major difference with this decklist with previous Generaider lists is that there are no supplementary engines to support the strategy - Generaider is now able to stand on it's own archetypal legs post-PHHY. 
 
No other engines mean that Generaider has more room for staple cards to specifically counter the meta - Ash Blossom, Nibiru, Book of Eclipse and Skill Drain. 
 
Since Generaider is incentivized to include more level 9s with the addition of Vala, ten level 9 Generaider bosses are used to enable the deck go into rank 9 XYZ plays. Laevatein is your main go-to rank 9, however, some situations may call for Infinitrack Earth Slicer or Enterblathnir. Some hands allow for four level 9 Generaider to be deployed on the board, so you can hand-rip two cards from your opponent's hand (Double Enterblathnir) then make Utopic Draco Future! Combos will be explained below.
 
3 Hop Ear Squadron is particularly effective in this deck. During your opponent's turn, you can synchro two tokens away with Hop Ear Squadron to hand rip your opponent for one card and make Baronne De Fleur!
 
3 Skill Drain is used since Generaider functions perfectly fine under it, since they all tribute themselves for cost, effectively dodging Skill Drain's field-wide negate. If you ever want to turn off this floodgate, Laevatein can attach the card under Jormungundr as XYZ material!
 
There are 15 ways to search Generaider Boss Stage in this deck + the three Boss Stages themselves - giving you a total of 18 ways to get your all-inportant field spell on board.
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
 
Generaiders function as a control strategy, negating and interrupting your opponent until your giant beatsticks can attack for game. Pure Generaider combos are simple since the strategy is so straightforward. Do not underestimate it's simplicity, since it is very potent!
 
Here are the combos for Generaider:
 
Vala, Seidhr of the Generaider Bosses + Mardel, Generaider Boss of Light = Boss Stage and Laevatein
  1. Activate Vala's effect to summon herself by sending Mardel to the GY. 
  2. On summon, activate Vala's on-field effect to summon a Mardel from your GY/hand.
  3. Mardel searches Boss Stage. If you have another Generaider on hand, search Boss Quest instead, then search Boss Stage + Another Generaider S/T. 
  4. Activate Boss Stage.
  5. XYZ summon Laevatein using Vala + Mardel. 
Vala, Seidhr of the Generaider Bosses + Any level 9 Generaider + World Legacy Monstrosity = Boss Stage, 2 card hand-rip and Utopic Draco Future
  1. Activate Vala's effect to summon herself by sending level 9 Generaider to the GY. 
  2. On summon, activate Vala's on-field effect to summon a level 9 Generaider from your GY/hand.
  3. Activate Monstrosity targeting Vala on the field. Summon from deck Mardel and another level 9 Generaider. 
  4. Mardel searches Boss Stage. If you have another Generaider on hand, search Boss Quest instead, then search Boss Stage + Another Generaider S/T. 
  5. Activate Boss Stage.
  6. XYZ summon Enterblathnir. Activate it's effect to banish a random card from your opponent's hand. 
  7. Repeat step 6. Banish a second card from your opponent's hand. 
  8. XYZ summon Utopic Future by overlaying your two Enterblathnirs.
  9. XYZ summon Utopic Draco Future using your Utopic Future. 
 
Hop Ear Squadron + 2 Generaider Tokens = 1 card hand-rip and Baronne De Fleur
  1. During your opponent's draw phase, summon Harr, Generaider Boss of Storms from deck. 
  2. During your opponent's main phase, negate your opponent's card effect with Harr, using two tokens so Hop Ear can use their effect. 
  3. Synchro summon using Hop Ear Squadron from hand + Generaider token for Desert Locusts. 
  4. On summon, discard a card from your opponent's hand with Desert Locusts. 
  5. Synchro summon using Desert Locusts + Generaider Token for Baronne De Fleur. 
Going first, it is imperative that the Duelist always establish Generaider Boss Stage. Everything else is just extra. Almost every hand would end on Laevatein's "XYZ Superpoly" and Boss Stage's summon from deck of another Generaider Boss. However, the most incredible hands can end on Enterblathnir's double hand-rip, Utopic Draco Future's monster negate/steal, Desert Locust's hand-rip and Baronne De Fleur. Also, this deck boasts 15 staple slots, so you hand can have an Ash Blossom, Nibiru, etc. for further interruption. 
 
Going second, this deck's ample space enables it to side in a multitude of going second cards. After an enemy's board has been sufficiently weakened, you can summon beefy beatsticks to beat down your opponent's monsters in the battle phase, then in main phase 2 you can use Laevatein to XYZ superpoly away their surviving monsters, backrow, and GY. 
 
GENERAL TIPS
 
  • Although somewhat limiting, this deck can still play relatively comfortably under Dimension Shifter, Dimensional Fissure and Macro Cosmos. If the duel calls for it, you can side this into your deck to metagame your opponents. 
  • A huge weakness this deck has is Cosmic Cyclone/Runick Destruction/Twin Twister on your Boss Stage. That usually ends most of your interaction and interruption vs. your opponent. 
  • Summon Loptr with Generaider Boss Stage first to give all your Generaider monsters and tokens an attack boost. Opponents tend to attack the low ATK tokens since they're a weak point in your defense. Tribute them before they get a chance to!
  • If one of your Generaider monsters get negated or rendered useless, you can tribute it with Loptr to summon another Generaider Boss from deck, giving you another form of interaction.
  • This Generaider deck has a lot of staples. These are the best cards to side-out in games 2 and 3 - Nibiru, Ash Blossom, Hop Ear Squadron, Book of Eclipse, Generaider Boss Room and Skill Drain. 
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
The gameplay of pure Generaider is tempo based, where you go for 1 for 1 trades vs. your opponent until you come out on top because of Generaider Boss Stages sheer grind power and free resource generation every turn It's not too complicated with it's combos which is perfect for duelists who just want to play Yugioh without worrying about messing up their complex combo/gameplay (like me lmao). A rare props to Konami for their design choices for the support for this archetype. Granting an underpowered deck with one of the strongest forms of removal, Laevatein's "XYZ superpoly" fixes Generaider's problems breaking boards going second. Generaider's crippling limitations with level 9 bricks in hand is largely solved by Vala while simultaneously enabling rank 9 plays is genius! 

All in all, this older deck is granted new life for today's meta with two very strong support cards. Now, give your opponent the Boss Rush of their dueling career as you negate, hand-rip and XYZ super poly to victory with Generaiders!!!
 
 GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Red Dragon Archfiend, Resonator, Chaos, Rokket
deck_description:
A Red Dragon Archfiend deck focusing on bringing out the heavy hitters in the Extra Deck as consistently as possible with help from the new Chaos Synchro cards and a small Rokket engine. When Chaos Ruler, the Chaotic Magical Dragon was banned, the deck took a heavy hit, since Chaos Ruler helped majorly with consistency and play extension. However, the deck is not totally dead, as the new Chaos Synchro cards heavily increase the consistency of the Main Deck, allowing for far easier spamming of Level 8 Synchros, as well as the bigger boys, like Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss, Bane, and of course, Red Supernova Dragon, as well as some new DARK Synchro Monsters, like Bystial Dis Pater, and some non-Dragons in case you're able to Summon them, like Chaos Angel and Chaos Beast.

The deck's win conditions are still mostly the same. Hope for a good hand, or use the many consistency tools to sculpt one, then go down the Crimson Resonator line into Red Supernova Dragon. This time, however, the Chaos Synchro cards help save your Normal Summon throughout the combo, making it just a little easier to play through interruption, and allowing you to continue your combo after the Supernova hits the field. A new major boss of the deck, Bystial Dis Pater, helps with interruptions. Being a DARK Dragon Synchro Monster, it combos perfectly with the two Traps, Red Reign and Time to Stand Up, allowing for it and either Trap to hold the field down until the next turn. Specifically, with Red Reign, you can banish all monsters your opponent controls in the middle of their combo (as long as you do so before they get a Level 10 or higher monster), then if they can continue further, Dis Pater can shuffle one of your opponent's banished monsters (or one of your own) into the Deck, then either negate the effect of or destroy the monster they were hoping to save their field with. Time to Stand Up is also a monster negate from the Graveyard while you control Dis Pater (or any other Level 10 or higher DARK Dragon Synchro Monster), and it's easy to set up, as it can banish itself the same turn you use its field effect to Special Summon some Resonators from your Deck, which you can hopefully use to your advantage next turn. If you wish to Special Summon Red Resonator and use its Special Summon effect to heal yourself for a phat 3500+ LP, activate it in Chain Link 1, please.

Other changes from my previous Red Dragon Archfiend deck include a smaller Rokket package; really just a trimming of the excess Rokkets, as you don't really need two Recharger or Synchron. A third copy of Tracer was shaved as well, as though it's a good Normal Summon, you'd prefer to Special Summon it with Quick Launch. Space can be made for a third copy, though. Some Extra Deck fluff was shaved. Ancient Pixie Dragon is no longer necessary, as making Level 6s and Level 8s are much easier than Level 7s with the new Chaos Synchro cards. Chaos Ruler was also removed, since it is now unfortunately banned. A second copy of Scarlight Red Dragon Archfiend was included, as its name is useful, and its effect is serviceable, especially in the relatively low-ATK meta we're seeing right now. Some other cards that could be included in the Main Deck are seen in the Side. I couldn't find space (or necessity) for Chaos Mirage Dragon, Resonator Command, or Burning Soul, but they may be preferrable to some. Chaos Angel and Chaos Beast were only included because the Extra Deck isn't super tight, and they may be useful in the niche situation where you're bloated with Chaos monsters who don't lock you into Dragons. Chaos Angel's LIGHT material effect is extremely useful if you can bring it out, as activated monster effect immunity can be incredibly useful for securing the effects of your Red Dragon Archfiends. Chaos Beast is also nice as a self-recurring Synchro Material, finding itself useful for niche comebacks where you can manage to use it for Tyrant Red Dragon Archfiend or even Red Supernova Dragon. Void Ogre Dragon is more useable in this version of the deck, as you can empty your hand fairly quickly with the banishing to achieve a deadily field. Hopefully Void Ogre Dragon is enough Spell/Trap negation to balance out the loads of monster negation and overall shafting that the other Synchros and Trap Cards provide. Red Resonator is also more useful than in some other versions, as the Chaos Synchro monsters in the Main Deck can be Special Summoned by any card effect, not just their own, making some awkward hands where you have no banish material playable, where even Crimson Resonator might be useless in that situation.

I hope this decklist is to your likings, Kings. This should hold us over nicely until Konami reveals the new Red Dragon Archfiend support cards we should be getting soon-ish from the semi-recently revealed Jack Atlas Structure Deck. We will all soon be the Masters of Faster, and we shall all soon rule the duels, Kings.

deck_excerpt: Basic Gold Pride deck supported by P.U.N.K. engine.
deck_description:
A Gold Pride deck that uses the P.U.N.K. engine to eat your lifepoints to activate your gold pride cards. Cards that eat lifepoints like Hope for Escape or that increase your opponent's life points like Upstart also work. 

Side deck and handtraps are to counter Kashtira. Out of all the TCG exclusive archetypes, Gold Pride is the closest to being playable. They just need more ways to lower lifepoints on turn one and a way to play through being banished by dimensional shifter.

Side Deck Notes:

1. Cosmic Cyclone x3 > Replace 1 Sanga of the Thunder, 1 Kazejin, and 1 Suijin

2. Ash Blossom OR Ghost Belle > Replace 1 Ash Blossom OR Ghost Belle, add either Harpie's Feather Duster or Called by the Grave

3. Foolish Burrial Goods x2 OR Sacred Sword of Seven Starts x2 > Replace Angel of Blue Tears x2
WIP budget deck
fun deck

deck_excerpt: A non-meta counter to Traptrix and Labrynth, with some side prep for Kashtira.
deck_description:
Traptrix and Labrynth are super meta right now, as is Kashtira, so I've tried my hand at a build to counter them and pave a way for Dragonmaids. The most expensive cards here are the Bystials, obviously, and you want EEV in your main deck (swappable with Book of Moon depending on if you think you'll fight Trix/Laby or Kash more often.)

You almost always want to end on Hieratic Seals and Sheou as per usual Dragonmaids strategy, and keep Tidying in the GY for some card advantage. Super Polymerization is here as a backup tool, but it's not the focus of anything. And of course we have Feather Duster and Lightning Storm for backrow removal, as well as Evenly in the side.
Swarm board with level/link/rank 2's and create boss link/xyz monsters.

deck_excerpt: Dino's and traps, what more could you ask for?
deck_description:
Deck overall usage can be used in just about any format, as it can be annoying to deal with. 

Note: This deck is not limited to Master Duel, it can work very well on it's own in TCG and other such usage. 

Best Case Scenario is using Domain and Frenzy, getting Rexterm and Kentregina out during your opponents turn to lock-down effect cards with attack at or above your LP, which is fairly common. If it isn't low enough, use Kentregina to get it even lower!

Diplos summons can provide support if Kentregina's already out, throwing Sonic or Brute into the grave to use from Kentregina. 

If you draw either Solemn card, have them set before you use Therizia or Lilith, or save them for your opponent's turn to lock-down the board. 

Ferret Flames compliments your low LP and can help clear away your opponent's monsters. 

Gozen, Rivalry, and Mistake is nasty to use all at once, with Imperial Custom to support them, but limiting your spell / trap zone, rarely seen, but used with caution. 

Mistake counters your Fossil Digs, so make sure if you get one, use it before activating Mistake.

deck_description:
This is basically my Diamond 1 Worthy build which you can find here:
https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/diamond-1-worthy-runick-spright-deck-321736

The only change I made was taking out Triple Tactics Talent for Lava Golem. It helped a lot with going 2nd. After they nerfed the deck by limiting the runick archetype, the deck's capacity to go 2nd diminished quite a lot. Adding those 2 extra board breakers helped a lot more than Triple Tactics Talent.

Category: Tournament Meta Deck

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Bazil "Oni no Hanzō" Batise

Tournament: Winnipeg WCQ Regional - March 19th 2023

Placement: Top 8

Fun deck to play, contains:

-A lot of ways to special summon spellcasters monsters.

-Different spell cards.

The Deck Yugi used against Joey in Episode 1.

It's based on a *possible* deck that Yugi had before merging it with Grandpa's Deck (both manga and anime). Some filler cards were added that I felt made sense in this deck.

It's meant to be played before Battle City rules and I tried not to give up cards that came too much time out of newer sets. Trap cards weren't much of a thing back then, but Magical Hats was a spell pretty early on in the manga (and Spellbinding Circle was a personal pick, because it honestly made a lot of sense to exist in this deck too).

Summoned Skull was his deck's most powerful card, as stated in the original manga, so it probably was always part of Yugi's Deck (not Solomon Muto's Deck). Block Attack and Stop Defense sound like really good cards in this format (I feel like they could almost become staples there), so they were pretty useful picks.

The Deck Joey used against Yugi in Episode 1.

It's based on a *possible* deck that Joey had. The few amounts of info we had about it was that it was only made out of monsters. Some filler cards were added that I felt made sense in this deck.

It's meant to be played before Battle City rules and I tried not to give up cards that came too much time out of newer sets. Added a few monsters that were part of Fusion Monsters that he had. The last line also includes monsters that have Joey's comments in their card text (I believe that's all of them right? They were pretty funny and iconic, there's no way I'd miss them for this deck).

This was purposely made to be a weak deck, even by the standards of the rules by that time, but I had a lot of fun making it.

deck_description: Very solid and competitive deck

Based on the Deck Kaiba used to battle Yugi for the first time (Manga).

It is based on a *possible* deck that Kaiba had before the iconic duel (in the manga, Kaiba attempted to steal Yugi's Blue-Eyes by giving him a fake one; he was then challenged to Shadow Game; needless to say that it went really well for him afterwards). Some filler cards were added that I felt made sense in this deck (especially, those extra 2 "Saggi").

Without his iconic Blue-Eyes, Kaiba had 2 other well-known cards on his arsenal - Battle Ox and Megamorph.

Kaiba's name also means "Sea Horse" (or "Baby Dragon") and there's a mythical creature called "Hippocampus", a monster with the upper body of a horse and the lower one as a fish (quite litterally a Sea Horse), so no wonder one of his drops in Duel Links is actually "Tatsunootoshigo" (yeah, take a guess - it's "Seahorse" in japanese). That's also why I used a few WATER monsters in his deck. "Mystic Lamp" also refferences his future not-yet-used "La-Djinn".

His Side Deck refferences Yugi's stolen Blue-Eyes, or even Mokuba's custom "Blue-Eyes White Dragon" card (Mokuba drew one for Kaiba and gave it to him, when they were younger). I'll leave that one to interpretation.

After the banlist, Tearlaments got hit really hard. Still, it still a good engine for some fusion decks (alongside the Ishizu cards), that's why Shaddoll it's a good match with this archetype. This deck can work going first, but i'd recommend to use it going second.

deck_excerpt: Just because Chaos Ruler is banned doesn't mean this deck is unviable
deck_description:
If you've payed any attention to the OCG, you'd know this deck is being used and is quite strong. This could be due to Chaos Ruler being legal plus Tear still being the best deck in the OCG but the TCG variant of the deck (when Assault Synchron gets released) has it's own merits too.

We have 2 extra copies of Bystial Magnamhut, an extremely strong crackback tool for your turn 3. We also have an extra copy of E-tele which gives the consistency of the P.U.N.K package a bit more of a boost. Lastly, we have slightly different chain block rules. in the OCG, you can't chain block using cards in your hand while in the TCG you can. This means every single bystial on turn 2/3 is a chain block and E-tele is a chain block.

While the loss of Chaos Ruler is quite a hit to this deck's consistency and ceiling, losing the extra level 8 for rank 8 plays and the search + mill is devestating, Jam Drive Dragon is still really useful and strong.

If you want to remove the extra tools of finding Assault Synchron then you can use the P.U.N.K field spell for some extra draws. If you were to get rid of anything for the P.U.N.K field spell, I'd recommend removing On Your Marks, Get Set, DUEL! as it's a continuous spell meaning MST can negate it.

I think this deck is going to still be really strong, despite the different meta climate we're in and how we dont have Chaos Ruler. I wouldn't be surprised if this deck is at the very least tier 2 when Assault Synchron releases.

deck_excerpt: We live in a godless world
deck_description:
For Fire Fist monsters, we are playing 3 Dragon, 3 Elephant, 1 Buffalo, 3 Rooster, 3 Bear, and 3 Gorilla. For Tri-Brigades, we are playing 3 Fraktall, 2 Kerass, 2 Kitt, and 3 Nerval.

For Spell/Traps: 1 Domei, 3 Tenki, 3 Fire Fortress atop Liang Peak, 3 Tensu, 3 Tri-Brigade Roar, 1 Sinto, and 1 Tri-Brigade Revolt.

In our Extra Deck, we have 1 Gladiator Beast Domitianus and 1 Gladiator Beast Tamer Editor. If you get 10 counters on Liang Peak, you can use it to Summon Tamer Editor who summons Domitianus for a free monster negate. 1 Abyss Dweller and 1 Number 106: Giant Hand. If you have seen the MBT video where this Deck was in action, they played Chakanine and Drident, but since Drident is banned, we have to use other Rank 4's. 3 Tiger King. You will need all 3 of them to set up your Fire Formation Spell/Traps as well as Summon Fire Fists from Deck by destroying it with Bear 3 times. 2 Shuraig. 1 Apollousa. 1 Bearbrumm. You are never hard making Bearbrumm until you side in cards to go more Tri-Brigade-orientated, but you can still send it to the GY with Roar in order to search Revolt. 1 Ferrijit. 1 Double Dragon Lords. 2 Brotherhood of the Fire Fist - Eagle. This card is just absolutely stupid as it allows you to use all of the Fire Fist effects for free and it can dump Buffalo for a free Summon. 

We are siding 1 Gladiator Beast Heraklinos which can replace Domitianus if you know your opponent is playing a more Spell/Trap heavy Deck. The rest is mainly going second cards like Evenly Matched and Dark Ruler No More. The others are cards you can side in to play more of a standard Tri-Brigade Deck by siding out the Bears and the Gorillas and the Liang Peaks.

Full combo is access to the Fraktall line as well as Rank 4 access with access to Fire Fist Bear. If you have Dragon and another Fire Fist, you can discard the extra Fire Fist for Kerass and get out Eagle and use Dragon to Summon back the Fire Fist you discarded. If you have Elephant, you can discard some other Beast, Beast Warrior, or Winged Beast for Kerass, make Eagle, and Normal Elephant to get out another Fire Fist from hand. Then, if you have any Fire Formation on field, you can use Eagle to return it to hand to dump Buffalo from Deck for a Level 4 body. Either way, you want Eagle on field along with 3 Fire Fist monsters, one of them being Bear and the others being any Level 4. The two Level 4's make Tiger King who sets Liang Peak. You then use Bear to pop Tiger King to get a Gorilla and a Bear from Deck. Your spent Bear and Gorilla make another Tiger King who sets Sinto. Bear destroys it again and you summon another Gorilla and Bear. Make another Tiger King who sets Domei, Tensu, or Tenki (whichever you don't have). Bear destroys it and it Summons 2 Dragons from Deck. Link off some stuff for something like Ferrijit or Apollousa in order to clear the field. The first Dragon summons back Tiger King and the other Summons back Bear. The two Dragons make a Rank 4 like Dweller or Giant Hand to clear the field again. Then, you can use Bear to pop Tiger King again for 2 Fraktall. At this point, you can Xyz or Link Summon another monster to clear the board. Fraktall banish 2 to summon Double Dragon Lords. From there, you can continue Linking off to clear the board. Here, you can continue extending with Tensu or Buffalo (if it is still in GY), or if you have 10 counters on Liang Peak, you can Summon Tamer Editor who Summons Domitianus or Heraklinos. If you have Tri-Brigade Roar during this whole thing, you can set it as a monster negate or use it to send Bearbrumm to grab Revolt.

Combo: 1 Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi or Superheavy Samurai Bike and any VS name (I will be using Vanquish Soul - Panthera)

 

-Panthera Specials herself,

-Wakaushi effect places Superheavy Samurai Monk Warrior Big Benkei on the scale summoning itself,

-Benkei adds Superheavy Samurai Soulhorns which equips and special summons itself,

- Wakaushi and Horns into Angelica, Princess of Noble Arms which also puts Wakaushi back to the scales

-Angelica adds The Noble Arms Museum which adds "Infernoble Arms - Durendal" 

-Durendal targets Angelica which sends Vanquish Soul - Razen and summons Infernoble Knight Captain Roland from your ED

 -Panthera into Rock of Vanquisher which adds Razen, Pendulum or Normal Razen adding Vanquish Soul - Dr. Madlove which on summon will add Vanquish Soul Dust Devil or Vanquish Soul Continue (I will be adding Continue),

- Razen and Roland into Infernoble Knight Emperor Charles which is equipped with roland and then linked into Charlemagne ,

-equip Charles to him and use Museum to special summon the equipped Charles, continue target Razen

-XYZ him and Madlove into Tellarknight Ptolemaeus which then becomes Stellarknight Constellar Diamond .
Fun deck for locals and friends. Have not tried in a serious setting but have won many games with this build. Idea came from Youtube searching.

deck_excerpt: Danger Dark World cute anime girls
deck_description: HI DAVE

Use battery man d to protect giant Spright until you can get summer summoner out to get material for appollusa and then AA zeus use shooting code talker to break their board If you are desparate hold off using mannequin cat and sky calvalry until you can bring out appolsusa and Mekk knight

Going first:

- Opening Keeper of Dragon Magic and no Branded Fusion:

Normal summon Keeper, search Instant Fusion, fusion into Predaplant Ambulomelides, effect search for Predaplant froge, second effect tributing Ambulomelides to special Predaplant Darlington Cobra, effect to search Fusion Deployment. Deploy Dark Magician, use froge to fusion Dragoon. That's 4 summons, you'll be able to stop Ash or Nibiru if played after your Branded fusion.

- Opening Keeper but no Branded fusion:

Normal Keeper, search Instant Fusion, fusion Ambulomelides, use effect search Predaplant froge, second effect tributing Keeper to summon Cobra, Cobra effect to search Branded Fusion, at this point you can use froge to fusion into Predaplant Dragostapelia, this won't protect you from Ash or Nibiru, but at least gives you an extra interruption which is nice. You can opt to not search Branded Fusion and go Fusion Deployment for Fallen of Albaz, and then use froge to fusion into Lubellion, or even Mirrorjade straight away.

- Opening Aluber/Branded Fusion, no Keeper

Search for Branded Fusion, play as normal, if Branded Fusion in hand, Aluber can search Branded Lost, Branded in Red, Branded in White, whichever works best. Instant Fusion in hand can be used for Millenium-Eyes Restrict to protect you from Ash and other hand traps.

Branded Fusion Combos:

If going first, assuming first round and you haven't sided, play it sending Albaz and:

- Mercourier for Rindbrumm if you have Branded in White (use Branded in White to go into Lubellion, getting a Mercourier search in the process, generally grabbing Albion the Shrouded Dragon)

- Tragedy for Lubellion for Branded in Red or Branded Banishment follow-up next turn (Tragedy searches Ad Libitum, Lubellion into Mirrorjade, use Mirrorjade on himself, sending Albion, end phase Albion set Branded in Red (for Proskenion if you can, or generally Quaeritis to protect you from attacks, Ad Lib effect to bring back Mirrorjade, Tragedy searching Aluber for follow-up next turn) or Branded Banishment for disruption, if you go for this route, make sure you have another target other than Mirrorjade because you won't be able to bring him back with Ad Libitum.

If going first, having sided, sending Albaz and:

- Disciple of Ra straight to Albion, into Lubellion, into Mirrorjade, use effect to get Expulsion. Only do this if you have another monster to send to GY or banish, for example, having used aluber or kitt to search and then targeting either with Mirrorjade after your fusions resolve.

- Jinzo to Lubellion, etc. against trap heavy decks. Same logic as above.

- Tragedy for Lubellion for Branded in Red setup but for Masquerade if the matchup calls for it.

Going second:

- Having Fusion Deployment to go straight into Albaz is a nice option to get rid of something from the opponent's board, you can search it with Keeper line. Normal summon Albaz works as well.

- You have Imperm and Ash for hand traps.

If you have sided:

- Contact "C" for "hand traps"

- Super Polimerization can use Mudragon of the Swamp, Predaplant Dragostapelia or Starving Venom Fusion Dragon depending on the matchup. This is also searchable with Keeper line.
Going second Scareclaw deck
ki

Try getting Dragoon out asap using branded fusion or any other way, even using bystials. You can also get the monster negate of Mechaba by linking Aleister into Artemis and then using Invocation or, if you manage to, summon Dragoon and then at the end of your main phase summon Invoked Caliga, this way you'll negate the only effect your opponent can activate that turn. Also, Dragoon doesn't get destroyed after Eternal Soul leaves the field so don't worry about it. There's a big set of hand traps so you can stop your opponent in time. Or, if you happen to have Piercing the Darkness in hand, summon Dark Magician the dragon knight and search for Eternal Soul, it's unbeatable, literally. That's all, I think.

deck_excerpt: An interesting spin on one of the most fun decks ever printed
deck_description:
This deck aims to end on AFD, ABC-Dragon Buster, and Transfurlmine. Transfurlmine can also set Magikey Unlocking, which is a Spell/Trap negate and it also can set up Transfurlmine in some scenarios which you haven't already used his effect to destroy on summon

Theory

The main theory is that you can use Advanced Ritual Art or Magikey Maftea (given you have a normal monster on field) to send Baby Dragon and Flamvell Guard to the graveyard to ritual summon Batosbuster. Batosbuster will add Magikey World, searching Mafteal. You can reveal Mafteal, get an extra normal summon, and then Summon both him and Special Summoning the Baby Dragon from Graveyard. Mafteal has a restriction which makes him only able to be used as material for a "Magikey" monster, but batosbuster does NOT have this restriction, meaning you can use both it and Baby Dragon to make Ancient Fairy Dragon, allowing you to pop world and add Union Hangar to do the main ABC combo. We're only running 1 of each of the ABC pieces, which can be garnets, but luckily Magikey World allows you to search Maftea and put a piece back into the deck to smooth out some bad hands.

Breakdown

We're running 2 of the Baby Dragons and Flamevell Guards, this is because you usually dont want to draw one so you can send them off of ARA, but it's also ok to draw them so that you can normal summon them and use Maftea to send the other from deck for batosbuster. This deck doesn't need it's normal summon, so we're also running Manju of the Ten Thousand Hands to add a missing combo piece to our hand while also getting extra material on field. A really neat interaction is using ABC-Dragon Buster's effect to summon the 3 pieces from the graveyard. Assuming you have a discard in hand, you can use AFD to pop Union Hangar and add Magikey World, using it to search Garesglasser and Maftea while putting that discard fodder back into your deck. You can then use Maftea to summon Garesglasser with the 2 ABC pieces, because either way you can just banish the ones from the graveyard to get to ABC-Dragon Buster again. In theory, we can also make Tellarknight Ptolemaeus which can detach 3 materials to rank up into Cyber Dragon Nova, then into Infinity for an omni-negate/removal, and banish all 3 pieces from the grave to make ABC-Dragon buster.

Side Deck Explanation

We're hilariously able to side deck Twin Long Rods #2 and Jerry Beans Man. Because Baby Dragon can be a flex slot for any Level 3 Normal Monster, we can side it out for these cards to make Transfurlmine more effective against Water/Earth decks. We're of course siding 3 Nibiru and Eclipse against Kashtira. The 3 Cosmic Cyclone is just because Anti-Spell Fragrance is running around, and that turns off our entire strategy, so we need an answer to that (and other floodgates if nessecary). Since this deck doesn't need it's normal summon, we can also side Jinzo just because Labrynth is also really popular this format.

Hope you enjoy this deck! It's a lot of fun.

This deck is one version of how we think Duke Devlin might try and win using Musical Sumo Dice Games. Use the Inifintrack Engine to play Dice Games, and prevent it's destruction. Hopefully use the traps to force the battle phase and manupliate the dice roll so that Dice Games hoovers up River Stormer to win.

Part 1 Duke Devlin Deck - Modernised part 1 2023 - YGOPRODeck

This deck combines Musical Sumo Dice Games with the Ninja engine, in a deck aiming to mimic the strategies used by Duke Devlin in the anime. Use the Ninja cards to disrupt and build advantage. XYZ 2 Meizen to play Dice Games, and use your advantage to hoover up monsters to win via Dice Games, or attack directly at your opponents heart...i mean life....points.

This deck is focused on control; Psychic End Crusher can be used as a option going first or second, since many decks might have a hard time getting him out of the board (Personally, i'd rather go for the Shirakusai quick effect to synchro summon Amazing Dragon, but any off the options are fine). On this version of the deck I've tried to include the other P.U.N.K. spells that usually don't see play and, well, they're ocasional, but not bad. Ashura King is in the extra deck; he is not a consistent summon (mostly because at points were I could summon him, Apollousa was a option too).
