deck_name: Doodle Beast Dinosaur (Master Duel April 9th Banlist)
deck_description:
Doodle Beast Dinosaur is a mild variation on the Dinosaur deck. It utilizes the Doodle Beast cards. Their monsters, "Doodle Beast - Stego" and "Doodle Beast - Tyranno" enable a point of disruption on your opponent's turn. By using the Doodle Beast - Tyranno's effect in hand to quick effect, tribute summon it to your field by tributing 1 Dinosaur monster you control. Its trigger effect on summon lets you non-target destroy one monster on the field. I'm also utilizing "True King Lithosagym, The Disaster" as the Doodle Beasts are both Earth monsters, enabling more ways into Lithosagym's summon to banish three different cards from your opponent's Extra Deck.

 

True King Combo

Your True King Combo is a combo that uses the effect of "True King Lithosagym, The Disaster" to start out our turn. It's a decently powerful combo that can end with a fair amount of powerful monsters on the board if the right cards are destroyed for its effect to summon.

True King Lithosagym, The Disaster Effect > Destroy Babycerasaurus + 1 other Monster > Summon Lithosagym > Babycerasaursus Mandatory Effect > Summon Souleating Oviraptor from Deck.

From this point, the other monster you destroyed will come into play. If you destroyed another Dinosaur monster that isn't one of the recruiters, you can use Oviraptor to add Miscellaneousaurus to your hand. *(If you've already drawn into Misc you can add Doodle Beast - Stego instead to summon it to add and discard "Doodlebook - Uh uh uh!".)* Activating Miscellaneousaurus's effect from hand, and then banishing it and your other non-recruiter Dinosaur to summon Babycerasaurus. Summoning this Babycerasaurus will allow us to use Souleating Oviraptor's second effect to destroy it and summon the other one from the GY. On the mandatory effect of Babycerasaurus we will summon Animadorned Archosaur. Archosaur's effect will trigger to destroy the Babycerasaurus summoned from your GY to add Double Evolution Pill and activate the second Babycerasaurus. This Babycerasaurus can summon out one of our Scap Raptors *(Should we have not drawn into all available copies in the deck.) Alternatively you can summon out Giant Rex.

Moving forward, I will illustrate paths that can be taken with both of these options. As a refresher, our current board would look as follows: 1 Lithosagym, 1 Oviraptor, 1 Animadorned, either 1 Scrap Raptor or Giant Rex, and the potential Doodle Beast - Stego.

With this current field, we can start digging into our Extra Deck to develop our end board. If we have Scrap Raptor we could use its effect, destroying our Animadorned to give us another Normal Summon of a Scrap Monster. We could then use the Scrap Raptor and the Lithosagym to make Scrap Wyvern, for which I will go over the combo later on.

If we have Giant Rex we can use Oviraptor and Giant Rex to make "Evolzar Dolkka". Alternatively, because we used Animadorned Archosaur's effect to add Double Evolution Pill, we could use the Lithosagym and Giant Rex to make "I:P Masquerena". This would give us follow-up during the opponent's turn, and get the Giant Rex in the GY to be banished with Lithosagym off of Double Evolution Pill to summon Ultimate Conductor Tyranno from our deck. This will trigger the Giant Rex's effect to special summon itself back to the field because it was banished. If we have Stego on field we can use it as the 1 card tribute effect of the Doodle Beast - Tyranno in our hand that we added off of Doodlebook - Uh uh uh!'s GY effect on our opponent's turn.

 

Scrap Combo

Your Scrap Combo enables your Synchro plays. By utilizing the trio of Scrap Raptor, Scrap Chimera, and Scrap Wyvern, you can be presented with a lot of summoning power to push out Synchro monsters from your Extra Deck to make your finished board that much stronger.

To start, Scrap Raptor can destroy a monster you control, giving you an additional Normal Summon for Scrap monsters. Scrap Raptor can also search out a non-tuner Scrap monster from your deck if it's destroyed by the effect of a Scrap monster. This effect easily plays into itself as Scrap Raptor can be its own target for its first effect. You're searching out Scrap Chimera with this effect, and Scrap Chimera can Special Summon a Scrap tuner monster. While Chimera can't be used as a Synchro material for anything other than a Scrap monster, it can still act as generic Link material. Scrap Wyvern is a Link-2 monster that needs two monsters including a Scrap monster to summon. It can bring back a Scrap monster from your GY to your field and then it destroys one card you control. Its other effect lets you Special Summon a Scrap monster from deck when a Scrap monster is destroyed while its on the field and then destroy any 1 card on the field, non-targeting. Your combo in action will look something like this:

Scrap Raptor Effect > Destroy itself to give additional Normal Summon > Scrap Raptor Effect to Add Scrap Chimera > Normal Summon Scrap Chimera > Scrap Chimera Effect to Revive Scrap Raptor > Link Scrap Raptor + Chimera into Scrap Wyvern > Wyvern Effect to Revive Scrap Raptor then Destroying Scrap Raptor > Scrap Chimera Trigger Effect to Special Summon another Scrap Raptor from Deck.

Suppose you refer back to the above True King Combo -- we ended on a fair number of monsters on our board with that. If we go through that same example and have a Scrap Raptor instead of Giant Rex, we could use the Scrap Raptor to destroy the Animadorned Archosaur and then use Scrap Raptor and Lithosagym to make Wyvern. This play would allow us to use the Wyvern to bring back the Scrap Raptor and destroy it, triggering both Wyvern and Raptor's effects at the same time and allowing you to Chain Block. This lets you insulate one of the cards on the chain from something like "Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring".

Because this combo produces a level 4 Tuner, you have a couple of options to play with in the Extra Deck. I've gone with two options in this deck: Borreload Savage Dragon as it can act as a negate against almost any card, and Geomathmech Final Sigma because it can be made off of a Doodle Beast - Tyranno and a Scrap Raptor, and it's funny. Feel free to play around with other options.

 

Dinosaur Combo

The Dinosaur combo is your main show. It's what is going to give you access to almost all of your deck, and let you do very powerful plays that end on a variety of monsters that act as disruption. Your main playmaker is Souleating Oviraptor. It can add a Dinosaur from your deck to your hand and it can revive a dino from your GY be destroying a different dino on your field. I'll go over what a combo with Oviraptor will generally look like:

Summon Souleating Oviraptor and Activate Effect to Search > Add Miscellaneousaurus > Activate Miscellaneousaurus > Activate Miscellaneousaurus in the GY > Summon Animadorned Archosaur > Animadorned Archosaur Effect Destroy a Dinosaur *(Optimally you want to destroy either Babycerasaurus or Petiteranodon with the effect of Animadorned Archosaur so you can get an additional summon out of them)* > Add Double Evolution Pill.

If we start Oviraptor + Miscellaneousaurus, Oviraptor + Fossil Dig, or Miscellaneousaurus + Fossil Dig, you can use the Oviraptor to search out one of your recruiter Dinosaurs to use for the destruction effect of Animadorned Archosaur we'll summon off of Miscellaneousaurus.

If we have a recruiter Dinosaur like Babycersaurus we can destroy it with Animadorned's effect to add the Double Evolution Pill. The Babycerasaurus's effect can summon out a Petiteranodon. You can then proceed to use your established Oviraptor to destroy the Petiteranodon and summon the Babycerasaurus back from the GY. Petiteranodon's effect will activate, letting you summon Scrap Raptor from the deck.

In this current position, we can use the Scrap Raptor's effect to destroy the Babycersaurus to gain an additional Normal Summon of a Scrap monster. Then the Babycerasaurus can summon out either Giant Rex to act as an extender. By using it and Scrap Raptor to make Scrap Wyvern, or to summon the second Petiteranodon to destroy at the end of the Scrap Wyvern's last effect to summon out a Dinowrestler Pankratops from the deck. This acts as disruption for the opponent's next turn. *(Refer to above Scrap Combo for more details.)

There are uses for each option. Summoning out Giant Rex gives you the ability to later use it as one of the banished materials for Double Evolution Pill or even Ultimate Conductor Tyranno if you drew into it. Giant Rex could then summon itself back out to then be made into an Evolzar Dolkka or an Evolzar Laggia with the Souleating Oviraptor.

 

Tech Choices and Final Thoughts

To elucidate some of my Extra Deck choices, I will go over why I've decided to play specific choices and suggest alternatives. To start I've decided to play Linkuriboh + Secure Gardna because in some scenarios it can be used to turn Animadorned Archosaur into a 1-card Ultimate Conductor Tyranno by ising the Animadorned to summon Linkuriboh and then use the Linkuriboh to summon Secure Gardna. This lets the Double Evolution Pill banish the Secure Gardna + Animadorned to summon UCT from deck.

Likewise I'm playing Bagooska for if there's ever a hand I have where I can't do too much beyond summoning 2 level 4s that don't get the combo fully going if the rest of the hand isn't optimal. It also has some niche utility in games where you can link climb into Accesscode Talker to close out the game while keeping your opponent's on-field monsters at bay.

I'm playing Linguriboh as a way to out Knightmare Corruptor Iblee. Spright players can take advantage of Knightmare Corruptor Iblee by having it special summon to your side of the field, locking you out of special summoning anything except Link monsters. Spright players will try to set this up with a I:P Masquerena as a way to make Knightmare Unicorn and bounce your normal summon back to hand, stopping you from making a Link-2 with your normal summon and Iblee. The Linguriboh gives you a safe way to remove it from your field with no commitment attached. It also has the benefit of being a trap card negate, which could come up against something like Infinite Impermanence or Evenly Matched.

I'm playing Abyss Dweller as tool to shut down GY centralized decks. It can easily shut down a lot of different archetypes and is farily accessible with the amount of level 4 monsters we have the ability to summon out.

Other choices could include cards like Knightmare Phoenix or Tornado Dragon as a way to destroy Spells/Traps. Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder can be played as a payoff for attacking with an XYZ monster giving you a quick effect board wipe. PSY-Framelord Omega can be played as a way to rip cards out of your opponent's hand, as well as being able to return itself and another card in the GY back to the deck. Underworld Goddess of the Closed World can be utilized as a way to get rid of big monsters with a lot of protection on your opponent's side of the field.

The Dinosaur deck is a fun toolboxy deck that has a lot of power to do a lot of powerful plays. Its extra deck can be tinkered with a lot to the pilot's preferences. The main deck offers a nice amount of versaility in summoning boss monsters as well. With cards like Ultimate Conductor Tyranno, Dinowrestler Pankratops, and Doodle - Beast Tyranno the deck has a fair amount of big monsters that can close out games. The intoruduction of the Doodle Beast cards can help act as a bridge for some combos depending on what your opening hand looks like. It gives you slightly more options to go into through your combo.

I hope you enjoy this deck and always feel free to try out whatever you like and play it however you feel comfortable. See this sort of as a starting pad to work off of. I hope you've found this profile helpful and informative and happy dueling.

deck_name: Scrap Dino Ogdoadic Transcendrake Apr23 Format
deck_excerpt: Complete guide to playing Scrap Dino with new Transcendrake generic support
deck_description:
Theory about new archetype Transcendrake:

Of the 7 cards revealed, the ones that have practical application are the Spell and the Lv6 Tuner because they add new 2 card combo to the deck. Archetype monsters have the mechanic of needing Normal Monsters to activate certain effects and using Normal Monsters in 2023 is not an option.

The archetype's Fusion is a good card but nothing worth having to use Vanilla and Cross Sheep to use it. Of course, there is the argument that it has great synergy with Tyranno, being able to be destroyed and return to the field and add a follow up to the hand and still destroy cards, but even so, this is only consistent in the ideal scenario where you don't get hand traps.

The same goes for RANK-6 that can recycle from banished zone Miscellaneousaurus which is just an Ok card since the deck already has efficient ways to recycle the banned Miscellaneousaurus as Psy-Frame Omega and yet the vanilla needed to do it is the worst possible because must be lv6.

Finally all moves involving this archetype lose to Nibiru, the Primal Being among other hand traps mainly in the moves of the Scrap Raptor engine, lock you in certain types of extra deck monsters that don't help you much when you go second since they are end board cards and not field-breaking cards in addition to the fact that you have an extra deck worsened by using cards that only make sense if the combo passes completely without taking interactions like Cross-Sheep and RANK-6.

This again means using the Dinosaur deck in the wrong way. I've already said in other deck profiles that there's no point in making beautiful combo plays with Apollousa + Savage etc to lose to several hand traps and on top of that not having any follow up if the opponent uses Dark Ruler No More and cleans his field. It's always better if you make combos that have more resilience to hand traps, continue to have great interactions and have a lot of follow up.

 

Positive points of using Spell and the new Tuner lv6:

1 - The Spell greatly increases the consistency of the deck because it plays the same role as the Dragonic Diagram, but I believe in a better way. Since now using at least 3 Babycerasaurus and 1 Petiteranodon is mandatory in the deck to be able to start plays without spending Normal Summon.

2 - The spell does not need to add Lv6 so in many combos it is better to add Scrap Raptor which is a great Normal Summon and makes a combo with Lost World and Miscellaneousaurus.

3 - Regarding the Lv6 Tuner, its main advantages are that you can create a Lost World token and protect yourself from the target of cards without spending the Normal Summon. This whether going first or second is great for starting plays against target interactions.

4 - As he is a Lv6 tuner along with any Lv4 monster he makes Baronne de Fleur which is the best Synchro-10 in the game and brings a lot of versatility to the deck both by denying cards and destroying as well which improves the combos going first as well. Just for that fact the card is already very good because Baronne de Fleur means forcing at least 2 interactions from the opponent.

5 - By indication, the combos involving Lost World and Xeno Meteoros as an extender have the synergy of you being able to access Knightmare Cerberus to destroy the Token on the opponent's side and make a Full Combo. It basically replaces the Doodle Beast in the deck by doing the same role only much better.

6 - These cards have very good synergies in the deck and are very viable in all possible versions of Dinosaur.

 

///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////So after saying what I think about the supports, let's see in practice the use of the new archetype in the Dinosaur deck:

 

For example you can do the following combos:

Spell + Oviraptor = Spell + Babycerasaurus/Petiteranodon

One of the main novelties is that you can easily access Baronne de Fleur which means it is a protection against hand traps in addition to being an extender for your combos going first because it can destroy any card on the field, whether it is Babycerasaurus or Token on the opponent's field.

 

The Spell + Miscellaneousaurus combo is also possible and pretty much the same combo as Miscellaneousaurus + Scrap Raptor.

 

The Spell + Scrap Raptor combo brings good possibilities going second by accessing Baronne de Fleur which is a card that manages to force at least 2 interactions from the opponent since it destroys and negates cards in addition to being a follow up in the Standby Phase.

 

The combo involving you Special Summoning the Lv6 Tuner and doing LINK-2 Knightmare Cerberus or Fur Hire to destroy the token on the opponent's side to trigger Lost World and start playing is really good.

Just the fact that you can Special Summon the Lv6 Tuner along with your normal summon with Lost World activated on the field allows you to play even after being hand trapped in normal as an Infinite Impermanence. In case if the card he denies is the Oviraptor you can make Baronne de Fleur and destroy the token. If it's the Scrap Raptor you can continue playing normally by doing the Scrap Wyvern. These combos have a weaker end board but are already something better than being hand trapped in Normal Summon and simply passing the turn.

 

//////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////RESUME:

The deck is very consistent with the new supports whether in the pure version or with the Ogdoadic. This spell can make you start moves without spending your normal summon among other great synergies like throwing bricks from the hand deck to the gy.

I don't doubt if they can use an engine involving this spell in other decks because it's practically a lv6 extender tuner that enters the field and allows you mainly to make Synchro-10 plays being the second best option besides Baronne de Fleur or Bystial Des Pair that It's a great card in the Chaos deck.

 

One detail that I noticed in the pure version is that you have a lot of consistency spell cards but you don't have space for tech cards so that's why I created the 60-card version that has the role of adding more go secund cards so you have chances going second.

 

////////////////////////////////////////NEW COMBOS WITH TRANSCENDRAKE CARDS:

complete the continuation of the URL on the website duelingbook.com/

Combo 5: (Ground Xeno + Giant Rex) + Oviraptor

Possibility to make Exciton Knight and Baronne de Fleur easily.

This combo is interesting to demonstrate the advantages that you can have with the Ground Xeno spell even when you open with your bricks, be it the Giant Rex or the level 8 monsters of the Ogdoadic to play them to the GY having some better utility than in the hand .

 

Combo 6: Lost World + Ground Xeno + Random Card

Here the existing synergy refers to you being able to create the Token on the opponent's field without using your Normal Summon by summoning Xeno Meteors, which means that he will no longer be able to target your monsters so you can turn off several interactions without having to Normal Summon what is excellent.

 

Combo 7: Xeno Meteors + Doodle Beast in the Opponent Turn

Xeno Meteors enters the field when any card is destroyed so if your opponent destroys their own cards you will also be able to put it on the field being a monster with good ATK status and TUNER threatening to make Baronne de Fleur on your next turn.

Even with the help of Doodle Beast it also becomes interaction because the effect of Doodle Beast stays alive even on turn 0 of the game which is very interesting.

Xeno Meteoros is very interesting. It could have a better effect that doesn't involve Normal Monster but just the fact that it can be searched even with Fossil Dig and has many qualities already makes it an excellent card in the deck.

deck_description:
The SHS cards are really something man

It's hilarious when the starters are also the combo pieces, and when all the combo pieces are all starters. It's also funny that it has no garnets and about 1 real brick.

Oh and a free pendulum scale which allows you to summon other cards like the PUNKs, speaking of..

 

The PUNK engine is so ridiculously flexible.

You can play it as a backup, or pendulum summon them with the new SHS cards. All while plusing to infinitum with a Ghost ogre and a boss monster that bounce cards and also summon your other PUNKs in the GY for the next turn.

What the PUNKs do to this deck is allow it to have a grind game which the SHS lack since that archetype is almost pure gas.

Since you only need 1 card to start the whole SHS combo (Bike, Soulpiercer, Prodigy), you can sometimes draw those cards while activating Session which I find Funny. 

Oh and you have access to Psychic End Punisher.

Bystials

They're are played since it allows for easy level 10 synchros and because Dis Pater Can summon Omega in the Banish zone so you can handloop twice which is funny and extra if anything.

Hmmmm...

I guess the downsides are is that your sideboarding is pretty limited, and you don't really have a good out to FLOODGATES except Eccentrick.

The FTK version of SHS is good but I think this one is just a lot more safe and flexible since the 2 archetypes can function well seperately. But If they're together then your boards are almost unbeatable.

deck_excerpt: Flap your beautiful and heroic wings to strike the enemy at the speed of light! Synchro Summon! Appear! Level 7! Clear Wing Synchro Dragon!
deck_description:
Deck Master - Speedroid Ultra Hound

The plan is simple. Summon the doggo from the Deck Master Zone to send the trap card, Speedroid Dupligate, to the GY then link both those two cards to link summon the Rubber Band Shooter. The rest from there is all up to you and your hand. No matter what, do not stop fusion- I mean, do not stop synchro summoning!

In more extensive detail, the Windwitches also consist of WIND monsters both for both the main and extra deck so setting up a quick Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon can enable the one-card Ultra Hound combo to access more synchro monsters to end off on before your opponent can even play. Miscellaneous WIND monsters such as The Tricky or Red Hared Hasty Horse serve as self-explanatory extenders to make the higher level synchro monsters. 

*Note that other notable Speedroid monsters such as Terrortop or Marble Machine are also great alternatives to serve as the deck master instead of Ultra Hound to perform one-card combos. The latter is just one example and does not have to be relied on 100% of the time to get the engine running.

deck_excerpt: Pure P.U.N.K, updated for the April 2023 Masterduel meta, featuring "Instant Contact."
deck_description:
Since its inception, PUNK has gained notoriety as an engine, enabling 1 card OTKs, Halq/Auroradon combo without normal summon and etc. Competitively, PUNK was only viable as an engine smushed into goodstuff decks – it was never good “pure.”

This all changes with the release of the "Sprites of Miracle" pack in Masterduel, with two new ridiculously strong PUNK support cards printed in the set! The field spell “Extreme Session” is an extender AND pot of greed, all in one card! Dragon Drive searches any level 3 psychic tuner on summon (including Ghost Ogre) and is also an extender if your opponent chains to your PUNK effect!

Extreme Session and Dragon Drive enable a mass handtrap playstyle for PUNK, allowing it to still fight through board wipes like the all-too-common Dark Ruler No More! This support granted the previously unfit engine to top competitively – all on its own archetypal legs!


Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

Pure P.U.N.K, updated for the April 2023 Masterduel meta.
 
The most recent winner in the Duelist Cup was a PUNK player! Their cool, creative addition to the PUNK builds was the inclusion of "Instant Contact."
 
Instant Contact summons level 5/7 bodies to the field for additional extension into more synchro plays - allowing PUNK to more easily make strong boss monsters like Dragite, Baronne and Chengying!

This deck is a variant of my "Pure PUNK" deck guide I made last year, so If you want a complete guide with all the combos, tips and gameplant, visit my Pure PUNK article linked here.
 
Small World is amazing since it replaces a brick in your hand to add one of your starters! The following are Small World search combos:
  • Activate Small World -> Any Orochi/Effect Veiler -> D.D. Crow -> Obtain PUNK Ogre Dance (starts PUNK combo line)
  • Activate Small World -> Psy-Frame Gamma/Effect Veiler -> Nibiru -> Obtain PUNK Foxy Tune (starts PUNK combo line)
  • Activate Small World -> Ash Blossom/Ghost Ogre -> PUNK Deer Note -> Any Level 3 Punk Tuner (starts PUNK combo line)
  • Activate Small World -> Any Level 3 Punk Tuner -> Effect Veiler -> Ash Blossom/Ghost Belle (I usually do this if I have all combo pieces already)
There are more Small World combos out in this deck and that can be included in, but these are the ones I primarily use. Feel free to experiment and add more!

With the disappearance of Halqifibrax, this is Pure PUNK's standard combo:
  1. Summon Ze Amin. Activate effect to search for Foxy Tune. 
  2. Activate Foxy Tune's effect to summon from deck Sharakusai. 
  3. Activate Sharakusai's effect to fusion summon Ze Amin + Sharakusai -> Rising Carp. 
  4. Activate Rising Carp's effect to summon Wa Gon and Deer Note from deck. 
  5. Activate Wa Gon's effect to search for Extreme Session. Activate Extreme Session. 
  6. Synchro Wa Gon + Deer Note -> Dragon Drive. 
  7. CL1 Dragon Drive to search Madame Spider from deck. CL2 Deer Note to summon Sharakusai from GY. On resolution, Extreme Session draws you 1 card. 
  8. Activate Extreme Session's effect summon Madame Spider from hand
  9. Activate Madame Spider's effect to search for your PUNK trap of choice (I personally prefer Nashiwari Surprise). On resolution, Extreme Session draws you 1 card. 
This is the standard Pure PUNK combo. This combo grants you a bounce of up to 4 cards on the field with Sharakusai's quick synchro into Amazing Dragon on the opponent's turn. Amazing Dragon is also follow-up for next turn, since it generates resources by summoning any PUNK from the GY. You also have a pop any card/negate monster of with your PUNK trap. Finally, Extreme Session drew you two cards, which may be hand traps, or follow-up for next turn.

Note that if you have extenders like Instant Contact and Ascended of Thunder, you can make Dragite, Baronne, Chengying or Psychic End Punisher.

deck_excerpt: Fluffal and Tearlaments is a deck with fun gameplay to play
deck_description:
Fluffal Tearlaments is a deck that I got off the ground a little while ago, but I was already thinking about the possibility of testing it even before the banlist that killed Tearlaments.

This deck was made with the intention of improving Fluffal's end board which in the pure version usually makes Apollousa + Toadally Awesome + Cruel Whale on the opponent's turn and sometimes I:P Masquerena.

Here you access more versatile interactions against the opponent due to the Tearlaments engine. Its end board is more resilient to blind second cards. You no longer have multiple negates spread out on a single card like Apollousa and during the combo you use your main deck monsters in a more efficient way to make extra deck monsters whether link or fusion or xyz summon.

In summary here you have several ways to use all the cards that enter the field by special to make interactions different from an Apollousa.

 

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

Below I will leave all the test hands with the deck I made to demonstrate why certain combos were chosen. There is no single way to play with Fluffal, there are combinations of cards that make your gamestate advance which includes drawing cards, discarding cards by effect or by cost to the GY and fusion summoning while having the other mechanics mainly the link summon to help you maintain the upper hand.

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-48254370

Test Hand 1

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-48254575

Test Hand 2

You could have not used the effect of Cruel Whale and used it as material for Proxy F Magician and returned it to the Extra Deck with Frightfur Repair and that way you could use it on your next turn. That's the only big detail of this combo and it's also interesting to see if you can finish with the Spright Sprind to send Merrli to the GY and do one more interaction and together with the Abyss Dweller be one more interaction. The important thing is during the tests with the deck you see if it's really worth using Sprind instead of any other extra deck card.

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-48257138

Test Hand 3

Here at the beginning of the combo you could have left Kelbek in the lurch and sent Frightfur Fusion to the GY instead to use Scheiren eff and sent him to the GY to mill 8 which would have been more efficient. The interesting thing about this end board is that you end up with Spright Sprind on the field and Dweller so you can use Spright Sprind bounce eff having one more interaction.

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-48265533

Test Hand 4

The detail here is to make Frightfur Tiger because it's the only way to make Mudragon.

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-48266237

Disregard Dragostapelia on the field because you already used Merrli eff, but it's a card that could have been done anyway on the opponent's turn.

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-48264566

Test Hand 5

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-48257138

Test Hand 6

Cards you activated wrong: Merrli had already used it before and you have to use Repair to summon Fluffal Dog in the combo because he had already Normal Summoned it.

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-48255279

Test Hand 7

At the end of this combo you can do Spright Sprind to get one more possible interaction with the opponent.

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-48254575

Test Hand 8

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-48254575

Test Hand 9

It was not supposed to have Summoned Dragostapelia in the zone that Proxy F Magician points to in case of drawing a monster of 1000atk or less you can summon it on the opponent's turn. Another detail is that you return the Cruel Whale with Repair

 

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

And it is in this gameplay that the synergies of the deck appear because you, in this process of giving new draws and discarding cards by effect, access the Tearlaments, Ishizu, Destiny HERO, Magicians' Souls and Golden Lord engines that are necessary for you to have more play extenders and make better extra deck monsters.

That's why this Tearlaments engine is so good for giving you access to cards like Rulkallos, Spright Sprind, Dragostapelia, Mudragon that allows you to easily do the Abyss Dweller and whenever you have Beatrice on the field on the opponent's turn she becomes more an interaction sending the Tearlaments to the GY.

Not to mention that several archetype cards already work by themselves as hand traps like Edge Imp Scythe, Tearlaments Havnis, the Ishizu monsters themselves, which improves even when you go second.

 

//////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

Comments about the cards used in the main deck and the side deck that can be tested in this version:

In the main deck the Ishizu are good cards to draw when you open with two together since they have a lot of synergy between them. Polymerization using two copies is the bare minimum but three copies isn't bad in this version either.

I put a lot of side deck card options that Tearlaments is used to using, among which Time Thief Redoer and Garura stand out. The first because it detach material as an effect and can trigger Tearlaments eff and the second because it is lv6 and facilitates access to Beatrice.

Overall I'm very satisfied with the performance of this deck and it has many ways to improve when testing the deckbuild.

////////////////////////////////////////////////

The cope life of Tears post Feb 23 ban list. 

The basic combo is PUNK engine into grab ghost ogre and xyz into zombie vampire for mill four and special materials either for sprind or dharc. Hopefully mill four will lead to more mills or searchers. 

Side Note:

I might replace tear grief for metanoise, so I have a more consistent way to recycle any tears in gy. 2 Kaleido heart is just a personal preference for grind game, but you can replace with Time Thief Redoer. you can summon Baronne with Kash Tear and any lv3 tuner. Borrelsword help beat any towers and close out the game. Dugares if you can get 2 lv 4 on the field and it help fix your hand and start a combo. 

There is no consistent endboard. All endboard is RNG based on what you mill and pull.

deck_excerpt: THE SKY THE LAND THE SEA
deck_description:
A improved(?) version based on my previous ghoti melffy spright deck with the aim to improve going first plays.

Note this deck is still being tested and I'm working on the right proportions for things to flow. I'm thinking of about 45 cards but would want more hand traps and not hurting consistency. any help/suggestion would be appreciated!

used crossout as a marker to split between archetypes (if it displays correctly)

Ghoti melffy synchro v1: https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/ghoti-melffy-synchrp-315705

My previous deck has some really explosive plays during my opponents turn and is very hard to stop unless they use field wipes at the very start which is surprisingly a huge weakness after I ate a lot of lava golems, ra eggs etc in locals. 

I started to notice that the plays I can make my first turn are usually setting up plays (ss melffies at the end phase and banishing ghotis so they can explode in my opponents turn)

By adding spright into them I should be able to get more bodies on the field such as spright red/carrot, smashers to banish a ghoti, IP or some generic links to provide interuptions as well as forcing my oppoenet to deal with both my ghoti melffy line and my spright/link xyz line making my plays more solid and hard to completely interupt. The lv2 restriction from spright starters/gigantic spright matters little since the majority of my plays are in my opponents turn

Accel synchro stardust is a very interesting card and if paired with a ghoti tuner on field (ss by its own effect in the opponents turn): you can either use Accel's effect to get a stardust and synchro into Deep Beyond/Ruddy Rose or use the ghoti tuner to go into Deep Beyond. The opponent will need to spend 2 monster negates to fully stop this or face a board/grave banish. not to mention how easy it is to make Accel through the melffy searchers with pinny or hop ear.

As usual the side deck are cards that could be build into the deck for potentially more plays/consistency

deck_excerpt: That look on your opponent's face when you summon Dragoon from a DW deck is priceless
deck_description:
This deck is an improved version from the deck I made here.

Major differences:

- Fleshed out the extra deck to cover more situations. Some notable examples: Cross-Sheep is an excellent starter to add effects on subsequent Extra Deck summons. Akashic Magician when paired with Ceruli, Guru of Dark World makes for an excellent way to demolish your opponent's hand. Other cards are typical staples add extra power, negations, or protections to the extra deck.

- Removed less-than-ideal or situational main deck cards, particularly Dark World spells and traps.

- Restructured the Branded engine. Three copies of Branded Fusion proved to be unneccesary and occasionally downright bad if more than one copy is drawn. Instead, I dropped it down to one copy. Since Dark World and Danger monsters almost never normal summon, Aluber the Jester of Despia serves as the deck's only normal summon to search Braded Fusion. Aluber also can bait out negates like Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring at no detriment to the Danger Dark World engine.

- Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon added as a new major boss monster by removing some cards and adding Dark Magician. This would probably be the best target for your opponent to prevent you summoning, so it almost serves as a "spoof" engine. If you summon Dragoon, fantastic, as it's an amazing boss monster with negates and protections; if not your Dark World engine can resume without it.

- Radian, the Multidimensional Kaiju was a much needed addition to wipe opponent's "untouchable" monsters. It's Fiend type also allows Muckraker From the Underworld to summon it from grave for a decent beatstick.

- The side deck was tailored to handle more specific threats. The remaining slots can always be filled with Danger! cards for more draws and summons, facilitating further link summons. Limited staples like Called by the Grave and Harpie's Feather Duster are always helpful. Added Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring to use when necessary. Denko Sekka was added to combat backrow-heavy decks like certain Kashtira variants and Traptrix
Just a simple trap control deck with searchable floodgates really. Oh, and don't use Sea Stealth Attack on the trap monsters.

Ignore ME!

This is not my deck, but DarkArmedDuelist's. Visit the linked video for additional info.

(modified to meet my broke af budget)

The goal of this deck is to sort out some of the problems I've been having recently playing adamancipators. In the current format I feel like you have to put out a floodgate/ hard answer to the threatening decks, and while I feel like this deck has been performing great vs the tier 2 decks of the format, I wanted to push it more towards handling kash/Branded.

Goodbye the earth hex sealed fusion package, hello Aegerine turbo. 

Aegerine is like a 1 card win condition vs kash and branded, this card does absolutely everything except out rindbrum. (simply have guardian on field?)

 

But I didn't want to give up on exterio entirely, at the cost of 1 maindeck slot and 2 extra deck slots, this engine is super easy to access and can easily beat tier 2 threats competitors like traptrix and labyrinth, as well as more rogue decks like sky striker and any ritual archetype. 

There are definitely some high rolls in here, and some low rolls, but to mitigate that I have desires, signs, and even leonite.

I hope this deck is a bit better at breaking boards, even though dragite is slightly more likely to whiff.

deck_name: Greed Quasar / Colossal Fighter / Calculator infinite attack loop
deck_description:
This is a very no-brainer deck i made after seeing a video on youtube with greed quasar 5million levels and i said that "yeah i can make that without the new dark world support".....

Anyways deck revolves around using dark world dealing to yeet ceruli, ceruli discard lucent, lucent throws greed quasar FROM DECK to opponents side in attack position then you do everything in your power to end on borreload dragon and colossal fighter on your field with chicken game or pseudo space copying chicken game. +50 style points if you end up with calculator as well which can be revived with spright elf. you go to battle phase and attack to greed quasar with colossal fighter infinitely until you are satisfied with its level and attack, yoink with borreload dragon and finally attack for game either with quasar or calculator. 

A/D changer is a must cause otherwise you might have to include some infernity engine to do piercing damage or pentestag, A/D changer can turn one of our ceruli we gift our opponent to attack position. or you can use it to flip morphing jar which can be removed from the deck. Pot of Avarice and Slash draw cards are a must cause if you start with quasar you are pretty much screwed so you can recycle it with those cards after drawing ceruli and lucent and immediately throw it to opponents side for the loop.

The deck is very weak against called by and nibiru but it can definetly play around ash or maxx c thanks to humongous amount of drawing cards and card destruction. dont be afraid to throw greed quasar and calculator to the graveyard so you can recycle them. Dark allure targets are mostly level 3 danger monsters if not level 4 danger monsters.

I couldnt make it more consistent cause i feel like i always draw too much and fall short on special summons or maybe summon incorrectly so i cannot end on calculator all the time. I am open to suggestions since its hard to pull up. the deck is a going 2nd deck obviously since you OTK with 100k/300k hit if you are fast enough.

Just a casual deck. Here is how to play:

- Draw with Treasure Panda and Saryuja until you get combo pieces.

- Combo-I: The True Sun God >>> Ancient Chant >>> Have Ra in hand.

- Combo-II: Tribute Summon Ra to reduce HP >>> A Feather of Phoenix >>> Put Spell/Monster card on top of deck.

- Combo-III: Set Fuhma Shuriken >>> Play Reversal Quiz >>> Choose correct answer! >>> KO!!!

 

Here are some budget tips if you want to save SR or UR:

- "Allure of Darkness" and "Into the Void" cards can be unlocked through "Infinite the Void" Secret Pack to save 120 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" isn't really needed and so is "Stardust Charge Warrior", if you are low on SR. Saryuja and other Link monsters can pick targets to refill GY for "Pot of Avarice" more than enough. 90 SR saved!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contact Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "The True Sun God" is just a filler that tutors "Ancient Chant". Thus, 30 UR is saved!

- "Link Spider", "Link Bound" and LAN are given for free, if you've picked "Link Generation". Thus, 90 SR is saved!

- "Reversal Quiz" can be found from "Legacy Pack". Hope you were lucky to get one for free to save 30 SR.

- "Moray of Greed" can be a good and cheap alternative for drawing cards. Just remove 3xExodia+Flamvell to add 4xWater monsters alongside Moray and you're good to go.

 

So, in total, you can save up to 540 SR and 30 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this deck. Thanks for reading, feel free to ask anything. Have fun in Master Duel!
Banish Maju

Anime Deck based on Yugi's Duelist Kingdom Deck. Contains all cards that Yugi used in the anime in that season.

Duelist Kingdom has different rules than the current ones (those would only take place in Battle City).

This deck also contains cards like "Block Attack" and "Stop Defense" because they honestly sound like really good cards for rules like this (with no direct attacks and only 2000 LP) and were part of some of his decks.

The side deck contains both Ritual Monsters needed for his Ritual Spells (in-deck) and "Dark Sage" because, at this point, the rules for this mechanic weren't really specified (so I went with Forbidden Memories and Old School Yugioh Games rules) and Dark Sage could really be a Side Deck option against Joey (really oddly specific that they had this, that was a lot crap lol). As well as some other cards Yugi used.

"Time Wizard" and the Exodia pieces were throwaway cards (especially, Exodia), but Yugi definitely had them with him at the start.

Born out of an idea to use Despian Quaeritis effect which changes the attack of monsters on the field except lvl 8 or higher fusions to 0. Why go through that trouble of making Quaeritis just for this effect?...well thats where the reptiliannes come in.

Reptilianne Echidna  can add reptile monsters from the deck up to the number of monsters on the opponent's field to zero. Reptilianne Vaskii can tribute summon off the opponent's monsters with 0 attack.

Also adding the alien monsters from the deck like Alien Overlord , assuming you have "A" counters on the field, could help you extend into Cosmic Slicer Zer'oll  for locking your opponent's monsters from activating their effects if they have "A" counters. 

This deck is great for going second and although you could be locked into only special summoning either reptiles or fusion mosters. With the main win conditions around the branded / despian fusions or the alien/ reptiliannes, i believe this deck has potential.

Huge shout-out to th3realone for inspiring me to play reptiles and i must add also that this is a theory-based deck that has only been tested in Dueling Nexus (https://duelingnexus.com/). I also understand that there could be much better cards or ideas surrounding this playstyle and i would appreciate it greatly if those ideas and play experiences with the deck could be shared in the comments. Thank you.

deck_name: Official TCG Dark Magician Structure Deck: Vortex of Magic
deck_excerpt: You must Fusion and/or Ritual Summon your way to victory by using card's named "Dark Magician" or "Dark Magician" monsters.
deck_description:
The deck focuses on Fusion and Ritual Summoning at the same time with a "Impcantation" engine for Ritual Summoning faster, basically 1 card combo for bringing out "Magician of Chaos" or "Illusion of Chaos" while searching for Ritual Spells and Ritual Monsters. The ace monster(s) of this deck are "The Dark Magicians" for draw power, "Magician of Chaos" for disruption, and/or "Dark Magician the Dragon Knight" for an unbreakable board with having "Eternal Soul" on your field. The goal is to bring out "Magician of Chaos" while you setup the "Dragon Knight boardlock" also having "Dragon Knight" on your field. This deck focuses on different card type monsters named "Dark Magician", which are:

1. Dark Magician the Dragon Knight (Fusion): You can combo this card with Timaeus, Circle, Salvation, Combination, Chaos Form, Eternal, Piercing, Secrets of DM, and Souls. 

2. Magician of Chaos (Ritual): You can combo this card with Timaeus, Circle, Salvation, Combination, Eternal, Piercing, Ritual Art, Chaos Form, Preparation, Wonder Wand, Impcantations, Secrets of DM, Rod, and Souls.

3. Magician of Dark Illusion (Effect): You can combo this card with Timaeus, Eternal, Salvation, Combination, Circle, Chaos Form, Wonder Wand, Dark Magician, Rod, and Secrets of DM.

4. Dark Magician (Normal): You can combo this card with Timaeus, Eternal, Circle, Salvation, Combination, Chaos Form, Secrets of DM, Piercing, Rod, Souls, Chaos Ritual Monsters, Ritual Art, Wonder Wand, Dark Magician Girl, Dragon Knight Fusion Monsters, and Dark Illusion.

I will show a picture of the final endboard and I will go over step tutorials if needed and/or wanted. This deck is made to go first and/or second, but mainly second. This deck was originally created by the OCG Structures Manga creators and its really good. This deck can do a lot. Thats for sure. Always try to start your combos off with "The Dark Magicians" to get access to whatever combos you need to pull off. Next stop: Gaia's Spiral Spear Strike! DM best deck, lets go! Salute to Konami!

The "C" in "C" Deck stands for "Chaos," as this deck is focused on swarming the field with powerful "Evilswarm" monsters that can quickly overwhelm the opponent. The deck uses the "Rescue Rabbit" card to easily summon two Level 4 monsters, which can then be used to Xyz Summon powerful monsters like "Evilswarm Ophion" and "Evilswarm Bahamut." These Xyz monsters have powerful effects that can shut down the opponent's plays, like preventing them from Special Summoning or negating their monster effects.

The deck also includes several defensive trap cards like "Fiendish Chain" and "Bottomless Trap Hole" to stop the opponent's plays, while "Infestation Pandemic" protects your own monsters from card effects. "Mystical Space Typhoon" helps to get rid of any pesky Spell and Trap cards your opponent might have.

Overall, the "C" Deck is a fast and aggressive deck that can quickly swarm the field with powerful monsters and shut down the opponent's plays with its powerful Xyz monsters and defensive trap cards.

It also has synergy with "Red Resonator" which can grant you access to "Muddy Dragon" so you can summon "Dark Magician the Knight of Dragon Magic" to further your OTK during battle damage. This deck is similar and also mirrors the same ratio that was used for "Vortex of Magic":

2 Gaia = 2 Dark Magician

2 Lightpulsar = 2 Impcan

1 Darkness Metal = 1 Candoll

2 Soldier Gaia = 2 Dark Illusion

2 BLS - Envoy of the Beginning = 2 Magician of Chaos

1 Lord Gaia = 1 Dark Magician Girl (or Mahad if you dont play her but you need her for both Combination and Salvation so dont use him)

3 Magical Knight = 3 Magicians' Souls

3 Cursed Dragon = 3 Rod

1 Dragonfire = 1 Timaeus

3 Artillery Catapult = 3 Illusion of Chaos

3/2 Red Resonator = 3/2 Preparation of Rites

1/2 Keeper = 1/2 PRE-Preparation of Rites or Fusion Recovery (for a fusion engine, also 2 Keeper and 2 Resonators was also optional for any type of balance, if you didnt like 3 Resonator and 1 Keeper)

2 Seven Stars = 2 Spellbook of Knowledge, Wonder Wand, or Allure of Darkness

1 Spiral Spear Strike = 1 Piercing the Darkness

3 Spiral Fusion = 3 Secrets of Dark Magic

2 Heaven and the Earth = 2 Dark Magical Circle

3 Galloping Gaia = 3 Soul Servant

2 Gateway = 2 Salvation

1 Dragon's Mirror = Chaos Form, Polymerization, or Magicalized (if you drop the Ritual engine and add in some Fusion engines)

1 Reborn = 1 Eternal

1 Discharge = 1 Combination

 

Other than that, this deck is fun and very decent to play with and/or against. Enjoy!

deck_name: G Golem Vanilla Link Climb Deck
deck_excerpt: Protect your heart and climb the Links with this cheap, solid, and fun G Golem deck!
deck_description:
I love the G Golem cards, but their restriction to only EARTH-Attribute materials makes them difficult to run in a normal Cyberse link-climb deck. This deck fixes that while also being cheap and easy to build. It doesn't have a TON of combo lines, but it's fun to play and makes them at least playable in a casual, or possibly even semi-competitive setting.

So your main play-starters are going to be Unexpected Dai, Pebble Dog, Rock Hammer, or Widget Kid.

Use Unexpected Dai to summon out one of your vanilla Cyberses, link it off into Link Spider, use Link Spider's effect to summon out another Vanilla from your hand (if you have one), and link those off into Stubborn Mehnir. Then you just need one more material on the field (you haven't even used up your Normal Summon at this point, but make sure your last material is a Cyberse monster. Ash Blossom won't link into anything) and you can link Mehnir with your other material to summon Crystal Heart. Use Crystal Heart's effect to revive Mehnir and trigger its effect to special summon and effect monster from your GY (you should have at least one, unless you only drew vanilla monsters and no searchers) and link off Mehnir and the revived monster to summon Transcode Talker (which is why you need an effect monster) and use its effect to revive Mehnir. If you have another way to get a monster on the board (which isn't difficult with this deck, I find that I have a way to do so more often than not) then you can link off Mehnir with your last material(s) to summon Invalid Dolmen or Dignified Trilithon. If you don't have another material, you can link off Transcode and Mehnir to make Dolmen, which renders both Crystal Heart and Dolmen immune to your opponent's monster effects.

This is your main combo line, but there are a ton of different variations to make it work. Rock Hammer's effect can send Dotscaper to the graveyard to Normal Summon itself and turns into minimum 4 materials on its own, 6 if you have a vanilla monster in hand (Link Spider into Mehnir into Crystal Heart). Pebble Dog and Painful Decision both give you easy ways to get Gravity Balance to come online, Widget Kid gives you 2 materials for free, Bitrooper can also discard Dotscaper or Pebble Dog to get an additional material or a search for Gravity Balance or Rock Hammer.

This isn't a highly meta deck, the best board I've been able to end on with this deck is Crystal Heart, Transcode Talker, and Dignified Trilithon, which isn't incredible, but it gives you a targeted-effect negate and two beefy monsters, and can turn into a solid OTK strategy due to Crystal Heart turning Transcode into a 3400 beater with piercing damage that can attack twice, allowing Dolmen or Trilithon to swing for game.

As far as Accesscode goes, you don't really need Accesscode. It's good to have, since the highest attack you can get with any consisitency is 3700, making certain decks really difficult to get over, so if you arrive at your end board and find that your opponent still has something you can't attack over, Accesscode gives you an option to pop it. You get two pops since you'll have an EARTH and a WATER in your GY, but at most you'll have 3 pops if you've used Ash Blossom that game, and without Update Jammer Accesscode isn't an OTK on its own.

Overall, the deck is fun, effective, and cheap, and the most effective way I've found to play the G Golem engine. It's kind've like an "Accesscode-At-Home" kinda deck, but I enjoy it and I hope you will, too!
Something like this

These are some of the basic interactions you can have within this deck:

- The usual target for Metaphys Daedalus' effect to banish one card from the deck is Metaphys Nephthys.
- Metaphys Nephthys is the best searcher for this deck and is not hard once per turn. The best interaction you can have with this card is to add Metaphys Ascension while you have Asymmetaphys. Use Asymmetaphys' effect to banish Metaphys Ascension drawing one card and adding 1 Metaphys card from your deck to your hand.
- Metaphys Daedalus & Metaphys Nephthys are a great duo when it comes to triggering both their effects when special summoned by the effect of a Metaphys monster. First, you add either one of them to your hand through Metaphys Nephthys, then you banish Metaphys Tyrant Dragon using Metaphys Daedalus' effect. On the next turn, Metaphys Tyrant Dragon special summons either Daedalus or Nephthys for a board wipe (special summoned monsters or set spell & trap cards).
- Aloof Lupine facilitates the access to certain interactions and the best one of all if you open it with Necroface. That's 10 cards banished. You can also use Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring as a bridge to Necroface since both of them are a zombie.

In the current meta, please drop the Nemeses cards for the best one: Nemeses Keystone. Regarding the extra deck, you can adjust it with the best cards in the current meta like Baronne De Fleur and Underworld Goddess of the Closed World.

For Link Evolution players, I'm running a new mod with Requiem created by BritishPiper that added 500 new cards. The mod works on the original, cracked or modded version of the game. The mod adds cards like Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon, Accesscode Talker, Eldlich, Adamancipator, Plunder Patrol and more. Check the Description of this video on YouTube for more info.

deck_excerpt: Dinomorphia, Doodle Beast, Tyranno, Dinos, Dinosaur, Dinosaurs,
deck_description:
• This is a really fun/competitive (and surpisingly consistent) 60 card Dinosaur deck that revolves around Dinomorphia, with some added support from Doodle Beasts/Tyranno/Link monsters/etc
  • This is a First turn deck (though you can manage on turn 2)
  • Dinomorphia works REALLY WELL with some of the other staple Dinosaurs:
    • Using Miscellaneousaurus' GY effect to summon Babysarasaurs and Special summon Therizia at the End of turn (Babysarasaurus gets destroyed by Misc's effect, triggering it's effect), allowing you to set a Dinomorphia trap.
    • Ultimate Tyranno is almost always summonable on your second turn
      • In most cases, you get Kentregina/Rexterm on the field on your opponents turn via Dinomorphia Frenzy or Domain, which sends 2-4 dinosaur monsters to the GY. U. Tyranno only needs 2 in the GY to be summoned
    • Can search/Special summon Dino's w/ Oviraptor, Fossil Dig (Spell), Babysarasaurus, Petiteranodon, etc.
  • This also works really well with the Doodle Beast package:
    • Stego (searcher)
      • Can be special summon on your turn (with no cards or with a dino on the field, which is almost always the case)
      • Can search Doodlebook - Uh uh uh (Trap) when special summoned
        • Attack negate & a Doodle Beast special summon
        • Can banish from GY (on any turn this card was not activated) to add a lvl 5 or higher Dino to your hand from the deck
    • Tyranno (Monster whipe)
      • Can be Tribute summoned by tributing 1 dino monster
      • Can destroy an opponent's monster after it's tribute summoned
      • If a Doodle Beast monster was tributed (Stego) you gain half of that destroyed monster's attack (permanent boost)
  • Added Link package
    • Dinos can get a good amount of cards on the field without triggering any summon locks
      • the only real summon lock is Dinomorphia Alert 
    • Getting 2 dinos on the field w/ Parallel EXceed in hand can be big
      • Summon I:P, trigger P. Exceed's effect to get 2 of them on the field, go into Update Jammer using the P. Exceeds
      • Can go into Avramax/Underworld Goddess(with one additional monster on your side of the field)/Knightmare Unicorn/or a 2+ negate Apollousa on your opponents turn
        • You'll get a 2 attack Avramax/Underworld Goddess/Knightmare Unicorn that cant be targeted or destroyed by card effects

 

The lines in this deck are really determined by the opening hand. Overall, there is ALOT that can be done in this deck. Enjoy!!

A short description made by ChatGPT about how the deck functions.

The "Abyss Actor" Deck is a Pendulum-based archetype that focuses on controlling the field with its various monsters and Trap Cards. The deck's main monster, "Abyss Actor - Superstar," allows the player to search for any "Abyss Script" Trap Card from the deck, while "Abyss Actor - Leading Lady" and "Abyss Actor - Extras" can help to swarm the field with additional monsters.

The deck's strategy revolves around the use of its Pendulum Scale, which can be set with cards like "Abyss Actor - Sassy Rookie" and "Abyss Actor - Wild Hope," and activated to Pendulum Summon multiple monsters at once. The deck also includes various Spells and Traps, like "Abyss Script - Abyssal Playhouse Fantastic Theater" and "Abyss Actors' Curtain Call," which can help to disrupt the opponent's plays and protect the player's monsters.

The Extra Deck includes various Xyz Monsters, like "Abyss Dweller," "Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir," and "Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon," which can help to control the field and deal damage to the opponent. The inclusion of Link Monsters like "Crystron Halqifibrax" and "Linkuriboh" also allows the player to extend their plays and make it easier to summon their Xyz Monsters.

Overall, the "Abyss Actor" Deck is a fun and versatile deck that can control the field with its various monsters and Trap Cards. The deck's reliance on its Pendulum Scale makes it vulnerable to cards that can disrupt the player's Pendulum Summon, but the inclusion of cards like "Abyss Actors Back Stage" and "Maxx 'C'" can help to mitigate this weakness.

deck_excerpt: If Kashtira can play with something like Dark Magician, then that's how good it is...
deck_description:
I thought I would be making this deck for the fun of it (and to warm myself back up to homebrewing). What I forgot about was that the 250th YCS was going on the week I was recording the video, and the fact that Kashtira has peaked into the metagame. What I also just noticed is that Dark Magician (the archetype) can also work well with the Kashtira cards as an extra step towards XYZ extensions. Even without one or the other, both can hold their own in their own way as I had experimented this week.

 

   For the Dark Magician package, I went with the Dragoon package to feed off of "Eternal Soul" and "Dark Magical Circle". All by milling "Dark Magician" from the deck and Special summoning him next turn with "Eternal Soul" (triggering the effect of "Dark Magical Circle") .I also had the option of adding "Dark Magician The Dragon Knight" to the deck, which is fusion summoned using the spell card "Secrets of Dark Magic". I haven't used this often due to not having a good chance of a "Magician's Rod" nor being able to always play "Timaeus the United Dragon". The XYZ monster, "Ebon Illusion Magician" was used for this deck to special summon "Dark Magician" for Kashtira XYZ extensions.

 

   Kashtira's side of the fence seem pretty rudimentary as always: with "Kashtira Fenrir" and "Kashtira Unicorn" being the centerpieces for search monsters and spells for the archetype; "Kashtira Riseheart" being the miller (and sometimes triggering certain effects of Kashtira spells if banished, such as "Kashtiratheosis"); and Tearlaments/Scareclaw Kashtira being lore pieces that are good for some reason. The XYZ monsters (in my opinion) are what truly make the deck into the siege weapon it was meant to be: from "Dark Armed, The Dragon of Annihilation" and the endless destruction looping (and material feeding for "Kashtira Arise-Heart"), to "Number 89: Diablosis the Mind Hacker" and the Extra Deck cherrypicking with the possible deck destruction on top of it. This alone is what truly proves that regardless of what gets thrown at them (or what ridiculous hybrids Kashtira gets mixed into), they somehow still seem to do just fine. They are just that good at carrying on their own or with another archetype you happen to put them with (within reason).

deck_excerpt: I created a up-to-date version of one of my favourite decks of all time, Generaider Windwitch for the April 2023 Masterduel metagame!
deck_description:
I created a up-to-date version of one of my favourite decks of all time, Generaider Windwitch for the April 2023 Masterduel metagame!

If you want a detailed explanation how to use this deck, click here.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

This deck features incredibly potent anti-meta cards like Dimension Shifter, Macro Cosmos, Imperial Order and True King of Calamities. Generaider Windwitch plays comfortably under these floodgates, while the opponent keels over and dies. If you have access to any of these cards, they generally insta-win you the game since they shut off almost every route of play.

While preferring to go first, this deck can still comfortably go second if forced to, since it features 12 hand traps. It can also play past interruption, since it has multiple methods to start off its gameplay.

I found it funny that almost nobody knows what the heck Generaiders and Windwitches do, and they end up underestimating the deck until it's too late. Before long, your opponent may find themself facing down Harr's omni-negate, Crystal Wing's monster negate, Dimension Shifter's banish, and lethal backrow like Judgment and Imperial Order!

Another bonus about this deck is that it functions nicely under Maxx "C," the undisputed king of Master Duel. This deck doesn't summon much, so the opponent doesn't have much incentive to use Maxx "C." This deck can even function under Summon Limit or Winda!

The only major problem about this deck is that it bricks HARD, since there are 6 "hard" bricks in the deck (5 Generaider bosses + Ice Bell) and 1 "soft" brick (Glass Bell). This weakness is avoided with Pot of Prosperity and Maxx "C" functioning as cards that will get you starters for the deck.

deck_excerpt: control, EvilEye, Evil Eye, Ghostrick, Xyz, Rank 3, Level 3, Rogue, Small Core, Versatile
deck_description:
You like big Towers? Then Evil Eye might be a deck for you. With the two new support cards we also get alot of new utility and raise the ceiling by alot.

The main objective of this deck is to slap a big Evil Eye boss ( Serziel, Watcher of the Evil Eye , Gorgon, Empress of the Evil Eyed or Zerrziel, Ruler of the Evil Eyed ) equipped with an Evil Eye of Selene on the field and reach a gamestate where you can recover 3 level 3 monsters from your GY each turn to access your large rank 3 toolbox. The two new Evil Eye additions from Photon Hypernova allow a rank 3 play for a monster negate and a search for an Evil Eye Spell/Trap card in addition to the old standard Evil Eye setup.

The gameplan should always revolve around getting Evil Eyes Unleashed into play and filling up your GY with Catoblepas, Familiar of the Evil Eye and the new monster Basiltrice, Familiar of the Evil Eye , aswell as Evil Eye of Gorgoneio for the additional search.

A standard turn 1 endboard would usually include a Serziel, Watcher of the Evil Eye , equipped with Evil Eye of Selene , an Evil Eye Retribution , searched by Evil Eye of Gorgoneio  and a Number F0: Utopic Draco Future , with 2 Ghostrick Angel of Mischief as materials. Since there are many ways to get to Evil Eyes Unleashed through the core of the Evil Eye archetype and the only requirement to make a Number F0: Utopic Draco Future is 2 level 3s into Ghostrick Alucard , there is alot of space for non archetype cards, which are very neccesary in the current format.

The deck actually seems pretty stable and beats most other rogue decks. I have a solid winrate against Spright and Despia, I do struggle with the Labyrinth matchups but the deck can even snach a game or two off Kashtira.

Hey there guys,

You aim to go first in every duell!!!

going first: (standard combo)

normal summon parlor-parlor effect- dump tidying- link into strikerdragon-tidying effect in grave-banish to summon parlor back-link into hieratic seal- set backrow-end your turn- opponent does stuff as soon when you see an opening use hieratic seal- tribut-summon nurse from deck-nurse effect-bring back parlor-parlor effect to dump- depending on the gamestate-dump fusion for your next turn-or dump another tidying for setup. 

that was a pretty simple one card combo you can do depending on your hand you can do alot more stuff turn one and ending on I:P / Seal and a small dragonmaid to use I:P with.

when you have hospitality in hand and want to play around handtraps bait it with your normal summon effect most people will ash/imperm that and then youre free to use hospitality.

there are alot of ways to make your first turn i wanna show you another simple but effective combo with dragonmaid chamber and any other small dragonmaid in hand for this example we just take nurse

normal chamber-effect search hospitality-link in striker dragon-use hospitality to special nurse from hand- hospitality effect dump the big dragonmaid- nurse effect-bring back chamber- use chamber and striker for seal-set traps and opponent turn-use seal effect to special parlor from deck-parlor effect-dump a big dragonmaid or fusion-now wait for battlephase and return nurse and parlor to hand-let your traps do the rest-if your big dragonmaid for nurse lives special summon nurse back-nurse effect bring back chamber-chamber effect for tidying-next turn use your fusion and go from there.

as you can probably tell there are alot of ways to play this deck and i really enjoy it so give it a try maybe youre getting hocked like me.

for going second you have moderate value like ash/imperm/superpoly to be honest these day a ash and imperm dont do alot so superpoly is probably your best bet so believe and just draw it^^. 

For second game the siding if you win you will probably go second so keep the imperm in the deck cause you can use it from hand maybe side in more handtraps when youre comfortable with it like evently or lightning storm.

If you lose or for some reason youre sure that youre going first side out that imperm for the draco utopian aura and maybe side in your second fusion when the opponent can banish your first if not there is no need to cause you can recycle the fusion endlessly.  

And for those who are asking why i dont play bystials the answer is simple, i dont like them enough to play them i like a pure deck for sure you can use bystials in this deck and they will do some work but mostly i found it hindering having bystials more then control traps to use.

deck_excerpt: Galaxy, Galaxy-Eyes, Photon, Kite Tenjo, OTK
deck_description:
Setup

Searchers

Pretty simple, all good decks have it, and thats why they also have Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. Try not to get negated using these effects to add your desired cards from the Deck to your hand.

Galaxy Soldier can add any "Galaxy" card to your hand when Special Summoned.

Galaxy Wizard can add any "Galaxy" card to your hand by tributing itself. A shame, really.

Photon Orbital can add any "Photon" or "Galaxy" card to your hand if it can attach and detach itself from a monster on the field.

Photon Vanisher can add a "Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon" to your hand with its ability once played.

Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord can add any "Photon" or "Galaxy" card to your hand on your opponent's turn.

Reinforcement of the Army can add either "Photon Vanisher" or "Photon Advancer" to your hand.

The Melody of Awakening Dragon can add "Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon" and "Galaxy-Eyes Afterglow Dragon" to your hand.

Photon Change can add any "Photon" card to your hand.

Photon Timestop can add any "Photon" or "Galaxy" Continuous Spell to your hand.

Level 8's

Your Extra Deck is comprised of many XYZ Monsters who are hungry for Level 8 monsters. Let's get them on the field. 

Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon is your main meal, and as such, there are quite a few ways to get him out. They are described in the next section.

Photon Emperor can be discarded using Galaxy Hundred, Galaxy Soldier, Trade-In, Photon Change, and some Extra Deck monsters. He Special Summons himself to the board if this happens. He can be reused as when he is detached as material, he is Special Summoned as well. 

Galaxy Brave is a free Level 8 Special Summon as long as you have another Level 8 monster in your hand. With the amount of searchers available, you always should before your combo starts. 

Galaxy Knight can be Normal Summoned to the field if you have a Galaxy or Photon card is already there. While he takes up a vailuable normal summon, he can special summon Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon from the GY, netting two Level 8 material if played well. 

Galaxy Wizard is a Level 4 monster who can use its ability to become a level 8. Again, this takes a valuable Normal Summon.

Galaxy-Eyes Afterglow Dragon can be special summoned onto the field if you already control a "Galaxy-Eyes" monster. This works well if you are already well-developed, but most of the time is summoned after Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon is summoned, or for a quick summon, you can play Galaxy-Eyes Solflare Dragon from your Photon Tokens from Photon Sanctuary. This card is highly valuable due to it's usage in the OTK (detailed in a later section)

Galaxy Photon Dragon (the XYZ monster) can turn any Special Summoned Light monster to Level 8 (or 4) until the end of the turn, though you probably won't benefit off this effect until your next turn.

Finally, your arsenal of spells help you get out Level 8's as well. Galaxy Expedition, Galaxy Trance, and Galaxy Zero are spells that can be played for some easy 8's, though they each have their own conditions to be met first. 

The Dragon

Photon Vanisher is your best friend here. Normal or Special Summon out anything you can, then Special Summon him out on the field, allowing you to activate his effect and get a Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon in your hand. If you can, try XYZ summoning Starliege Photon Blast Dragon and Special Summoning Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon from your hand, who is now protected from Target Effects.

Otherwise, two Level 4 monsters can XYZ summon Starliege Lord Galaxion, who can Special summon Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon from your deck or hand.

If your effect chaining is brutally negated, you can Special Summon Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon by tributing two monsters with 2000 or more ATK-- something all your photon cards should have except Photon Orbital. 

Galaxy Knight, Galaxy Summoner, Bujinki Ahashima, Galaxy Trance, and Galaxy Zero are all cards that can special summon your dragon out from the Graveyard. There are many discard effect cards as well, in order to trash the dragon from your hand to the GY for a nice effect. Dont worry, he's coming back to the field.

Your "Galaxy" Spell Cards and Photon Change are also there to help you summon your precious Photon Dragon. 

Playing It Safe

Galaxy monsters have a few nice negates. Try taking the first turn to disrupt your opponent, though sometimes the second-turn OTK is a better choice. Despite the choice, here are card that can save your life.

Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord is a searcher and negate card worth an investment. 

Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy negates and eats all spell cards your opponent activates. He also can detach a material to change attack targets to him. His defense isn't that high, so try attaching a Photon Orbital to him to prevent him from being destroyed.

Starliege Photon Blast Dragon is here to protect the rest of your Boss Monsters, making them untargetable and indestructable from effects.

Galaxy-Eyes Solflare Dragon is a cheap card that can pop an opponent's Special Summoned monster on their turn if you can pay the discard price.

Constellar Belt is a Spell that prevents your Light monster effects from being negated. I'm confused why it doesn't see much play-- I guess people don't like continuous spells that much.

Tachyon Transmigration is a Negate trap that negates all your opponent's effects in the chain. It only works if you control a "Galaxy-Eyes" Monster.

Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir is a well-known staller and negate. Use him if you wanted to go second but was forced first. This could force your opponent to end on a bad board-- ripe for the OTK.

The OTK

Use your huge amount of searchers to get Galaxy-Eyes Afterglow Dragon into your hand and any Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon summoned on the field. Use these two to land the OTK, XYZ summoning Number 62: Galaxy-Eyes Prime Photon Dragon and detaching Galaxy-Eyes Afterglow Dragon after attacking to hit with a hefty 11600 ATK (4000 +XYZs total rank x200 x2) minimum! Make sure you have at least one Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon in your deck before attacking or this wont work.

The non-simorgh variant I have been testing the past week, also probably the list I will be taking to the WCQ at the end of the month. Have been having a lot of success with it, especially against Naturia/Runick, not much practice against Kashtira but it should do relatively well, I'll update this next week after some more practice. In the main deck, I simply replaced the Simorgh package with 2 Harpie Harpist, a Terraforming, and a Feather Duster, and I replaced my 3 Book of Eclipse for 3 Book of Moon because I feel like you mostly only need to book 1 card, and this one can't be ashed.

I also changed the side deck a little from the Simorgh variant, I felt like Advent was not enough to play for time, as it can only be used if you start, which won't always be the case game 3 so I added Dogwood. I also think Dark Hole is a good card to have in this meta, and I found D Barrier redundant with Feather Storm already in the side, so I simply added a trap trick to use as a 4th copy of Feather Storm. Nibiru is the big "if" in this list... It is basically only useful going 2nd, and only if you have it in your opening hand, but it helps play against Kashtira if they try the full combo.

deck_excerpt: Labrynth and eldlich! Traps and control.
deck_description:

Will have to change a few of the floodgates in a few days once Skill Drain is limited to 1 copy.

deck_name: The Dark Magicians' Lock aka the new Yata Lock (Rogue/Anti-Meta Entry)
deck_excerpt: My trade: I draw 2 cards on your turn and on my turn. Your trade: Your locked out of card effects when I activate mine.
deck_description:
This is the broken new Dark Magician Lock. The Dark Magicians can easily abuse Powersink to draw cards on your opponents while your opponent is locked out of monster effects before the Main Phase starts. Lmfao The Dark Magicians are super OP more than Dragon Knight and Dragoon. Damn! 🤣🤣🤣😭😭😭😆😆😆😆

If you have 2 The Dark Magicians, Secret Village, and Powersink all on the field on your opponents turn, its game over. Lmfao. Even worst, Souls can act as another draw engine to draw into your Exodia pieces. This is insanely good! DM players shouldve thought of this idea already lmfao. Its the new Mystic Mine but better than Mystic Mine. I guess you could call this deck the new Yata Lock. 

Edit: Decklist is an idea for which cards to use to play against meta. The actual decklist is forbyou to figure out alone.

Meta decks cannot get over this deck until its with generic handtraps and it would have to depend because the handtrap thing wouldnt even matter at this point. Evenly Match could stop this deck but I doubt it. Lmfao. You could setup another Trap negate so it wouldnt matter. Just beaten Kashtiras again with this deck. 

Will show example in the comments! Thanks!

deck_name: Unbreakable Board One Card Combo Deck
deck_excerpt: The combo you need to know.
deck_description:
Things you need to know about the deck:

- Drop the second copy of Destrudo. I made an assumption that was wrong. The card can be played from HAND and GY. I must be tripping -.-
- Since there is no way to put Rescue Ferret back in the deck, I added a second copy to mitigate the chance of opening it in starting hand.
- During the combo, we summon Power Tool Dragon twice to add two specific cards: The first is D.D.R. - Different Dimension Reincarnation and the second is Telekinetic Charging Cell. That's why, we run three copies of each card to get them 100%. 
- You have 3 cards in this deck you need to send to the GY: Blackwing - Zephyros the Elite, Summoner Monk and Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade. You can discard both the monsters when using Reincarnation and Phoenix Blade can be simply equiped to 1 monster before linking Isolde.
- If you open Cyber-Stein, Blackwing - Steam the Cloak and/or World Legacy - "World Key", don't worry since you can put them back into the deck using Saryuja Skull Dread.
- When you summon The Last Warrior from Another Planet, you need to negate its effect with Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon and then during the SAME CHAIN, activate Dusktopia's effect targeting The Last Warrior to protect it from Destruction.

For Link Evolution players, I'm running a new mod with Requiem created by BritishPiper that added 500 new cards. The mod works on the original, cracked or modded version of the game. The mod adds cards like Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon, Accesscode Talker, Eldlich, Adamancipator, Plunder Patrol and more. Check the Description of this video on YouTube for more info.

Scroll down for the full combo. Enjoy. Peace.

deck_excerpt: Meta, Branded, Bystial, Fallen of Albaz, Lore, Fusion, Despia,
deck_description: This deck is the best possible branded deck after Cyberstorm Access. The main line is Bystial Lubellion, send saronir to get branded in white. Pretty much every hand ends in 5 interruptions whether it's mirrorjade or not. This deck has no problems playing through Ash. You don't main hand traps because the deck can easily build a strong board with 6 negates.

deck_excerpt: Master Duel, Meta, Tearlaments, Ishizu, Mill,
deck_description: This is one of the best ways to ruin Master duel now that Tearlaments run around.It's basically just Ishizu Tearlaments with added Handtraps and cards that search the field spell now that it is at 1. You run 1 Swamp King just so that you can still go even if kitkallos gets banished. Then if that isn't enough you run 1 nemese to return the ishizu shufflers to deck or to return Kitkallos. You can also run nemese flag and it can be better in some instances but i choose to run umbrella so to it being an aqua water so you can use it for Fusions.
